Fancytree - Examples

Fancytree is a JavaScript tree view / tree grid plugin with support for keyboard, inline editing, filtering, checkboxes, drag'n'drop, and lazy loading.

This site presents some live examples for Fancytree.

Select a topic on the navigator to the left and click 'View source code' at the bottom of the sample frame for details.

More documentation and infos can be found at the Documentation Wiki.

Have fun :-)

印度土邦 States before 1947

土邦王公称为马哈罗阁（Maharaja）或罗（Raja）的，一般是起源于印度教或锡克教的封建主；称为纳瓦布（Nawab）的，原是莫卧儿帝国中央政府派驻帝国较大省份的总督。称为尼扎姆（Nizam）的，原是中央政府封派的省级官员（后来成为掌握省的实权的最高长官）。纳瓦布和尼扎姆均为穆斯林。

马里 Mali

6 Sep 1880 French territory of Upper Senegal (Haut-Sénégal)

created (subordinated to French West Africa

[see Senegal]).

18 Aug 1890 Renamed territory of French Sudan (Soudan Français)

27 Aug 1892 Made a separate colony.

16 Jun 1895 Part of French West Africa (see Senegal).

17 Oct 1899 French Sudan broken up; part becomes territory

of Upper Senegal and Middle Niger (Haut-Sénégal

et Moyen-Niger).

10 Oct 1902 Becomes colony of Senegambia and Niger (Sénégambie

et le Niger)(subject to Senegal).

18 Oct 1904 Renamed Upper Senegal and Niger (Haut-Sénégal-Niger).

4 Dec 1920 Renamed French Sudan (Soudan Français).

16 Jun 1940 - 23 Nov 1942 Administration loyal to Vichy France (from 23 Nov

1942 [under Darlan to 24 Dec 1942], Free French).

27 Oct 1946 French Sudan overseas territory of France.

24 Nov 1958 Autonomy (Sudanese Republic [République Soudanaise])

24 Nov 1958 - 22 Sep 1960 Member state of the Communauté (French Community).

4 Apr 1959 - 22 Sep 1960 Part of the Mali Federation (Fédération du Mali)

(with Senegal), a member state of the Communauté.

19 Jun 1960 Mali Federation accedes to independence.

20 Jun 1960 Independence of the Mali Federation is proclaimed

in Dakar.

26 Aug 1960 Senegal withdraws from the Mali Federation.

22 Sep 1960 State is renamed Republic of Mali (République du

Mali) which is proclaimed a sovereign state).

1 Jul 1961 - May 1963 Part of the Union of African States a loose

federation of Ghana, Guinea, and Mali.

1 Apr 2012 - 12 Jul 2012 Tuareg secessionists occupy Kidal, Gao, Timbuktu

on 6 Apr 2012 declare the independence of Azawad.

27 Jun 2012 - 26 Jan 2013 Islamist rebels occupy Kidal, Gao, Timbuktu.

南高加索地区

外高加索特别委员会（1917）

英语：Special Transcaucasian Committee

俄语：Особый Закавказский Комитет

俄国二月革命之后，临时政府废除了原高加索总督区，于1917年3月22日（俄历3月9日）颁布法令，成立外高加索管理特别委员会（Особый комитет для управления Закавказьем (ОЗАКОМ)），以国家杜马成员瓦西里·哈拉莫夫（Vasily Akimovich Kharlamov）为主席，初始成员有马马德·尤素夫·贾法罗夫（Mammad Yusif Jafarov）、米歇尔·帕帕贾尼扬（Michael Papadjanian）、基塔·阿巴希泽（Kita (Ivane) Abashidze）和保罗·佩雷维杰夫（Pavel Nikolaevich Pereverzev）。随即孟什维克施压，阿卡基·钦克利（Akaki Chkhenkeli）取代了佩雷维杰夫。4月12日（俄历3月30日），这个机构正式更名为外高加索特别委员会，直属于临时政府。这个机构包括高加索地区国家杜马代表和其他地方领袖，旨在采用“集体总督制”领导，地方各民族都有代表。同时，临时政府允许了双重政权体制，允许各地设立苏维埃。

十月革命后，消息次日传到高加索，梯弗里斯苏维埃首先开会后宣布反对布尔什维克。外高加索特别委员会于11月24日（俄历11月11日）召开会议，决定不承认苏俄政权。梯弗里斯苏维埃、外高加索特别委员会与其他团体各派代表磋商决定撤销外高加索特别委员会，新设与布尔什维克没有任何从属关系的外高加索委员部。28日（俄历15日）委员部正式成立，外高加索特别委员会宣布结束。

外高加索委员部（1917-1918）

英语：Transcaucasian Commissariat

俄语：Закавказский комиссариат

外高加索委员部1917年11月28日（俄历11月15日）宣告成立，委员长为叶甫盖尼·盖盖奇科里（Evgeni Gegechkori），委员部由外高加索四大民族（亚美尼亚人、阿塞拜疆族、格鲁吉亚人、俄罗斯人）代表组成，取代特别委员会的南高加索政府地位。委员部反对十月革命，并计划行使职权直至1918年1月俄国立宪会议召开。1918年1月18日（俄历1月5日），全俄立宪会议召开，但是仅仅半天就被布尔什维克政权强制解散。

此前，外高加索委员部无意独立于俄罗斯行事，因此在奥斯曼与苏俄进行布列斯特谈判时，尽管奥斯曼外交官邀请委员部参加，委员部没有答复邀请。在立宪会议被解散后，奥斯曼帝国再度挥军攻入高加索，由于俄军基本撤离前线，委员部无力抵御奥斯曼帝国的全面推进，于是在2月23日同意和谈。

与此同时，由于立宪会议被解散，委员部领导人同意自组议会建立合法政府，以更合适的身份与奥斯曼帝国谈判，外高加索委员部决定召集外高加索议会（Transcaucasian Sejm）。议会于2月23日在梯弗里斯创建议会，格鲁吉亚孟什维克尼古拉·齐赫泽推（Nikolay Chkheidze）为主席

从委员部开始，外高加索政权的治理能力就先天不足，非常依赖几乎同时成立、基本按民族立场泾渭分明的民族委员会。新成立的议会中，代表三大民族的三大政党代表也是最多，分别是格鲁吉亚孟什维克（Georgian Menshevik），阿塞拜疆穆萨瓦特党（Müsavat Party）和亚美尼亚革命联盟（Armenian Revolutionary Federation，Dashnaktsutyun）。议会依然非常依赖三大民族团体组成的民族委员会，只能在其支持下运作，民族和政治成分复杂、权威地位不明导致内外冲突不断。

外高加索议会代表团3月8日抵达特拉布宗（Trabzon），准备和奥斯曼帝国的谈判。代表团等待和谈启动期间，奥斯曼帝国军队依据和苏俄签订的《布列斯特-立陶夫斯克条约》，在高加索地区继续推进苏俄已同意割让的地区。外高加索议会代表团不承认俄国权威，因此不承认《布列斯特-立陶夫斯克条约》。3月14日和谈开始，首席代表阿卡基·钦克利（Akaki Chkhenkeli）称外高加索十月革命后就没有中央权力机构，当地设立独立政府、讨论是否接受邀请参加布列斯特-里托夫斯克和谈时的做法与独立国家一致，即便尚未明确宣布独立也符合主权国家标准。而奥斯曼首席代表劳夫·奥贝（Rauf Bey）则认为人民委员会拥有俄罗斯全境的权威地位，奥斯曼帝国邀请外高加索委员部参与和谈不代表正式承认外高加索是主权国家。钦克利要求短暂休会，以便联络议会决定如何继续。休会期间，奥斯曼军队继续深入外高加索。、3月20日奥斯曼代表提出，外高加索必须宣布独立、确认不再隶属俄罗斯才能回到谈判桌。钦克利最终让步，4月9日他同意根据《布列斯特-立陶夫斯克条约》进一步谈判，同时要求其他同盟国参与，而劳夫则进一步明确表示外高加索是独立国家才能提这种要求。4月14日外高加索议会向奥斯曼帝国宣战，但军力薄弱，巴统（Batumi）当日失守，巴尔斯（Kars）被围困。4月22日奥斯曼帝国再度提出停火，等待外高加索的答复。面对奥斯曼的军事优势，格鲁吉亚民族委员会认为外高加索除宣布独立外别无选择，因为只有外高加索独立奥斯曼才会恢复和谈。

4月22日当日外高加索议会举行辩论，格鲁吉亚代表提议独立，亚美尼亚革命联盟普遍认为此时最重要的是阻挡奥斯曼军队前进，但他们不愿放弃这么多领土；代表阿塞拜疆族的穆萨瓦特党仍无法下决心对抗穆斯林同胞，但承认确保外高加索不被外来势力瓜分的唯一途径就是独立。辩论结束后，经投票，议会宣布外高加索是独立的民主联邦共和国。新成立的外高加索民主联邦共和国马上把独立的消息告知奥斯曼帝国，表示愿意接受《布列斯特－里托夫斯克条约》并将卡尔斯拱手相让。共和国宣布成立后，外高加索委员部同时解散。

姆甘临时军事独裁政府（1918-1919）

英语：Provisional Military Dictatorship of Mughan

俄语：Временная военная диктатура Мугани

姆甘临时军事独裁政府是一个在连卡兰地区（Lankaran）建立的由英国控制的反共短命国家，1918年8月1日成立。此前1918年4月在巴库苏维埃支持下，连卡兰地区也建立了苏维埃政权（执行委员会），领导人为Григорий Арустамов。巴库苏维埃和巴库公社失败后，里海舰队中央委员会独裁政权在巴库建立，姆甘临时军事独裁政府在连卡兰地区建立。该政府不支持阿塞拜疆独立，由白俄的T·P·苏霍鲁科夫上校领导，在英控巴库时期活动。仿照里海政权建制，姆甘成立五人独裁政权（Диктатура Пяти），组成人员为Ильяшевич， Сухоруков， Кропотов， Саратиков，Шиманов。

9月14日奥斯曼军队占领巴库后，里海政权倒台。姆甘五人政权随之结束，连卡兰地区短暂归属阿塞拜疆控制，但随着11月奥斯曼帝国投降，英军重返巴库，姆甘地方政权（Муганская краевая управа）得以恢复，称姆甘领地管理局”（Mughan Territorial Administration，Территориальное управление Мугани），依然由原五人政权执掌，这回是在忠于白俄政权的军事控制之下，先是Лазарь Фёдорович Бичерахов将军管控之下，之后是Михаи́л Алексе́евич Пржева́льский。该政权宣称其将成为“单一且不可分割的俄罗斯帝国”底下一个自治地区，接受邓尼金指挥。1919年4月25日，一场由亲布尔什维克工人组织的暴力示威在连科兰爆发，推翻了姆甘领地管理局。

【1919年5月2日，在布尔什维克主导下召开会议，决定尽速成立苏维埃政权。5月13日组织了选举， 5月15日连科兰地区工农苏维埃非常大会开幕，Бахрам Джафар оглы Агаев当选会议主席，会议宣布建立穆甘苏维埃共和国。为期四天的会议在5月18日选举了姆甘地区工农苏维埃代表，并选举了执行委员会，Давыд Данилович Чиркин为委员长。

1919年6月30日，白军攻占了察里津，红军被迫放弃了阿斯特拉罕。里海沿岸的布尔什维克势力陷入了最困难时期。7月阿塞拜疆民主共和国倒戈发动对穆甘苏维埃共和国的军事总攻，北线兵力从萨利亚内进攻，部分兵力船运至毗邻伊朗国界的阿斯塔拉，与当地部族武装一起向北进攻。1919年7月23日，阿塞拜疆民主共和国战争部长Samad bey Mehmandarov向连科兰公民发布了敦促投降的公告。7月28日，布尔什维克势力从连科兰撤往萨拉岛（Sarah Island），穆甘苏维埃共和国被灭，该地区被并入阿塞拜疆。】

西南高加索临时民族政府（1918-1919）

英文：Provisional National Government of the Southwestern Caucasus

俄土战争后，1878年3月3日土耳其被迫签订《圣斯特凡诺条约》（Treaty of San Stefano），卡尔斯（今属土耳其）被割让给俄罗斯。1918年3月3日一战末期苏俄政权和奥斯曼签署《布列斯特-立陶夫斯克条约》（Treaty of Brest-Litovsk），穆斯林人口占主导的卡尔斯和巴统（Batum），埃里温省（Yerevan province）的一部分，梯弗里斯省（Tiflis province）的阿哈尔齐赫区（Akhaltsikhe district）和阿哈尔卡拉基区（Akhalkalaki district）都被割让给奥斯曼。据此4月14日奥斯曼进占卡尔斯。在和新成立的亚美尼亚民主共和国爆发一系列冲突后，双方于1918年6月4日签署巴统条约，重申确认了奥斯曼的领土要求。1918年19月30日日奥斯曼与协约国签订穆兹罗斯停战协定（Armistice of Mudros）无条件投降，奥斯曼应撤出所有开战以来占领地区并解除武装。依照协议，撤军应于12月1日完成，然而到12月4日奥斯曼虽然撤至1878年边界，但决定保留卡尔斯多两个月，其实奥斯曼一直在争取时间让当地建立亲土耳其政权，以防止被亚美尼亚吞并。

在此背景下，1918年10月29日麦斯赫特临时政府（Axısqa Müvəqqəti Hökuməti）成立；11月3日阿拉斯土耳其共和国（Araz Türk Cümhuriyyəti）成立，以Əmir bəy Nərimanbəyov为领袖；11月5日，卡尔斯伊斯兰委员会（Qars İslam Şurası）成立，Fəxrəddin bəy Piroğlu为委员会主席。11月14日，第一次卡尔斯大会召开，建立以Fəxrəddin bəy Piroğlu为首的八人临时委员会，以及以Emin ağa Acalovun为首的国家伊斯兰委员会总中心（Milli İslam Şurası Ümumi Mərkəzi）。

1918年11月30日-12月2日，以上三政府在卡尔斯集会，召开第二次卡尔斯大会。全国伊斯兰委员会政府正式成立，İbrahim bəy Cahangirzadə当选政府主席。

外高加索民主联邦共和国（1918）

1918年4月22日，外高加索议会宣布成立外高加索民主联邦共和国，外高加索委员部同时解散。外高加索委员部委员长叶甫盖尼·盖盖奇科里（Evgeni Gegechkori）自认没有足够支持，拒绝继续担任领导人。外高加索议会辩论达成共识由谈判首席代表阿卡基·钦克利（Akaki Chkhenkeli）任总理，但他无意出任临时职务，只愿在新内阁成立后上任。4月26日内阁人选敲定，因此此前三天新共和国都没有行政机构。组阁过程中矛盾已然凸显，亚美尼亚革命联盟对钦克利放弃卡尔斯的做法不满，但格鲁吉亚孟什维克认为选择亚美尼亚人霍夫汉内斯·卡贾兹努尼（Hovhannes Kacharznuni）会令外界认定新共和国打算继续保卫亚美尼亚领土，进而导致阿塞拜疆族退出联邦，最终亚美尼亚革命联盟让步同意钦克利出任总理，而且阿塞拜疆与格鲁吉亚在内阁占领导地位。

5月11日，外高加索和奥斯曼在巴统召开和会，此次奥斯曼代表提出了比《布列斯特－里托夫斯克条约》更多的领土要求，并且只给外高加索民主联邦共和国几天时间考虑。5月21日奥斯曼继续进军，5月22日大军距埃里温只剩40公里，离梯弗里斯也只有120公里。外高加索方面，亚美尼亚族坚持与奥斯曼军队交战，阿塞拜疆族对布尔什维克控制巴库别有打算，格鲁吉亚族认定三族同床异梦，联邦共和国无以为继。5月21日，亚美尼亚、阿塞拜疆、格鲁吉亚三族议会代表会晤后认定继续维持联邦共和国的希望渺茫。格鲁吉亚代表克诺伊·佐达尼亚（Noe Jordania）与祖拉布·阿瓦利什维利（Zurab Avalishvili）起草《格鲁吉亚独立宣言》，5月26日格鲁吉亚孟什维克伊拉克利·策烈铁里（Irakli Tsereteli）在议会发表演说，说明人民缺乏团结和民族分歧导致面对奥斯曼入侵国家无法协调行动，外高加索民主联邦共和国无以为继，并直接指责阿塞拜疆族不支持国防，现在格鲁吉亚应该宣布独立。当日下午动议通过，“外高加索共和国的创立者在战争与和平问题出现根本分歧，已经不可能以整个外高加索的名义建立统一权威，议会证明外高加索确实已经瓦解，因此放弃权力”。议会中的格鲁吉亚代表随后与格鲁吉亚民族委员会委员会合，宣布格鲁吉亚民主共和国独立；5月28日《亚美尼亚独立宣言》与《阿塞拜疆独立宣言》相继公布，分别建立亚美尼亚共和国与阿塞拜疆民主共和国。三个新生独立国家均于6月4日与奥斯曼帝国签署和约，结束战争。亚美尼亚接下来与阿塞拜疆和格鲁吉亚短暂交战，确立最终边界。

亚美尼亚山地共和国（1921）

英语：Republic of Mountainous Armenia

俄语：Республика Горная Армения

亚美尼亚语：Լեռնահայաստանի Հանրապետութիւն

十月革命后，相继独立的亚美尼亚和阿塞拜疆之间存在诸多领土冲突，其中就包括赞格祖尔地区（Zangezur），今亚美尼亚休尼克省（Syunik）。1919年9月起，此地为加列津·恩贾德（Garegin Nzhdeh）实际控制。1920年4月28日，苏俄占领阿塞拜疆民主共和国，成立阿塞拜疆苏维埃社会主义共和国。8月10日，亚美尼亚和苏俄达成协议，允许苏俄派军队进驻赞格祖尔等争议地区。苏俄本意要将赞格祖尔地区并入阿塞拜疆苏维埃社会主义共和国，遭到恩贾德的激烈反对，并引发了对苏俄的起义。到11月21日， 起义军击败了苏俄第十一军，完全控制了这一地区。12月25日，第一届泛-赞格组里安大会（Pan-Zangezurian Congress）在塔特夫修道院（Tatev Monastery）举行，宣布成立休尼克自治共和国（Autonomous Syunik Republic），恩贾德为国家元首。国家成立的本意是反抗苏俄的占领，并伺机加入亚美尼亚共和国（已灭亡）。

同一时期，1920年12月亚美尼亚被苏俄红军占领后，亚美尼亚革命联盟（Armenian Revolutionary Federation）成员持续遭到镇压。在此背景下，亚美尼亚革命联盟于1921年2月13日发动反苏俄的起义，并于18日占领埃里温，成立以前亚美尼亚共和国总理西蒙·弗拉特相（Simon Vratsian）为首的祖国拯救委员会（Salvation Committee of the Fatherland），在组成政府前行使职权。苏俄军队4月2日重新占领埃里温，祖国拯救委员会撤退到加列津·恩贾德控制的赞格祖尔地区。

1921年4月26日，第二届泛-赞格组里安大会在塔特夫召开，会议宣布瓦约茨佐尔（Daralakyaz）、赞格祖尔（Zangezur）与阿尔察赫山区（Mountainous Artsakh）成为独立的自治共和国，名称是亚美尼亚山地共和国（Republic of Mountainous Armenia），加列津·恩贾德被选为总理兼外交和国防部长。

1921年7月1日，亚美尼亚山地共和国更名为亚美尼亚共和国（Republic of Armenia），西蒙·弗拉特相就任总理，同时恩贾德成为州长兼总指挥。此举直接对抗苏俄的亚美尼亚。在苏俄的猛烈进攻下，亚美尼亚山地共和国投降，并换取了苏俄承诺其继续作为亚美尼亚苏维埃共和国的一部分。加列津·恩贾德与他的士兵，于7月9日越过边界进入邻国波斯的大不里士城。

赞格祖尔地区的激烈抵抗使得自己得以保留在苏维埃亚美尼亚，而阿尔察赫地区则在斯大林的直接干预下，于1921年7月5日被并入苏维埃阿塞拜疆（1923年7月7日 成立纳戈尔诺－卡拉巴赫自治州），此即日后旷日持久的纳卡冲突之根源。

亚美尼亚民主共和国（1918-1920）

英语：Democratic Republic of Armenia

俄语：Демократическая Республика Армения

亚美尼亚语：Դեմոկրատական Հայաստանի Հանրապետություն

1912年10月-11月俄罗斯帝国境内亚美尼亚人口占优势的地区在梯弗里斯（今第比利斯）成立亚美尼亚民族局（Armenian National Bureau, Армянское национальное бюро），目的在于促进亚美尼亚地区的团结和敦促帝国对这一地区的改革。第一次世界大战期间，民族局积极组织征兵，帮助俄国对抗奥斯曼帝国。

1917年10月11日（俄历9月28日）俄罗斯帝国境内的亚美尼亚人在梯弗里斯（今第比利斯）召开民族大会（Armenian National Congress），讨论俄国革命形势下亚美尼亚民族的应对之策。大会于10月26日（俄历10月13日）结束。大会选举了35人组成的国民议会（National Assembly）作为俄国境内亚美尼亚人的立法机构，又指定了15人组成的亚美尼亚民族委员会（Armenian National Council），作为执行机构，以Avetis Aharonyan为委员会主席。

1918年5月28日，在组建外高加索民主联邦共和国的尝试失败后，亚美尼亚民族委员会在梯弗里斯宣布自己为亚美尼亚各省的最高和唯一行政机构并暂时承担所有政府职能，成立独立的亚美尼亚共和国。这一宣言在5月30日在埃里温正式发布。

1918年6月7日，Hovhannes Kacharznuni被亚美尼亚民族委员会任命为首任总理，6月30日组成首任内阁；7月19日政府正式从梯弗里斯迁到埃里温。

1918年8月1日，亚美尼亚议会开始运作，亚美尼亚民族委员会结束。

1920年8月10日，同盟国和奥斯曼帝国在法国色佛尔签署色佛尔条约，其中对亚美尼亚的条款规定所有签署该条约的国家承认亚美尼亚为一自由和独立国家，但由于奥斯曼苏丹穆罕默德六世从未签署，因此它实际上从未生效。

1920年9月20日，土耳其声称位于亚美尼亚内的土耳其人被虐待和镇压，军队开入亚美尼亚。9月24日亚美尼亚对土耳其宣战，土亚战争爆发。11月18日双方达成停火，但此时亚美尼亚全境已有三分之二被土耳其占领。与此同时，1920年11月29日苏俄第十一军开始入侵亚美尼亚。亚美尼亚领导人意识到无法抵抗两大强国，12月2日在埃里温屈服苏俄的最后通缉，决定加入苏俄，而苏俄则答应帮助它抵挡土耳其军队保护其疆域。仍在与土耳其进行和谈的亚美尼亚共和国政府12月2日-3日夜间签署了亚历山德罗波尔条约（Treaty of Alexandropol）作为和平条约，但此条约从法理上是无效的，因为共和国政府已不复存在。1920年12月4日红军开进埃里温， 12月6日费利克斯·埃德蒙多维奇·捷尔任斯基的秘密警察契卡入城，亚美尼亚民主共和国实际上停止存在。苏俄和土耳其大国民议会于1921年3月16日签订的莫斯科条约与其相关的卡尔斯条约（1921年10月13日）基本确保土耳其获得了在土亚战争中获得的土地，也确立了现代亚美尼亚和土耳其之间的边界。

里海舰队中央委员会独裁政权
阿塞拜疆民主共和国（1918-1920）

俄国二月革命后，阿塞拜疆族人也积极寻求民族自治，拥有一定阿族人口的地区纷纷成立穆斯林民族委员会（Muslim National Councils）。1917年3月27日，穆斯林委员会临时执行委员会（Temporary Executive Committee for the MNCs）成立，马马德·哈桑·哈金斯基（Mammad Hasan Hajinski）为委员会主席。十月革命后，阿族积极参与了外高加索的一系列独立活动。在1918年2月成立的外高加索议会中，阿族人数最多。

1918年5月26日，外高加索民主联邦共和国解体，27日外高加索议会中的阿塞拜疆人组成了阿塞拜疆国民大会（Azerbaijani National Council），Memmed Resulzade当选国民大会主席，Fath Ali Khan Khoiski当选执行委员会主席。5月28日宣布阿塞拜疆民主共和国独立，Khoiski成为部长会议主席，并组成了政府。

1918年6月4日，阿塞拜疆民主共和国与奥斯曼土耳其签订了巴统条约。1918年6月16日，阿塞拜疆国民大会移驻占贾（Ganja），宣布甘贾为临时首都，并依靠土耳其力量攻打巴库（时在布尔什维克巴库苏维埃和巴库公社控制之下）。由于阿塞拜疆极端民族主义者指责国民大会的左倾色彩，奥斯曼土耳其军队指挥官于6月17日解散了国民大会，权力由部长会议主席Fath Ali Khan Khoiski接掌。

【在奥斯曼军事压力下，巴库苏维埃决定向英国派遣军求援，尽管有布尔什维克的激烈反对，社会革命党人、孟什维克、达什纳克在7月25日以多数通过决议，请求英军入驻巴库。7月31日，邵武勉退出巴库苏维埃并率布尔什维克离开巴库，同日Lionel Dunsterville将军率领英国军队进占巴库，8月1日成立里海舰队中央委员会独裁政权。】

1918年9月14日，奥斯曼军队占领巴库，阿塞拜疆民主共和国政府也于9月17日迁入巴库。10月30日奥斯曼与协约国签订穆兹罗斯停战协定（Armistice of Mudros），事实上无条件投降，退出一战。据此，奥斯曼军队要退出包括巴库和巴统在内的整个高加索地区。

1918年11月16日，在奥斯曼军队退出后，阿塞拜疆国民大会得以恢复工作。11月17日英军在威廉·汤姆森（William Thomson）率领下进入巴库，并宣布其主要目的为确保奥斯曼土耳其军队及其仆从国阿塞拜疆民主共和国势力退出巴库并建立英国在巴库的地方管理当局。11月19日国民大会决定成立议会。

1918年12月7日，阿塞拜疆民主共和国议会（Parliament）成立，Alimardan bey Topchubashov当选为议长，Hasan bey Aghayev当选为副议长（因Topchubashov出席巴黎和会，Aghayev代理议长至1920年2月2日）。12月26日Khoiski组成新政府，12月28日汤姆森发表声明，承认Khoiski政府为阿塞拜疆唯一合法权力机关。

1920年4月25日，苏俄红军第11集团军越过了阿塞拜疆边界。4月27日，以纳里曼·纳里曼诺夫（Nariman Narimanov）为主席的阿塞拜疆临时革命委员会（Provisional Revolutionary Committee）成立，并向阿塞拜疆民主共和国政府发布最后通牒。4月28日阿塞拜疆民主共和国宣布自行撤销。4月30日，红军第11集团军兵不血刃进驻巴库，随之成立了阿塞拜疆苏维埃社会主义共和国（Azerbaijan SSR）。

比利时 Belgium

1

Belgian Congo (1908-1960)

 比属刚果

 刚果（金沙萨）

In 1876 the King of Belgium, Leopold II, formed the International African Association, interested only in the exploration of Africa. Although designed a multi-national, non-political organization, it was dominated by Leopold from the beginning. The Congress of Berlin in 1885 recognized Belgian sovereignty to the Congo River basin which was claimed by the expeditions authorized by Leopold. The Congo Free State was organized as a result, to be ruled by Leopold himself on a personal basis. Belgium assumed sovereignty and the colony was renamed Belgian Congo. It became independent in 1960 as Republic of Congo.

International Association of the Congo (1879-1885)

 国际刚果协会

 刚果（金沙萨）

Congo Free State (1885-1908)

 刚果自由邦

 刚果（金沙萨）

2

Ruanda-Urundi (1916-1962)

 卢旺达-乌隆迪

今属布隆迪和卢旺达 

The kingdoms of Rwanda and Burundi were part of German East Africa and were administered separately from the rest of the colony. They were occupied by troops from Belgian Congo during World War I and were granted as a mandate to Belgium after the war. Ruanda-Urundi was governed as a part of the Belgian Congo and the governor was also vice governor-general of the Belgian Congo. In 1962 after the Belgian Congo gained independence, Ruanda-Urundi became separately independent as two countries, Rwanda and Burundi.

丹麦 Denmark

Faroe Islands (1380-

法罗群岛

法罗群岛（丹）

The Faroe Islands became a part of the Kingdom of Norway in 1035. Norwegian supremacy continued until 1380 when King Olaf II of Denmark became also king of Norway, and the islands became part of the Kamar Union from 1397. Denmark and Norway kept the union while Sweden quitted in 1523. In 1537 the Danish Privy Council unilaterally declared Norway to be a Danish province, although this did not happen, Faroe Islands, Greenland, and Iceland became de facto directly under Denmark. The Faroe Islands were kept under Denmark after the 1814 Peace of Kiel when Norway the union of Denmark-Norway was dissolved and Norway was ceded to Sweden.

Greenland (1380-

格陵兰岛

格陵兰岛（丹）

The island of Greenland was under Kingdom of Norway suzerainty from 1261, and it followed similar history of Faroe Islands to join Denmark from 1380 and lasted after 1814 Peace of Kiel.

3

Danish Gold Coast (1657-1850)

丹属黄金海岸

今加纳

In 1657 the Danes expelled Sweden from the latter’s posts on the Gold Coast and established themselves in the Swedish fort of Osu near Accra. The post was renamed Christiansborg and it became the headquarter for Danish activities along the Guinea coast. Denmark built or purchased further posts at Keta (Fort Prinzenstein), Teshi (Fort Augustaborg), Ningo (Fort Friedensborg), and Ada (Fort Konigstein) along the coast. Denmark abolished slave trade in 1782, and these posts had little function left. Finally purchased all the Danish forts in 1850, and integrated them into the British colony of the Gold Coast.

4

Danish West Indies (1754-1917)

丹属西印度群岛

今属美属维尔京群岛 

The island of Saint Thomas was settled by the Danish West Indies Company in 1672. The island of neighboring Saint Johns was possessed by the Company in 1684. The island of Saint Croix was purchased in 1733 from the French who held since 1650 but never settled. These three islands comprised the Danish West Indies. From 1734 to 1756 Saint Thomas and Saint Johns were administered as one unit, and Saint Croix a separate unit, except that from 1734 to 1744 a governor-general administered all three islands. In 1755 they were transferred to the crown, and in 1756 the office of governor-general was reinstituted. From 1756 to 1871 the seat of the governor-genral was on Saint Croix and then moved to Saint Thomas. Saint Thomas-Saint Jones retained separate but subordinate administration under Saint Croix, and the post of governor for these two islands was abandoned in 1862. A treaty of sale was concluded with the United States in 1867 but was never ratified by the U.S. Senate. It was until 1917 finally sold to U.S. to be the U.S. Virgin Islands.

Saint Thomas-Saint John (1666-1717)

圣托马斯岛-圣约翰岛

今属美属维尔京群岛

Saint Croix (1734-1754)

圣克罗伊岛

今属美属维尔京群岛

5

Tranquebar (1620-1845)

 特兰奎巴

今属印度泰米尔纳德邦 

The Danish East India Company purchased Tranquebar on the Coromandel coast of southeastern India near the French post of Pondicherry from the raja of Tanjore in 1620. Denmark also acquired posts at Pondichery (1698) and Frederiksnagore (1755) in Bengal. The Nicobar Islands were occupied in 1756. Tranquebar was occupied but not administered separately by the British from 1808 to 1815. The three mainland posts were sold to Great Britain in 1845, and the Nicobar Islands were ceded in 1869.

今印度西孟加拉邦塞兰坡

法国 France

19

French Guiana (1643-1653, 1664-1809, 1817-

法属圭亚那

法属圭亚那

A French attempt to settle in Guiana in 1604 was unsuccessful but in 1644 a settlement was settled in Cayenne. The settlement was captured by the Dutch from 1653 to 1664. In 1674 French Guiana came under royal control. It was occupied by the Portuguese from Brazil from 1809 to 1817. Between 1930 and 1951 the interior of the colony known as Inini was administratively detached although shared the same governor as French Guinea. In 1946 French Guinea became an overseas department of France and the governor was replaced by a prefect. In 2003 it became an overseas region, and in 2015 a collectivité territoriale.

22

French Polynesia (1842-

法属波利尼西亚

法属波利尼西亚

French Polynesia consists of Tahiti and the Society Islands, together with numerous islets and atolls. In 1841 the ruler of Tahiti sought and received French protection, and finally in 1880 ceded to France. Neighbouring islands were acquired from 1842 onwards. From 1853 to 1860 New Caledonia was administered from Tahiti. From 1843 to 1849, 1854 to 1860 and 1881 to 1977 the colony was administered by governors (with intervening periods by commandants). In 1958 French Polynesia voted to remain within the French Community as an overseas territory, and in 1977 with limited autonomy the title changed to High Commissioner. More autonomy was granted in 1984 and French Polynesia became a French overseas collectivité in 2003.

24

French Southern and Antarctic Lands (1955-

法属南部及南极领地

法属南部及南极领地

French Southern and Antarctic Lands (Terres Australes et Antarctiques Françaises) was created in 1955.

31

Guadeloupe (1635-

瓜德罗普

瓜德罗普（法）

Guadeloupe is located in the Lesser Antilles and it is the largest of the French possessions in the Caribbean. It was first occupied by the French in 1635 under the auspices of the Compagnie des Îles de l'Amérique. From 1649 to 1664 it was private owned, from 1664 to 1674 it was administered by the Compagnie des Indes Occidentales, and after 1674 it was directly ruled by the crown. It was occupied by the British for some period (1759-1763, 1810-1814, 1815-1816). From 1674 to 1759 and from 1768 to 1885 Guadeloupe was subordinated to the governor-general of the French Antilles at Martinique but it retained a governor of its own. Saint Barthélemy and Saint Martin were attached to Guadeloupe until 2007 when they became separate overseas collectivités. Guadeloupe became an overseas department of France in 1946, and from 2003 an overseas region.

41

Martinique (1625-

马提尼克

马提尼克（法）

France took possession of the Lesser Antilles island of Martinique in 1625 but only began to settle it from 1635 under the Compagnie des Îles de l'Amérique which governed it until 1650. In 1664 the Compagnie des Indes Occidentales purchased it from the heir of Dyel du Parquet, and retained it until 1674 when it came under the crown rule. From 1667 to 1762 nd from 1768 to 1775 Martinique was the headquarter of the governot-general of the French Antilles. Martinique was occupied by the British for some periods (1762-1763, 1794-1802, 1809-1814, 1815-1816). In 1946 Martinique became as overseas department and the governor was replaced by a prefect. In 2003 it became a French collectivité territoriale.

43

Mayotte (1841-

马约特

马约特（法）

Mayotte, one of the Comoros Islands, was ceded to France by its ruler in 1841. In 1886 the other islands of the Comoros were proclaimed protectorates, and in 1912 those became direct dependencies of Mayotte. In 1914 all islands were annexed to Madagascar and the colony ceased to exist. In 1947 the Comoro Islands were detached from Madagascar again. In 1975 when the other islands voted for independence, Mayotte voted to stay within France. It became a French collectivité territoriale in 1976, and overseas département in 2011.

48

New Caledonia (1853-

新喀里多尼亚

新喀里多尼亚（法）

The island of New Caledonia, discovered by James Cook in 1774, was occupied by the French in 1853. Until 1884 the governor of New Caledonia was also the commander of the French naval forces in the Pacific. New Caledonia voted to remain within the French Community as an overseas territory in 1958, and it gained some autonomy in 1984.

54

Réunion (1642-1810, 1815-

留尼汪

留尼汪（法）

Réunion, one of the Mascarenes (including Mauritius, Rodrigues), was claimed by France in 1639, but the first settlement was only in 1664 from Fort-Dauphin in Madagascar. Réunion was governed by the Compagnie des Indes until 1764 when the crown assumed control. After 1727 it was subject to the authority of the governor-general at Île de France. It was occupied by the British between 1810 and 1815, and when it was returned it was the only French colony left in the Indian Ocean east of Madagascar as Île de France and the Seychelles were kept for the British. In 1947 Réunion became an overseas department of France and in 2003 an overseas region.

Saint Barthélemy (1648-90, 1698-1781, 1781-85, 1878-

圣巴泰勒米

圣巴泰勒米（法） 

The island of Saint Barthélemy was settled by the French in 1648. It was transferred from the Company of the American Islands (Compagnie des Îles de l'Amérique) to the Order of Saint John (Knights Hospitaller) in 1648, and then the French West India Company bought it along with the Order’s other possessions in the Caribbean in 1665. By 1674 when the company was dissolved, the island became part of the French colony of Guadeloupe. Saint Barthélemy was sold to Sweden in 1784 and was repurchased back in 1878. It kept as part of Guadeloupe until 2007 when it became a separate overseas collectivité.

Saint Martin (1648-

圣马丁

圣马丁（法）

The island of Saint Martin was first sighted by Columbus in 1493, but was not settled by the Spaniards for quite a long time. The Dutch built Fort Amsterdam on Saint Martin in 1631 but it was occupied by the Spanish in 1633 during the Eighty Years’ War. Spain withdrew after the end of the war in 1648 Peace of Münster in which Spain recognized the independence of the Dutch Republic. The Treaty of Concordia of the same year between France and the Netherlands agreed to divide the island. The argument continued until 1816 when the final border was finalized, both sides suffering numerous conflicts and occupations, even occupation by the British 1781, 1801-02, 1810-1815, 1815-1816. The French part of Saint Martin was under Guadeloupe from 1716 to 2007 when it became a separate overseas collectivité.

60

Saint Pierre and Miquelon (1604-1713, 1763-1778, 1783-1793, 1802-1803, 1816-

圣皮埃尔和密克隆

圣皮埃尔和密克隆（法）

Saint Pierre and Miquelon is a group of eight small islands off the southern coast of Newfoundland. It was claimed by the French in 1535, but settlement only began in 1604. In 1670 it was annexed and subordinated to Plaisance, and a local governor was named in 1693. The islands was abandoned in 1709 and reinhabited to France in 1763 Treaty of Paris after all other French possessions were ceded to the British. Great Britain also occupied the islands between 1778 to 1783, 1793 to 1802, 1803 to 1816 from the beginning of the American Revolutionary War till the end of Napoleonic War. It was finally settled by the French in 1816, an overses territory in 1946, an overseas département in 1976, an collectivité territoriale in 1985, and an overseas collectivité in 2003.

70

Wallis and Futuna Islands (1887-

瓦里斯和福图纳

瓦里斯和福图纳（法）

The Wallis Islands were governed as a protectorate under French Polynesia beginning in 1842. In 1887 a protectorate was proclaimed over the Futuna Islands and the two groups were administered from New Caledonia. In 1917 they were made a colony and in 1961 an overseas territory under the high commissioner at New Caledonia, and then in 2003 a French overseas collectivité.

6

Acadia (1604-1654, 1670-1710)

阿卡迪亚

加拿大新斯科舍省

Acadia (now Nova Scotia) was the first French colony in the New World. The first settlement occurred in 1604 and was occupied by the English between 1654 and 1670. In 1710 it was permanently occupied by the English which was confirmed by the Treaty of Utrecht in 1713. After brutal fight began in 1954, France was forced to allow Algeria independence in 1962.

7

Algeria (1830-1962)

阿尔及利亚

阿尔及利亚 

France invaded Algeria in 1830, deposed the dey of Algeria and put Algeria in direct rule. It kept a military province until 1879 when a civil government was set up.

8

Annam (1884-1945)

安南保护国

越南

In 1875 the ruler of Annam accepted a resident at his court under French duress. In 1883 the powers of the resident were expanded to became the de facto ruler of the kingdom. The protectorate of Annam was a component of the Union of Indochina in 1887. It was occupied by the Japanese during the World War II. After French withdrawal in 1954 the area of Annam was divided between North and South Vietnam.

9

Cambodia (1863-1953)

柬埔寨保护国

柬埔寨

France proclaimed a protectorate over the kingdom of Cambodia in 1863. In 1887 Cambodia became a constituent member of the Union of Indochina. During World War II the Japanese suppressed the French administration in Cambodia/. French control was reimposed in 1945. In 1949 Cambodia became an associated state of the French Union, and it became fully independent in 1954.

10

Cameroun (1916-1960)

法属喀麦隆

喀麦隆

During World War I France occupied the eastern and major part of the German colony of Kamerun. From 1922 Cameroun was administered under the mandate from the League of Nations, and in 1946 a trusteeship from the United Nations. Cameroun became independent in 1960.

11

Chad (1900-1960)

乍得殖民地

乍得

The area of Chad became subject to the French penetration after 1890 and an administrative structure was established in 1900. From 1906 to 1829 Chad and Ubangi-Shari were administered as one unit. After 1920 Chad became a separate colony within French Equatorial Africa. The colony was ruled by lieutenant governors until 1946 when the rank was raied to governor. Chad voted to became an autonomous state within the French Community in the referendum of 1958 and it became independent in 1960.

12

Cochin China (1858-1949)

法属交趾支那

越南

French began the occupation of this southernmost part of Kingdom of Annam in 1858, and this conquest was recognized by Annam who ceded the provinces of Cochin China to France. Until 1879 all governors were all admirals of the French navy and after that followed by civil government. The colony was governed by a lieutenant governor since 1887 when the Union of Indochina was instituted, and in 1911 the rant was raised to governor again. Cochin China was the only component of Indochina rule directly, while others were nominally protectorates. Cochina China was occupied by the Japanese in 1942 during World War II. After 1954 Cochin China became a part of South Vietnam.

13

Comoro Islands (1886-1975)

科摩罗

科摩罗

The islands of Ngazidja (Grande Comore), Ndzuwani (Anjouan) and Mwali (Moheli) became French protectorate in 1886 and were subordinated to Mayotte. In 1914 together with Mayotte, the Comoro Islands were incorporated into Madagascar. They were separated from Madagascar in 1947 and erected into a separate colony. Internal autonomy was granted in 1961 and the governors became high commissioners. Follow a referendum the Comoros gained independence in 1975.

14

Dahomey (1894-1960)

达荷美

今贝宁

Cotonou (1878-1883)

科特努

贝宁科特努

Porto-Novo (1863-1865, 1882-1894)

波多诺伏

今贝宁波多诺伏

A protectorate was established over Porto Novo in 1863 but withdrawn in 1867 only to be reasserted in 1883. Cotonou became a protectorate (attached to Gaban) in 1878 as well. In 1894 the interior kingdom of Dahomey was conquered and a protectorate was established there, and by 1900 the kingdom was abolished and the territory annexed. Until 1886 the settlements were under Gaban, from 1886 to 1894 under Rivières du Sud (French Guinea). In 1894 Dahomey became a separate colony, and in 1899 Dahomey became part of French West Africa. In 1937 the lieutenant governors of Dahomey became governors. In 1958 it became an autonoumous member of the French Community and in 1960 it became independent.

15

Diégo-Suarez (1886-1896)

迭戈-苏亚雷斯

今马达加斯加安齐拉纳纳

The colony of Diégo-Suarez was established in the far north of Madagascar in 1886 when France made the Merina Kingdom a protectorate. With the whole island of Madagascar controlled by French forces and the establishment of the colony of Madagascar in 1896, Diégo-Suarez was abolished and became a district of Madagascar.

16

Fort Dauphin (1642-1674, 1768-1771)

多芬堡

今马达加斯加陶拉纳鲁

Fort Dauphin on the southeastern tip of Madagascar was founded in 1642 by the French. From 1667 to 1671 it served briefly as the headquarters of the Compagnie des Indes Orientales, but it was replaced by India. Fort Dauphin was abandoned in 1674. There’s another settlement attempt between 1768 and 1771.

17

French Antilles (1667-1759, 1768-1775)

法属安的列斯

马提尼克（等）

The various French possessions in the West Indies were private owned and administered until 1667 when a governor-general was appointed, although crown control over the islands was deferred until 1674. The governor-general resided on Martinique, and from 1667 to 1762 the component islands still has their own administrations. The French Antilles included Martinique, Guadeloupe, part of Saint-Christophe (to 1702 when conquered by the English), Saint-Croix (to 1733 when sold to Denmark), Désirade, Marie-Galante, Grenada, and various minor islands. The English captured these islands between 1759 and 1762. The governor-general was not re-established after the British return of the islands, and there’s a reinstitution in 1768 but finally abolished in 1775.

18

French Equatorial Africa (1910-1960)

法属赤道非洲 

今加蓬、刚果（布拉柴维尔）、乌班吉-沙里（今中非共和国）、乍得

In 1882 the French Congo was created and in 1886 a commissioner-general was appointed. It has authority over both Gabon and French Congo, and in 1906 expanded to the newly created Ubangi-Shari-Chad (later separated into Ubangi-Shari and Chad). In 1910 the name French Congo was changed to French Equatorial Africa and the commissioner-general was changed to governor-general. In 1958 the federation was dissolved and each of the four component colonies chose autonomy.

20

French Guinea (1893-1958)

法属几内亚

几内亚

Riviéres du Sud (1882-1893)

南部河流

今几内亚

In 1882 the colony of Riviéres du Sud was created. After 1886 this included the French establishments alone the Gulf of Guinea as well. Until 1891 Riviéres du Sud was subordinated to Senegal, and in 1893 the name of the colony was changed to French Guinea and it was given separate status. French Guinea was part of the French West Africa in 1895. In the 1958 referendum it was the only colony to vote for fully and immediate independent and became the Republic of Guinea.

21

French India (1674-1954)

法属印度

今印度本地治里（等） 

French settlement in India was successful in 1768, and in 1674 Pondichéry was acquired. The British occupied these French possessions between 1793 to 1816. After 1816 the French India, known as the Établissements Français dans l'Inde, consisted of Pondichéry, Karikal, and Yanaon on the Coromandel coast, Mahé on the Malabar coast and Chandernagore in Bengal. France retained these possessions until after the India independence , only between 1950 and 1954 they were transferred to India.

23

French Somaliland (1862-1977)

法属索马里兰

索马里

Obock at the southern end of the Red Sea, was acquired by France 1862, but it was not occupied until 1884. In 1892 the capital was transferred to the more advantageously located at Djibouti and in 1896 the colony was renamed Côte française des Somalis (French Coast of the Somalis). The British occupied the colony during part of World War II although the administration remained under France. In 1958 referendum it voted to become an overseas territory of the French Union rather than to be autonomous. In 1967 the territory was renamed Territoire des Afars et Issas (French Territory of the Afars and Issas). In another referendum in 1977 it chose independence.

25

French Sudan (1880-1960)

法属苏丹

马里

In 1880 a commandant-supérieur was appointed for the French control in Senegal expanding eastward along the Niger River. Its name was changed several time, Upper River (1880-1890), French Sudan (1890-1899), Upper Senegal-Middle Niger (1899-1902), Senegambia-Niger (1902-1904), Upper Senegal-Niger (1904-1920), and finally settled as French Sudan in 1920. Until 1892 and from 1899 to 1904 the colony was subordinate to Senegal and it was part of French West Africa from 1895 to 1958. From 1932 to 1947 part of the suppressed colony of Upper Volta was attached to French Sudan. In 1958 French Sudan voted to become an autonomous member of the French Community, and in 1960 it became independent as Mali.

26

French West Africa (1895-1960)

法属西非

今毛里塔尼亚、塞内加尔、尼日尔、法属苏丹（今马里）、法属几内亚（今几内亚）、象牙海岸（今科特迪瓦）、上沃尔特（今布基纳法索）和达荷美（今贝宁）

In 1895 French Guinea, French Sudan, Ivory Coast and Senegal were administratively united in a federation known as French West Africa. Dahomey joined in 1899, and Mauritania, Niger, and Upper Volta also joined when they became separate colonies. The governor-general of French West Africa also served as lieutenant governor of Senegal until 1902 when Senegal was reconstructed as a colony. In 1937 the heads of the eight colonies were raised to the rank of governors. In 1958 the federation was dissolved.

27

Gabon (1839-1960)

加蓬

加蓬 

French settlements on the Gabon coast were organized under a commandant-particulier, subject to Senegal, in 1843. After 1859 the commandant-supérieur of Gabon and the Gulf of Guinea settlements had the title Commandant of the Naval Division of the West Coast of Africa, while a commandant-particulier remained in Gabon. In 1881 this individual became commandant-supérieur of Gabon and the Gulf of Guinea, but the latter was removed from his jurisdiction in 1886. In 1891 Gabon became subordinated to French Congo (later French Equatorial Africa), with a lieutenant governor. After 1910 it was a component colony of French Equatorial Africa. In 1946 the title was raised to governors. In 1958 Gabon became an autonomous member of the French Community and it achieved independence in 1960 as Gabon.

28

Gorée and dependencies (1677-92, 1693-1758,1763-79, 1783-1800, 1817-1960)

戈雷岛

今属塞内加尔

The islet of Gorée off Cape Verde in Senegal was occupied by the French in 1677. From 1763 to 1778 Gorée was the only part of Senegal retained by the French. Until 1854 Gorée was always subordinate to the governor of Senegal, and then detached from Senegal together with the French posts in Gabon and along the Guinea coast erected into a separate colony. The commandant-supérieur has simultaneously the title Commandant of Naval Division of the West Coast of Africa. The commandant-particulier resided in Gorée administered the island only, and by 1859 Gorée was reattached to Senegal while other posts were erected into a separate colony headquartered in Gabon.

29

Great Lebanon (1918-1946)

大黎巴嫩

黎巴嫩

Ottoman part of Syria fell to France after World War I. In 1920 the predominantly Christian sanjaks (administrative districts) were separated and formed Great Lebanon. In 1926 a republic was proclaimed but it was only until 1944 Lebanon won its fully independence.

30

Grenada (1650-1762, 1779-1783)

格林纳达

格林纳达

Grenada was discovered by Columbus in 1498. It was settled from Martinique in 1649, and in 1664 it was purchased by the Compagnie des Indes Occidentales. Ten years later it came under royal control. Grenada remained a French colony subject to the authority of the governor-general of the French Antilles until 1762 when it was occupied by the British. This became permanent in 1763 by the Treaty of Paris. There’s a brief reoccupation between 1779 and 1794.

32

Île de France (1715-1810)

法兰西岛

毛里求斯

Mauritius was occupied by the Dutch from 1638 to 1658 and 1664 to 1710 and then abandoned. It was claimed by France in 1715 and settled from Réunion in 1722. It was administered by the Compagnie des Indes until 1767 when it was directed ruled by the French government. The governor at Île de France was governor-general of the French possessions in the Indian Ocean after 1727. During the Napoleonic War in 1810 Île de France was occupied by the British and renamed it after the old Dutch name Mauritius. Great Britain retained the island at the Treaty of Paris in 1814.

33

Île Royale (1605-1745)

国王岛

今加拿大新斯科舍省布雷顿角岛

Île Royale, or Cape Breton, was occupied by the French after the British conquest of Acadia in 1710. Île Royale was occupied by the British from 1745 to 1749 and again in 1758 when the whole of New France was taken from the French, but only in 1784 it was constituted a separate British colony Cape Breton.

34

Île Saint-Jean (1663-1758)

圣让岛 

今加拿大爱德华王子岛

Île Saint-Jean, north of the Acadia across the Strait of the Northumberland, was only settled in 1720 by the refugees from Acadia. It remained a French possession with an interval of English occupation from 1744 to 1748, until 1758 when France’s all major North American colonies were permanently occupied by the British, who later named it Prince Edward Island.

35

Indochina (1887-1949)

法属印度支那

今越南、老挝、柬埔寨

Indochina was a federation formed in 1887 from the colony of Cochin China and the protectorates of Annam, Cambodia, and Tonkin. Laos was added as a protectorate in 1897 and Kouang-Tchéou-Wan 1900. Between 1941 and 1945 it was occupied by the Japanese but the Vichy-appointed governor-general was retained. From 1945 to 1946 Indochina was temporarily occupied by British and Chinese troops. Kouang-Tchéou-Wan was returned to China in 1946. Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam were recognized as independent within the French Union in 1949 and 1950, but the role of high commissioners (later commissioners-general) was retained. In 1954 France finally completely withdrew from the region.

36

Ivory Coast (1843-1960)

象牙海岸

科特迪瓦

In 1843 the protectorates were established at Grand-Bassam and Assinie. The commandant at Grand-Bassam often carried the title Commandant-Particulier of the French Establishments on the Gold Coast. It was under the authority of the commandant of the Naval Division of the West Coast of Africa, like those in Gabon. The French abandoned its claims to the posts in 1871, and in 1881 the commandant-supérieur of Gabon was granted responsibility for French interest in the Ivory Coast. From 1886 to 1893 the area fell under the jurisdiction of the lieutenant general of Riviéres du Sud (French Guinea). A resident was appointed at Assinie in 1889 and a colony called Ivory Coast (Côte d'Ivoire) was created in 1893. It was part of French West Africa from 1895 to 1958, governed by a lieutenant governor until 1937 and then by a governor. In 1958 the colony voted to became an autonomous member of the French Community, and two years later it became fully independent, keeping the name Ivory Coast (and in 1985 the French name Côte d'Ivoire was used as official name)

37

Kouang-Tchéou-Wan (1898-1946)

广州湾

今属中国广州

Kouang-Tchéou-Wan, in the northeast part of the Luichow Peninsula in Kwangtung Province of China, was occupied by France in 1898, and was forced to be leased from China. In 1900 it was attached to Indochina. In 1943 it was occupied by the Japanese, and returned to China after World War II in 1946.

38

Laos (1893-1953)

老挝保护国 

老挝 

A French consulate was established in the Kingdom of Luang Prabang in Laos in 1886. In 1897 France proclaimed a protectorate over Luang Prabang, and attached it to Indochina under the control of a resident-general. French control was restored in 1946 after the Japanese occupation during World War II. In 1949 France recognized Laos as independent within the French Union, and Laos gained fully independence in 1954.

39

Louisiana (1699-1762, 1800-1803)

路易斯安那 

美国路易斯安那州 

In 1699 Biloxi was settled from New France and in 1718 the capital was moved to New Orleans. It was under crown rule from 1699 to 1713, a proprietary colony of Antoine Crozat from 1713 to 1716, administered by the Compagnie de l’Quest from 1716 to 1733, and then again under crown rule from 1733. Louisiana was ceded to the Spaniards by the Treaty of Fontainebleu to forestall a British takeover.

40

Madagascar (1896-1960)

马达加斯加

马达加斯加

The coastline of Madagascar was first sighted by the Portuguese around 1500. From 1643 to 1674 there was a French colony at Fort-Dauphin. In 1750 France obtained Sainte Marie de Madagascar by cession and in 1841 the island of Nosy Bé. In 1885 French forced invaded the Merina Kingdom and proclaimed a protectorate. Meanwhile Diégo-Suarez was ceded to the French. In 1896 a second invasion resulted in the abolition of the Merina Kingdom and the whole Madagascar became a French colony, with the three colonies included. In 1958 Madagascar voted to became autonomous within the French Community, and then became independent in 1960.

42

Mauritania (1903-1960)

毛里塔尼亚

毛里塔尼亚

Only begin in 1900 full-scale occupation was began although the French rights to this region had been recognized by Great Britain as early as 1857. From 1902 to 1920 Mauritania was only a military district ruled by a commandant, but in 1920 it became a colony and a member of the French West Africa. It was so desolate that until 1958 it was administered from Saint Louis in Senegal. In 1958 it voted to became autonomous within the French Community and them became independent in 1960.

44

Middle Congo (1880-1960)

中刚果

今刚果（布拉柴维尔）

A separate administration for Middle Congo was established under French Congo in 1897. In 1911 a large chunk of the colony was ceded to Germany and attached to Kamerun in return for German non-interference in Morocco. After the Allied conquest of the German colonies during World War I, this territory was restored to Middle Congo. Three times during its existence (1903-1906, 1925-1929, 1932-1941) Middle Congo was suppressed and directly administered by the governor-general of French Equatorial Africa. In 1958 the colony became autonomous within the French Community, and it became independent as the Congo Republic in 1960;.

45

Minorca (1756-1763)

梅诺卡岛

今属西班牙巴利阿里群岛

The British colony of Minorca was occupied by the French in 1756 during the Seven Years’ War, and it was returned to the British at 1773 Treaty of Paris.

46

Montreal (1642-1760)

蒙特利尔

今属加拿大魁北克省

The town of Montreal was founded from Quebec in 1642, and remained a separate jurisdiction under New France until its capture by the British in 1760.

47

Morocco (1912-1956)

摩洛哥

摩洛哥

As a return to the cession of a large area of Middle Congo to German Kamerun, German withdrew its opposition to the French possession in North Africa, thus Morocco was then substantially divided into a Spanish zone and a French zone, with the city of Tangiers becoming an internationally controlled city. This lasted till 1956 when France was forced to give Morocco full independence. Spain followed almost immediately.

49

New France (1534-1763)

新法兰西

今加拿大魁北克省

In 1603 colonizing efforts began in Acadia, and in 1608 Quebec, which became the capital of New France, was founded. The colony was occupied by the English in 1629, but it was returned in 1632. All the French settlements in Canada were occupied by the British during the Seven Years’ War from 1756, and ceded to the British in 1763 Treaty of Paris.

50

New Hebrides Condominium (1887-1980)

新赫布里底群岛共管地

今瓦努阿图

51

Niger (1900-1960)

尼日尔

尼日尔

The French created a new colony, Niger, in 1911 with the penetration east of the Niger river. Niger remained under military rule until 1922 when civil government was introduced and it was raised to a colony. In 1937 the tile was raised from lieutenant governor to governor. In 1958 Niger became autonomous within the French Community, and it gained independence in 1960.

52

Nosy Bé (1840-1960)

贝岛

今属马达加斯加

Nosy Bé, a small island of the northwest coast of Madagascar, was ceded to France in 1840 by its local ruler. It was under Réunion until 1843, under Mayotte from 1843 to 1878, and then it was made a separate colony. In 1896 it was subsumed into the colony of Madagascar.

53

Plaisance (1640-1714)

普莱桑斯

今属加拿大纽芬兰省 

Plaisance, on an inlet in southern Newfoundland, was established by the French in about 1640 and it was colonized in 1662. Plaisance was surrendered to Great Britain by the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht.

55

Saint-Christophe (1625-29, 1630-90, 1699-1702, 1782-1783)

圣克里斯托弗

今属圣基茨和尼维斯

Saint-Christophe was the first French settlement in the West Indies, and from the beginning the island was shared with the English. The French part was privately owned successively by the Compagnie de Saint-Christophe (1628-1635), the Compagnie des Îles de l'Amérique (1635-1651), the Knights of Malta (1651-1665), and the Compagnie des Indes Occidentales (1665-1674). In 1666 the French drove the British from the island, but in 1671 the island was divided between the two nations again. In 1702 the French was finally expelled from the island and the British rule was confirmed by the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht.

56

Saint-Domingue (1633-1804)

圣多明克

今海地

Tortuga, an island off the northwest coast of the Spanish colony of Santo Domingo (also known as Hispaniola) was occupied by the French in 1641. By the Treaty of Ryswick in 1697 France obtained the western part of Hispaniola, renaming it Saint-Domingue. The 1789 French Revolution brought a decade of chaotic strife to the colony, by 1802 the French had lost control, and they withdrew completed in 1803. The colony gained independence as Haiti.

57

Sainte-Lucie (1643-64, 1666-67, 1719-1720,1744-62, 1763-78, 1784-94 1795-96, 1802-03)

圣卢西亚

圣卢西亚

The island of Sainte-Lucie was disputed between the English and the French between 1638 and 1763. From 1723 to 1743 and 1748 to 1756 the island was officially declared neutral. France occupied it in 1756, lost it in 1762, and regained it in 1763. It was in French hands for most of the time between 1763 to 1803 (with intermediate occupy by the British). After 1803 it became permanently British.

58

Sainte Marie de Madagascar (1750-1960)

圣玛丽岛

今马达加斯加布拉哈岛

Sainte Marie, a small island off the northeastern coast of Madagascar, was ceded to the French in 1750 by its local ruler, but it remained unoccupied until 1819. Until 1843 it was under Bourbon (Réunion), then subjected to Mayotte from 1843 to 1853, and a separate colony from 1853 to 1877. In 1877 it was returned to Réunion’s jurisdiction, until 1896 when it was annexed to colony of Madagascar in 1896.

59

Saint Eustatius (1629,1666-68,1689-90, 1781-84,1795-1801)

圣尤斯特歇斯岛

圣尤斯特歇斯岛

The French occupation of Saint Eustatius (Dutch colony) from 1781 to 1784.

61

Senegal (1626-1758, 1779-1809,1817-1960)

塞内加尔

塞内加尔

In 1659 the French built Saint Louis at the mouth of the Senegal River, and in 1677 they also occupied Gorée. From 1628 to 1758 French activities along the Senegal coast were controlled by below companies successively: Compagnie Normand (1626-1658), Compagnie du Cap Vert et du Sénégal (1658-1664), Compagnie des Indes Occidentales (1664-1673), Compagnie d’Afrique (1673-1682), Compagnies du Sénégal (1682-1718), Compagnie des Indes Orientales (1718-1758). In 1758 the British seized the French forts, and they returned Gorée in 1763 but ercted the remainder into the colony of Senegambia. The French retook it in 1778, lost again in 1809, and finally recovered it in 1817. In 1895 Senegal became the seat of French West Africa and lost its own individual administration until 1902. In 1958 Senegal became autonomous within the French Community and it became fully independent in 1960.

62

Seychelles Islands (1770-1810)

塞舌尔群岛

塞舌尔

France occupied the British colony of Seychelles Islands from 1788 to 1810.

63

Syria (1920-1946)

叙利亚

叙利亚

Syria fell to France as a League of Nations mandate after World War I. France divided the territory into five states – Aleppo, Damascus, Jabal Druze, the Alawis, and Great Lebanon, and collectively called them as the Levant States. The first four remained loosely united and in 1941 it gained nominal independence in 1941 as Syria. The mandate remained in effect until 1946.

64

Tobago (1666-1667, 1677, 1748-1749, 1781-1793, 1802-1803)

多巴哥岛

今属特立尼达和多巴哥 

France occupied the British colony of Tobago from 1781 to 1793.

65

Togo (1914-1960)

多哥

多哥

The German colony of Togo was occupied by British and French forces in 1914. In 1922 they were awarded mandates for their parts of togo. The British portion was part of the Gold Coast colony, while France portion became a separate colony. In 1946 Togo became a United Nation trusteeship. Im 1956 it was granted a measure of internal autonomy, followed by a full independence in 1960.

66

Tonkin (1883-1954)

东京保护国

越南

Tonkin was the northern viceroyalty of the Kingdom of Annam. In 1886 a French resident was appointed and subjected to the resident-general of Annam. Finally in 1888 Tonkin was raised to a parity with Annam as a member of the Indochina. It was occupied by the Japanese during World War II. In 1954 when France withdrew from Indochina, Tonkin became part of North Vietnam.

67

Tunis (1881-1956)

突尼斯

突尼斯

Tunis was occupied by the French forces in 1881. A protectorate was proclaimed and the resident-general became the effective executive head of the country. A measure of autonomy was granted in 1951 but nationalist pressure forced France to grant complete independence in 1956.

68

Ubangui-Shari (1892-1960)

法属乌班吉-夏利

今中非共和国

The French expansion inland from French Congo led to the creation of the province of Ubangi-Shari in 1894, and it was one of the four colonies comprising French Equatorial Africa. From 1906 to 1920 the lieutenant governors also administered Chad. In 1958 Ubangi-Shari became an autonomous member of the French Community, and it became independent in 1960 as the Central African Republic.

69

Upper Volta (1895-1960)

上沃尔特

今布基纳法索

The colony of Upper Volta was detached in 1919 from the provinces of Upper Senegal-Niger composed of the Mossi people. The colony was dismembered in 1932 and divided among Dahomey, French Sudan and Ivory Coast. In 1947 it was re-created, became autonomous within the French Community in 1958, and gained independence in 1960.

德国 Germany

71

German East Africa (1885-1914)

德属东非

含今卢旺达、布隆迪、坦桑尼亚、莫桑比克

In 1884 the Gesellschaft für deutsche Kolonisation (Society of German Colonization) was established, and it was renamed Deutsch-Ostafrikanische Gesellschaft (German East Africa Company) in 1885. At the same year, a protectorate was declared. By the 1890 Heligoland Treaty, Germany abandoned its claims to Zanzibar, the Sultanate of Witu, and Nyasaland to Great Britain, in return for Heligoland which had been occupied by the British since 1807. The territorial rights was transferred to the German government in 1891. After World War I, German East Africa was divided by the League of Nations, the greater part went to Great Britain as Tanganyika, and the interlocutrice states of Rwanda and Burundi were awarded to Belgium.

72

German New Guinea (1884-1914)

德属新几内亚

含今巴布亚新几内亚新几内亚岛北半部、俾斯麦群岛、太平洋保护领（所罗门群岛、加罗林群岛、马里亚纳群岛、马绍尔群岛和瑙鲁）

The New Guinea Company was formed in 1884 and within a year German sovereignty had been proclaimed over northeastern New Guinea, the islands to the north, which were known as the Bismarck Archipelago and the Marshall Islands. Nauru was annexed in 1888 and the Mariana Islands (except Guam), the Caroline Islands, and the Palau Islands purchased from Spain in 1899. Initially the New Guinea Company administered the mainland territory, christened Kaiser Wilhelmsland, and the Jaluit Company the islands. The former relinquished its sovereignty to the German government in 1899, the latter in 1906. British, Australian, New Zealand and Japanese forces occupied all German territories in the Pacific Ocean immediately after the outbreak of World War I in 1914. In the disposition of the German colonial territories in 1920, Japan received the Mariana, Caroline, Marshall, and Palau, and Australia received a mandate to the Bismarck, Nauru and Kaiser Wilhelmsland.

73

German Samoa (1900-1914)

德属萨摩亚

今萨摩亚

In 1879 Great Britain, the United States, and Germany signed an agreement by which the Samoan Islands to be under the joint supervision of these three countries represented by their respective consuls in Apia. This didn’t work well and in 1899 was replaced by the Tripartite Treaty provided that Germany and the United States divided the Samoan group between them with Great Britain receiving as compensation half the Solomon Islands, as well as a free hand in the Tonga Islands and some other German possessions. The western part of the Samoan Islands, known as the Territory of Western Samoa, was administered by Germany until 1914 when it was seized by New Zealand during World War I, which in 1920 received the mandatory rights to former German Samoa.

74

German Southwest Africa (1884-1915)

德属西南非洲

今纳米比亚

Germany proclaimed the area at Angra Pequena on the coast of southwest Africa to be under German protection, Germany’s first official colonial venture. The political boundaries of German Southwest Africa were demarcated in the 1890 Heligoland Treaty which established the Caprivi Strip extending to the Zambezi River. Earlier the German government had taken over direct control of the area from the Southwest Africa Colonial Company in 1889. Troops from the Union of South Africa invaded and conquered German Southwest Africa in 1915 during World War I, and this territory was later awarded as a mandate to South Africa by the League of Nations. In 1946 South Africa rejected the UN Trusteeship and claimed the area as one political entity with South Africa. The United Nations declared this an illegal occupation in 1970, and this area finally gained independence from South Africa in 1990 as Namibia.

75

Kamerun (1884-1916)

喀麦隆

今属喀麦隆

A foothold was secured by Germany along the Cameroon coast near Duala in 1884, and was expanded interior lands considerably with subsequent explorations. It also gained a big area from the French colony of Middle Congo as a by-product of the Agadir crisis, and thereby extended its boundaries to the Congo River. Kamerun was conquered by the British and French in 1916 and remained occupied by troops of both nations jointly. After the war it was divided. Britain secured a slice along the western boundary administered through British colony of Nigeria, and France received the vastly larger share which it governed independently as Cameroun. The League of Nations formalized this arrangement in 1922 by granting mandates.

76

Kiaochow (1897-1914)

胶州湾租借地

今属中国山东省

In 1898 Chian was induced to lease the Kiaochow peninsula to Germany for a period of 99 years. Koaochow was not governed through the regular German colonial administration but rather by the Naval Ministry because of the nature of Germany’s interest was its pursuit of an ice-free port in the Far East. In 1914 Japan occupied Kiaochow and administered it directly, not as a League of Nations mandate. It was returned to China in 1922.

77

Togo (1884-1914)

多哥兰

今多哥

In 1884 German commercial agents began to sign treaties of protection with the chiefs in the area of Togo while the German government assumed direct responsibility from the beginning. Eventually a long thin strip of territory was demarcated and it remained under German rule until 1914 when it was easily occupied by the surrounding British and French colonial forces. After the war it was divided between France and Great Britain, each granted a League of Nations mandate in 1922. Similar to the situation in German Kamerun, the British chose to rule it through existing colony of Gold Coast, and the French separated it to rule as Togo.

英国 United Kingdom

78

Acadia (1654-1670)

阿卡迪亚

加拿大新斯科舍省

The French colony of Acadia was occupied by the English from 1654 to 1670.

79

Aden (1839-1967)

亚丁殖民地

今属也门

Aden, near the southwestern corner of the Arabian Peninsula was established by the British in 1839. The settlement was subject to the presidency of Bombay under the government of India until 1947. It included as dependencies, the islands of Karaman and PErim in the Red Sea, and Socotra and Kuria Muria in the Indian Ocean. The Adam government also exercised jurisdiction over the states of the Eastern and Western Protectorates. In 1959 all these states began to unite into the South Arabian Federation. In 1963 Aden itself joined the federation and ceased to exist as a separate colony.

80

Ajmer-Merwara (1818-1947)

阿杰米尔-梅尔华拉省

今属印度拉贾斯坦邦

Ajmer and Merwara were ceded to the British by the Sindhia ruler in 1818, and between 1832 and 1871 were part of the North-West Frontier Provinces. Until 1871 it was governed by superintendents, and then the agent to the viceroy for Rajputana became the ex officio chief commissioner of Ajmer-Merwara. In 1947 it became part of India.

81

Andaman (1789-1947) and Nicobar Islands (1868-1947)

安达曼和尼科巴群岛

今属印度

The Andaman Islands, located in the Bay of Bengal, had been unsed as a penal colony by the British in India from 1789 to 1796 when it was abandoned. It was reestablished after 1850, and a superintendent was appointed in 1858. From 1872 the administering officer was known as chief commissioner. In 1869 the adjacent Nicobar Islands were obtained from Denmark. From 1942 to 1945 the islands were occupied by the Japanese, and in 1947 acceded to India.

82

Anglo-Egyptian Sudan (1898-1956)

英埃苏丹

今苏丹和南苏丹

The area of the Nilotic Sudan was occupied by the Egyptian forces until 1821, and it was administered by Egypt until 1881 when the Mahdist erupted and drove the Egyptians and their British supporters. In 1898 the Sudan was re-occupied which was nominal a condominium but all high-level officials were British. In 1956 the Anglo-Egyptian Sudan became independent as Sudan.

83

Antigua (1632-1666, 1667-1860)

安提瓜

今属安提瓜和巴布达

Antigua was discovered by Columbus in 1493. It was settled by the English from Saint Kitts in 1632 till its independence in 1981 (only a short period of French occupation 1666-67). In 1671 Antigua became the seat of the newly created Leeward Islands government but was locally administered by a deputy governor until 1747 when the office was abolished, After 1871 Antigua was administered by the colonial secretary of the Leeward Islands, and only in 1936 the office of Administrator of Antigua was created. From 1958 to 1962 Antigua was a member of the West Indies Federation, and it ceased to be a member of the Leeward Islands when its government dissolved in 1960. Antigua was a member of the Associated States of the West Indies from 1967 to 1981 when it won independence.

84

Ashanti (1896-1957)

阿散蒂

今属加纳

With the conquest of the Ashanti Kingdom in 1896 a resident was appointed by the governor of the Gold Coast. In 1902 the resident was replaced by a chief commissioner. When Gold Coast was granted internal autonomy, the officers of Ashanti were designated regional officers. In 1957 it was part of the independent Gold Coast.

85

Assam (1874-1947)

阿萨姆

今印度阿萨姆邦

The region of Assam was under Bengal until 1874 when a commissioner was appointed. From 1905 to 1912 it was part of the short-lived province of East Bengal and Assam, and then again, a separate government. In 1921 it was elevated to a governor’s province. In 1947 Assam was part of India, and later became the state of Assam in 1950.

86

Assiniboia (1812-1870)

阿西尼博因

今属加拿大西北地区

The area of Assiniboia in western Canada was granted to the Scot Lord Selkirk by the Hudson’s Bay Company in 1812. It was directly ruled by the Company from 1836 to 1870, when it was absorbed into the newly created province of Manitoba.

87

Australia (1901-1931)

澳大利亚

澳大利亚

The British colonies of New South Wales, Northern Australia, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria, and Western Australia was unified to establish the Commonwealth of Australia in 1901. Australia is a federal state, with each of the former colonies now individual states within it. It gained its legislative independence from the United Kingdom when the Statute of Westminster granted sovereignty to the British Dominion.

88

Bahama Islands (1648-1657, 1670-1781, 1781-1973)

巴哈马群岛

巴哈马

The Bahama Islands were discovered by Columbus in 1492, and were sporadically occupied by the Spaniards until 1629 when they were occupied by the English. The civil government was inaugurated only in 1670 after the grant of the islands to the lords proprietors of South Carolina. The direct crown rule was resumed in 1717. The islands were occupied by the Americans and the Spaniards during the American Revolutionary War. The Turks and Caicos Islands were subject to the governor of the Bahamas. The Bahamas remain a crown colony of Great Britain until 1973 when it gained independence.

89

Bahrain (1880-1971)

巴林

巴林 

Bahrain, an island and sheikhdom in the Persian Gulf, was brought under British protectorate during the 19th century. In 1900 a political agent was appointed to the court of Bahrain (until 1947 this agent was appointed by the government of India), who was subject to the authority of the chief political resident of the Persian Gulf. Bahrain gained its full independence in 1971.

90

Baluchistan (1877-1947)

俾路支斯坦

今巴基斯坦俾路支省

The British began to control the extreme western of India known as Baluchistan in the 1870s. British protectorates were established over the states of Kalat and Las Bela and a chief commissioner was appointed in 1877. Baluchistan became part of Pakistan in 1947.

91

Bantam (1603-1682)

万丹

今印度尼西亚万丹省

Bantam in West Java was the most important Englist post in the East Indies since 1603. A chief factor was appointed by the East India Company in 1613. In 1617 it was raised to a presidency bur reduced to an agency under Surat between 1630 to 1634. After 1634 it was again a presidency. When the presidency was moved to Madras in 1652, Bantam became an agency again. It remained so until it was abandoned in 1682 when the Dutch power in Java became dominant.

92

Barbados (1625-1966)

巴巴多斯

巴巴多斯

Barbados in the Lesser Antilles was discovered by the Spaniards in 1519. The British began to setter in 1627, and in 1628 they expelled the original colonists. In 1662 the British crown assumed direct control. From 1833 to 1885 the governor of Barbados was also governor-in-chief of the Windward Islands, which includes Granada, Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent, and Tobago. In 1855 Barbados became again a separate crown colony when the Windward Island was reconstructed without Barbados. Barbados became independent in 1966.

93

Basutoland (1868-1966)

巴苏陀兰

今莱索托

In 1868 the area occupied by the Sutu was proclaimed a protectorate of the British Empire. In 1871 it was attached to the Cape Colony but with special legislative provisions which ensured its autonomy. It was detached from Cape Colony following the Disannexation Act of 1883, and a resident commissioner replaced the government in 1884. Subsequently the resident commissioner was subject to the high commissioner for South Africa but not to the Union of South Africa. The protectorate remained separate until 1966 when it gained its independence under the new name of Lesotho.

94

Bay Islands (1638-50, 1742-50, 1779-86, 1839-60)

海湾群岛

今属洪都拉斯

Th Bay Islands consist of Ruatan and several other islands in the Bay of Honduras. It was first discovered by Columbus in 1502. The English settled in 1638 but was destroyed by the Spaniards in 1650. There’s British occupation between 1742 and 1752, and then 1779 to 1786. It was only after 1838 considerable immigration from the Cayman Islands took place, and in 1841 the British claimed the islands. In 1852 it was erected into a distinct crown colony. The governor of Jamaica was the governor-in-chief of the Bay Islands, and the superintendent of British Honduras was the lieutenant governor of the Bay Islands, when the resident authority on the islands was titled presiding magistrates. In 1860 the British ceded the islands to Honduras, which took full possession in the following year.

95

Bechuanaland (1885-1966)

贝专纳兰

今博兹瓦纳

As a buffer zone for Britain’s South African possessions, the area was proclaimed a protectorate of Bechuanaland in 1885. In 1891 the area was delimited , and the administrator was replaced by a resident commissioner who subject directly to the high commissioner for South Africa. It was never under the authority of the Union of South Africa although its south area was annexed to the Cape Colony in 1895. Bechuanaland remained a protectorate until 1966 when it became independent as Botswana.

96

Bencoolen (1685-1825)

明古连

今属印度尼西亚苏门答腊

British established York Fort in the Bencoolen area at the west coast of Sumatra in 1685. After 1714 the British centre was moved to Fort Marlborough. Until 1760 the Bencoolen posts were subordinate to Madras, and then raised to the status of a presidency until 1785 when it became subordinate to Bengal. Great Britain retained control of Bencoolen until 1825 when it was ceded to the Dutch (Netherlands East Indies) as a result of 1824 agreement of exchange (the Dutch in the East Indian archipelago and the British in Malaya).

97

Bengal (1681-1947)

孟加拉管辖区

含今印度、孟加拉国等

Bengal was the first large area of India to come under direct British rule since 1700 as Presidency of Fort William in Bengal. In 1774 the governor of Bengal became governor-general of all the British possessions in India. It governed the majority of the possessions in India expect Bombay and Madras, and in 1834 Agra (later the North-West Provinces) was carved from Bengal. Bengal got a separate lieutenant governor appointed which freeing the governor-general from the local responsibilities. Assam, Bihar and Orissa were removed from Bengal and created separate provinces in the following years. Between 1905 and 1912 Bengal was partitioned into two provinces, Bengal, and Eastern Bengal and Assam. In 1912 the lieutenant governor became governor, and in 1947 the province of Bengal was divided between India (as state of West Bengal) and Pakistan (as East Bengal, later independent Bangladash).

98

Bermuda (1609-

百慕大

百慕大（英）

The Bermuda Islands were discovered in about 1515 by the Spanish, but first settled in 1609 by the English sent by the Virginia Company. In 1615 it was sold to the Somers Islands Company which exercised control over the islands until 1684 when royal control was established. It remains a crown colony till now, with limited autonomy since 1968.

99

Bihar (1912-1947)

比哈尔

今属印度比哈尔邦

The East India Company acquired the rights to Bihar in 1765. Bihar remained part of Bengal until 1912 when the East Bengal-Assam province dissolved, Bihar and Orissa were detached and erected into a separate province of Bihar-Orissa under a lieutenant governor. In 1919 it became a governor’s province. When Orissa was detached in 1936, Bihar remained as a province until it became part of India in 1947.

100

Bombay (1662-1947)

孟买管辖区

今属印度马哈拉施特拉邦等

The island of Bombay on the western coast of India was ceded to Great Britain by Portugal in 1661. It was granted to the East India Company in 1668, and it replaced Surat as the chief British factory in India, although until 1687 the governor of Bombay continued to reside at Surat while governing Bombay through deputy governors. It was the centre of British authority in India until 1774 when replaced by Bengal. Bombay continued as a governor’s province until 1947 it became a part of India. From 1843 to 1936 Sind, and from 1839 to 1937 Aden was subject to Bombay.

101

British Columbia (1858-1871)

不列颠哥伦比亚

今加拿大不列颠哥伦比亚省

Vancouver Island off Canada’s western coast was granted to the Hudson’s Bay Company in 1849. The mainland known before 1858 as New Caledonia was settled from Vancouver Island and made a separate colony in 1858 with the same governor as Vancouver Islands. From 1864 to 1866 the two colonies were divided and then united as British Columbia. British Columbia became a province of the New Confederation of Canada.

102

British Guiana (1831-1970)

英属几内亚

今圭亚那

In 1803 Great Britain permanently occupied the Dutch Guianese settlements of Berbice, Demerara and Essequibo. In 1831 these colonies were united to form British Guiana. It became independent as Guyana in 1966.

103

British Honduras (1787-1981)

英属洪都拉斯

今伯里兹

The settlement on the Central American coast was governed by the superintendent of the Moskito Coast from 1740 to 1782, which was abandoned in 1786. The area around Belize was governed by a superintendent (before 1786 and from 1791 to 1797 by annual magistrates), in 1862 replaced by a lieutenant governor, and in 1884 finally by a governor. In 1954 British Honduras was granted semi-responsible government, and it was renamed Belize in 1983 and won its independence in 1981.

104

British Indian Ocean Territory (1810-

英属印度洋领地

英属印度洋领地

The Chagos Islands were first claimed by the French in 1665 when they settled Réunion. In 1786 the British claimed but only occupied this territory after Napoleon’s defeat in 1814. It became part of Mauritius until 1965 when it was detached to became the British Indian Ocean Territory. Its commissioner was the governor of the Seychelles Islands until 1976 when Seychelles became independent.

105

British Kaffraria (1847-1866)

英属卡夫拉里亚

今属南非开普省

As British authority extended eastward from the Cape Colony, the area just west of the River Kei was erected into a separate crown colony in 1847, called British Kaffraria. The colony was too small that consequently in 1866 it was annexed to the Cape Colony.

106

British New Guinea (1883-1975)

英属新几内亚

今属巴布亚新几内亚

British Territory of New Guinea was formerly German New Guinea in the northeastern part of the island, occupied by Australia in 1914. Between 1920 and 1942 Australia governed the area under a League of Nations mandate. New Guinea was occupied by the Japanese from 1942 to 1945 when Japan surrendered and Australian rule restored. Since then, New Guinea and Papua, the southeastern section of the island, were administered jointly as Papua New Guinea, which won independence in 1975.

107

British North Borneo (1762-1775,1877-1963)

英属北婆罗洲

今属马来西亚沙巴州

In 1877 and 1879 the territory later to comprise British North Borneo was ceded to a British syndicate by the sultan of Brunei. In 1882 the British North Borneo Company acquired the rights over the territory and in 1888 the British government formed a formal protectorate under the agreement that the company would continue to administer the area. After Japanese occupation during World War II, it was erected into a crown colony with Labuan attached to it. In 1963 it became a state of the Federation of Malaysia as Sabah.

108

British Solomon Islands (1893-1978)

英属所罗门群岛

今所罗门群岛

The Solomon Islands were discovered by the Spaniards in 1567. In 1893 Great Britiain assumed a protectorate over the southern islands, and in 1899 Germany ceded the northern islands to Britain in exchange for Samoa. A few of the westerly Solomon Islands were administered by Australia through British Territory of New Guinea. From 1942 to 1945 the islands were occupied by the Japanese. In 1953 the office of the Western Pacific High Commission was moved from Fiji to the British Solomon Islands, and the office of resident commissioner was abolished. In 1976 the Western Pacific High Commission was dissolved, and its commissioner became governor of Solomon Islands since 1974 and it gained its independence in 1978.

109

British Somaliland (1884-1960)

英属索马里兰

今属索马里

Great Britain established a protectorate over part of the Somali coast opposite Aden which has been occupied by the Egyptian troops from 1870 to 1884. A resident/political agent was appointed from Aden, an in 1898 Somaliland was transferred from the government of India to the Foreign Office and the political agent became consul general. In 1905 the Colonial Office assumed control and appointed administrators, which was replaced by commissioners in 1914. After 1919 British Somaliland was placed under a governor, although still kept as a protectorate. Briefly occupied by Italy in 1940 and 1941, British Somaliland became independent in 1960 and immediately untied with Italian Somaliland to form the new Republic of Somalia.

110

British Virgin Islands (1665-

英属维尔京群岛

英属维尔京群岛

Tortola, the most important of the British Virgin Islands, was settled by the Dutch between 1615 and 1625. The English claimed it in 1628, but only settled in 1645, but quickly destroyed by the Spaniards. The Dutch occupied in 1648 and was expelled by the English in 1672. The islands were included in the government of Leeward Islands until its dissolution in 1960, when it became a separate colony, which gained autonomous status by 1967.

111

Brunei (1888-1984)

文莱

文莱

In 1888 the sultan of Brunei surrendered the control of his external affairs to Great Britain and accepted as a British protectorate. After 1906 a British resident was appointed to Brunei (resided at Labuan until 1915), and it became high commissioner in 1959. Brunei remained out of the Malaya Federation and was finally gained independence in 1984.

112

Burma (1824-1948)

缅甸

今缅甸

Great Britain engaged a series of wars to occupy the Kingdom of Burma. Arakan in the northwest and Tenasserim in the south were annexed after the first Burma War of 1824-26. Pegu (north of Tenasserim) was annexed after the second Burma War of 1852 to 1853. In 1862 the three provinces were united to form Lower Burma. Finally in 1885 the core of the kingdom which was called Upper Burma by the British, was annexed and the whole was called Burma. Burma was part of British India until 1937 when it was separated and made a crown colony. It was occupied by the Japanese during World War II 1942-1945, and finally it became independence in 1946 and not a member of the Commonwealth.

113

Dominion of Canada (1867-1931)

加拿大

加拿大

Until 1758 the area of what was to become Canda was predominantly under the control of France. (Acadia, Île-Royale, Montreal, New France, and Plaisance). The British permanent control brgan in 1710 when they conquest and annexed Acadia (Nova Scotia). The British occupied all the French possessions during the Sever Years’ War and retained them by the 1763 Treaty of Paris. The Former New France (now under British, Quebec) was divided after 1791 as Upper Canada and Lower Canada, which were again united in 1841 as Province of Canada. The eastern provinces were governed as seprate colonies: Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, Cape Breton (absorbed into Nova Scotia in 1820), New Brunswick, and Newfoundland. The interest in a union was crystallized in 1867 with the Confederation of Upper and Lower Canada with New Brunswick and Nova Scotia. In 1869 the Hudson’s Bay Company sold its territory to Canada and in 1871 British Columbia joined Canada as well. Prince Edward Island joined the confederation in 1873, and Newfoundland in 1949. From the area acquired from the Hudson’s Bay Company, Manitoba was created in 1870, Alberta and Saskatchewan in 1905, and Northwest Territory and Yukon kept as territories. Canada was granted full sovereignty in the 1931 Statue of Westminster.

114

Cape Breton (1629, 1745-1749, 1758-1867)

布雷顿角

今属加拿大新斯科舍省

The Île Royale was briefly occupied by the English in 1629 and 1745-49. It was permanently occupied by the British in 1758 as Cape Breton, but it was only in 1784 that loyalists from the former American colonies to the south were allowed to settle there. At this time Cape Breton was created a separate colony and detached from Nova Scotia. This was reversed in 1820 however and Cape Breton was reunited to Nova Scotia.

115

Cape Colony (1795-1803, 1806-1910)

开普殖民地

今属南非

The Cape Colony, settled by the Dutch in 1652, was seized by the British in 1795, returned in 1803, and seized again permanently in 1806. From 1847 to 1901 the governor of the Cape Colony was also high commissioner for South Africa, which authorized authority over resident commissioners of Basutoland, Bechuanaland and Swaziland. In 1910 Cape Colony joined with Natal, Orange River Colony and Transvaal (the latter two annexed as a result of the Anglo-Boer War 1899-1902), to form the Union of South Africa.

116

Cayman Islands (1670-

开曼群岛

开曼群岛（英）

The Cayman Islands were ceded to the British by the Spaniards in 1670, and settlement from Jamaica began in 1734. Until 1900 they were locally governed by chief magistrates, from 1900 to 1962 by commissioners, from 1962 to 1971 by administrators and then from 1971 by governors. It was subject to Jamaica until 1962 became a separate colony.

117

Central Provinces and Berar (1861-1947)

中央省

今属印度中央邦

The British India annexed the Nagpur State in 1853 to create the Nagpur Province attached to Bengal, and merged it with the Saugor and Nerbudda Territories in 1861 to formed the Central Provinces. The Berar province of Hyderabad was administered by the British from 1853 and it was merged into the United Provinces in 1903 as Berar Division. In 1936 the province was renamed Central Provinces and Berar and it became part of India in 1947.

118

Ceylon (1796-1948)

锡兰

今斯里兰卡

In 1796 the British seized the Dutch possessions in Ceylon which was retained under the Treaty of Amiens. Until 1798 Ceylon was under military rule and administered as a part of the presidency of Madras. In 1798 it was granted a governor who was appointed by the crown but subject to the East India Company. This was lasted till 1802 when Ceylon became a crown colony. The inland kingdom of Kandy was conquered in 1815, and Ceylon remained a crown colony until 1948 when it became independent.

119

Connecticut (1639-1776)

康涅狄格

今美国康涅狄格州

Connecticut was founded in 1639 by settlers from Massachusetts Bay. In 1664 Connecticut absorbed the neighbouring New Haven. From 1687 to 1690 it was part of the Dominion of New England. In 1776 Connecticut severed its connection with Great Britain.

120

Cook Islands (1888-1900)

库克群岛

库克群岛（新）

The Cook Islands were discovered by the Spaniards in 1595 but named for the English explorer Jame Cook. In 1888 a protectorate was proclaimed and residents were appointed from New Zealand. In 1901 the Cook Islands became a dependency of New Zealand, led by a resident commissioner.

121

Coorg (1834-1947)

库格省

今属印度迈索尔邦

In 1834 the Kingdom of Coorg was annexed to British India. From 1834 to 1869 the commissioner of Mysore served as commissioner of Coorg. In 1869 it became a chief commissioner’s province (with commissioner, after 1881 resident, of Mysore serve as Coorg’s chief commissioner until 1940). In 1947 Coorg acceded to India.

122

Curaçao (1800-1803, 1807-1816)

库拉索岛

库拉索（荷） 

The Dutch colony of Curaçao was occupied by the British from 1800 to 1803 and 1807 to 1816.

123

Cyprus (1878-1960)

塞浦路斯

塞浦路斯

The island of Cyprus in the east Mediterranean was a part of the Ottoman Empire until 1878, and then it was handed over to Great Britain for administrative purposes.
