Only during the World War I in 1914 Cyprus was officially annexed to the British, and it became a crown colony in 1925. In 1960 Cyprus became an independent nation.

124

Delhi (1912-1947)

德里

今印度新德里 

Delhi was the capital of the Mughal Empire until its abolition in 1857. From 1857 to 1859 the area was under the North-West Provinces (United Provinces of Agra and Oudh), and from 1859 to 1912 it was under Punjab. In 1912 the capital of British India was transferred from Calcutta to Delhi and the area around the new capital was separated to create a chief commissioner’s province, Delhi. It remained so until 1947 India independence.

125

Dominica (1761-1778, 1784-1978)

多米尼克

多米尼克

Dominica was captured by the British in 1761 and made it part of the Windward Islands until 1771 and then became a separate colony. It was retaken by the French in 1777 but ceded to the British in 1783. In 1833 it became part of the Leeward Islands and remained so until 1940 when it was transferred to the Windward Islands. In 1960 the Windward Islands government was dissolved and Dominica became a separate colony. In 1967 Dominica became an associated State of the West Indies, and it gained independence in 1978.

126

Egypt (1801-1803, 1882-1922)

埃及

埃及

Egypt, an Ottoman province since 1517, was briefly occupied by the French (1798-1801) and the British (1801-1803), and then actually controlled by Muhammad Ali since 1805, still remained under the Ottoman Empire. In 1876 British and French controllers were appointed to stabilize the chaotic financial situation there. The confrontation with the Egyptian authority led to the invade by the British and French troops in 1882. The French withdrew the following year, but the British remained and a resident/consul-general was appointed, although Egypt maintained a nominal part of Ottoman. In 1914 when the Ottoman joined World War I on the side against the British, Great Britain proclaimed a protectorate over Egypt and appointed a high commissioner. The protectorate ended in 1922 and Egypt was proclaimed a sovereign and independent kingdom.

127

Falkland Islands (1766-1774, 1814-

福克兰群岛

福克兰群岛（英） 

The British planted a small garrison on West Falkland Island in 1766 but abandoned in 1774 after a dispute with the Spaniards and the latter occupied the whole Falkland Islands. After a brief Argentinian occupation the British reclaimed the islands in 1832. It was administered by a naval office-in-charge until 1841, when a lieutenant governor was appointed (from 1843, governor). The Falkland Islands remained a crown colony although a brief occupation by Argentina in 1982 caused the Falklands War.

128

Federated Malay States (1895-1946)

马来联邦

今属马来西亚

British residents were introduced into Pahang, Perak and Selangor in 1874, and into Negri Sembilan in 1889. The four states formed a federation in 1895 at the head of which was a resident-general. The title was changed to chief secretary in 1911, and federal secretary in 1936. In each instance these officials were under the authority of the governor of the Straits Settlements. All of the Malaya was occupied by the Japanese during World War II and when the British reoccupied the region the Federated Malay States ws not revived, and the four composing states all joined the new Union of Malaya.

129

Fiji (1874-1970)

斐济

斐济

The ruler of Bau, offered the islands of Fiji to Great Britain in 1858 but was officially rejected by 1862. In 1871 Fiji became a kingdom, finally it was offered to the British again by its own king in 1874 and became a crown colony. From 1877 to 1952 the governor of Fiji was also high commissioner for the Western Pacific. Fiji gained its independence in 1970 and became a republic in 1987.

130

East Florida and West Florida (1763-1783)

佛罗里达

今属美国佛罗里达州

The Spanish colony of Florida was ceded to Great Britain at the end of the Seven Years’ War in 1763. It was divided into East and West Florida by the British, but it was re-occupied by the Spaniards in 1780-81 and officially retroceded to Spain in 1893 Treaty of Paris.

131

Fort William (1700-1758)

威廉堡（孟加拉管辖区前身）

今属印度

British factories were established on the site of Calcutta in 1690, and 10 years later this post was raised to a presidency named Fort William. The control of this region kept expanding and after defeating the subahdar in 1757, Great Britain gained effective control of the whole province of Bengal.

132

The Gambia (1661-1695, 1713-1779, 1816-1965)

冈比亚

冈比亚 

In 1661 the English seized the port at the mouth of the Gambia River built by the Duke of Kurland 10 years ago, and built its own post named James Fort. The French occupied it between 1695 and 1709, and the British abandoned it 1709-1713. From 1713 to 1766 it was under the jurisdiction of various chartered companies, and then it fell under the new colony of Senegambia from 1766 to 1779 until Senegambia was occupied by the French. The British rule of Fort James was finally confirmed by France in 1816, and the area became part of Sierra Leone 1821-1843, a separate colony from 1843 to 1866, and then part of the government of West Africa Settlements centered at Sierra Leone from 1866 to 1888, which also included Lagos and the Gold Coast. The upriver area was proclaimed Gambia Protectorate in 1894 and put under the Gambia colony until 1935 when the protectorate was partitioned into divisions under the Gambia. The Gambia became independent in 1965 and a republic in 1970.

133

Georgia (1732-1777)

佐治亚

今美国佐治亚州

The first colonists arrived in Georgia in 1732 to create a proprietary colony. It became a royal colony in 1754. The British was expelled in 1776, but reoccupied it from 1779 and 1782 and then finally abandoned it to the United States.

134

Gibraltar (1704-

直布罗陀

直布罗陀（英）

The fortress of Gibraltar was captured by the British in 1704 during the War of the Spanish Succession, and retained by the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht. It was granted a responsible government in 1964.

135

Gilbert and Ellice Islands (1892-1979)

吉尔伯特和埃利斯群岛

今基里巴斯和图瓦卢

The Gilbert and Ellice Islands came under the general supervision of the Western Pacific High Commission and were made a protectorate in 1892. At the request of the native rulers the islands were annexed as a crown colony in 1915. From 1916 to 1976 the islands were under the authority of the high commissioner for the Western Pacific. From 1941 to 1943 the Gilbert Islands were occupied by the Japanese. In 1975 the Ellice Islands were separated and won its independence in 1978 as Tuvalu. In 1979 the Gilbert Islands won its independence in 1979 as Kiribati.

136

Gold Coast (1621-1960)

黄金海岸

今属加纳

From 1632 to 1665 the chief post of the English along the Guinea coast of West Africa was Kormantin, afterwards it was moved to Cape Coast Castle. Until 1821 these posts were under various companies and then they were assumed direct control from the crown under Sierra Leone. In 1850 the nearby Danish settlement were purchased and combined under Sierra Leone also. From 1866 to 1874 the Gold Coast were part of the West Africa Settlement centred in Sierra Leone. In 1874 the colony of the Gold Coast was erected with Lagos subordinate to it until 1886. In 1951 it was granted a large degree of self-government. Gold Coast became the first independent African member of the British Commonwealth as Ghana, and it became a republic in 1960.

137

Gold Coast, Northern Territories (1899-1957)

黄金海岸北方领地

今属加纳

The area of the Gold Coast north of Ashanti began to be occupied and administratively organized in 1899 and was fully organized in 1906. In 1953 the chief commissioner was replaced by a regional officer. On the independence of the Gold Coast in 1957, the office was abolished.

138

Gold Coast Colony (1945-1953)

黄金海岸殖民地

今属加纳

The Gold Coast Colony region, alone the coast south of Ashanti, was created as a separate region within Gold Coast in 1945 under a chief commissioner. It was abolished in 1953.

139

Grenada (1609, 1762-1779, 1783-1974)

格林纳达

格林纳达

Grenada, one of the Lesser Antilles, was discovered by Columbus in 1498. The attempt to settle by the English failed in 1609, and it was settled by the French in 1650 until its capture by the British in 1762. Grenada was a member of the Southern Caribbee Islands government until 1779 when it was captured by the French again, and it was returned to the British in 1783. From 1833 to 1885 Grenada was included in the Windward Islands government centered in Barbados. It became the seat of the governor of the Windward Islands in 1885 when Barbados was created a separate colony, and the colonial secretary of the Windward Islands government served as administrator of Grenada until 1944. Grenada remained in the Windward Islands until its dissolution in 1960 when it became a separate colony. It became an Associated States in 1967 and won its independence in 1974.

140

Griqualand West (1871-1880)

西格里夸兰

今属南非开普省 

The area of Griqualand West was disputed between the Cape Colony and the Boer Republic of Transvaal due to the diamond discovery in 1867. In 1871 it was arbitrated that most of the area went to Cape Colony and the governor of the Cape Colony became ex officio governor of Griqualand West. In 1880 Griqualand was finally annexed to the Cape Colony.

141

Guadeloupe (1759-1763, 1794, 1810-1814, 1815-16)

瓜德罗普

瓜德罗普（法）

Great Britain occupied the French colony of Guadeloupe from 1759 to 1763 and 1810 to 1814.

142

Heligoland (1807-1890, 1945-1952)

黑尔格兰岛

今属德国石勒苏益格-赫尔施泰因州

Heligoland, a small island in the North Sea off the northwestern coast of Germany, was seized by Great Britain from Denmark in 1807, and formally ceded in 1814. The island remained a colony of the British until 1890 when it was given to Germany in return for a freehand in Zanzibar and other concessions in Africa.

143

Hong Kong (1841-1997)

香港

今中国香港特别行政区

Great Britain seized the island of Hong Kong in 1841, and the neighbouring Kowloon Peninsula in 1860. It remained a crown colony after the Japanese occupation during World War II, and finally returned back to China in 1997.

144

Hudson’s Bay Company (1670-1869)

哈德逊湾公司

今北美地区

The Hudson’s Bay Company was formed in 1670 to explore the fur trade of Canada. It kept fighting with the French until 1763 when the French were fully expelled from North America. After merging the competitor North West Company in 1821, the Hudson’s Bay Company soon appointed a governor-in-chief to rule over the lands it owned. In 1869 the Hudson’s Bay Company sold rights of all its lands to the new Dominion of Canada and after that it existed as a commercial corporation only.

145

India (1858-1947)

印度

印度

British posts along the coasts of modern India were established begin in the 17th century, like Bombay, Fort William, Madras, and Surat. Between 1757 and 1765 all of Bengal and Bihar came under British rule. In 1774 the governor of Bengal was given authority, as governor-general, over all British possessions in India. By 1818 all of India except Punjab was controlled by Great Britain, or the East India Company. Punjab was added in 1846 and 1849. After the 1858 rebellion was cracked, the British crown took over the whole administration of India. Between 1860 and 1900 the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, Baluchistan, Burma, and North-West Frontier Provinces were added into India possessions, while the Straits Settlements were detached in 1867. The provinces of British India included Ajmer-Merwara, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, Assam, Baluchistan, Bengal, Bihar, Bombay, Burma (to 1937), the Central Provinces and Berar, Coorg, Delhi, Madras, North-West Frontier Provinces, Orissa, Oudh (to 1877), Punjab, Sind and the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh. They were governed by governors, lietenant governors, or chief commissioners. India itself was administered by the India Office therefore distinct from other colonies which were under the Colonial Office. British India became independent in 1947, divided into Hindu dominated India and Muslin dominated Pakistan.

146

Ionian Islands (1809-1864)

伊奥尼亚群岛

今属希腊

The seven islands of Cephalonia, Cerigo (Kythira), Corfu, Ithaca, Leucas, Paxo and Zante located in the Ionian Sea off the coast of western Grece were occupied by Venice until 1797 when they were ceded to France. In 1799 Russia occupied the islands and created the Septinsular Republic in 1800 under its protection. Surrenderred to France by the Treaty of Tilsit in 1807 they were ceded to France again. The Ionian Islands were occupied by Great Britain in 1809, who established a protectorate of its own until 1864 when they ceded the islands back to Greece.

147

Iraq (1916-1935)

伊拉克

伊拉克

The area of Mesopotamia came under British control during World War I. After the war, the area now known as Iraq was granted to the British as a mandate by the League of Nations. Iraq was virtually independent although a high commissioner was appointed who advised the Iraqi king. Finally in 1932 the mandate was terminated and Iraq became fully independent.

148

Irish Free State (1922-1937)

爱尔兰自由邦

爱尔兰

The Easter Rebellion of 1916 resulted a civil and it was only ended in 1921 by a treaty which Ireland was granted dominion status as the Free Irish State. This proved to be unsuitable which solved nothing and satisfied no one. The office of the governor-general was abolished in 1936, replaced by a president. In 1949 it formally withdrew from the Commonwealth and proclaimed a republic.

149

Jamaica (1655-1962)

牙买加

牙买加

Jamaica, the largest British possession in the West Indies, was under the Spanish until 1655, and it began to serve as a headquarter for English raids on other Spanish possessions around the Caribbean Sea. Jamaica had a representative government but it was withdrawn from 1866 to 1944. The governor of Jamaica was ex officio governor of the Bay Islands from 1852 to 1861. The Cayman Islands from 1734 to 1962, and the Turks and Caicos Islands from 1874 to 1962 were dependencies of Jamaica. Jamaica was the principle member of the West Indies Federation from 1958 to 1961, and gained its independence in 1962.

150

Java (1811-1816)

爪哇

今属印度尼西亚 

Great Britain occupied the island of Java (Netherlands East Indies) from 1811 to 1816.

151

Kenya (1920-1963)

肯尼亚

肯尼亚 

The Anglo-German Agreement of 1886 designated the area later known as Kenya to be within the projected British sphere. In 1887 the sultan of Zanzibar conceded to the Imperial British East Africa Company the administration of whatever mainland claims remained to him after the creation of German East Africa. A British protectorate was proclaimed over the sultanate of Witu in 1890, and another for the I.B.E.A area in 1894. In 1895 the Foreign Office assumed control of the company’s possessions in East Africa known as East Africa Protectorate, and a commissioner was appointed who was also, until 1904, the consul-general in Zanzibar. In 1906 the control was transferred to the Colonial Office and a governor appointed. A crown colony with the name Kenya was created from the area of the East Africa Protectorate. Kenya became independent in 1963 and it was proclaimed a republic in 1964.

152

Kuwait (1899-1961)

科威特

科威特

The sheikhdom of Kuwait was nominally under the jurisdiction of the Ottoman authorities at Basra during the 19th century. The sheikh recognized the protection of the British in 1904 in order to free himself from Ottoman. A political agent was appointed who was subject to the authority of the British chief political resident of the Persian Gulf. The protected status of Kuwait was terminated in 1961 and it became fully independent.

153

Labuan (1846-1963)

纳闽

今属马来西亚 

The British attempted to settle the island of Labuan in the north coast of Borneo in 1775 but failed. In 1846 it was ceded to the British by the sultan of Brunei, and became a crown colony in 1848. In 1890 it was entrusted to the control of the British North Borneo Company, and in 1907 it was annexed to the Strait Settlements.

154

Leeward Islands (1671-1816, 1833-1960)

背风群岛

含今波多黎各的库莱布拉岛和别克斯岛（时西属维尔京群岛）、英属维尔京群岛、安圭拉（英）、圣马丁（法）、圣马丁（荷）、圣巴泰勒米（法）、萨巴（荷）、圣尤斯特歇斯（荷）、圣基茨和尼维斯、安提瓜和巴布达、蒙特塞拉特（英）、瓜德罗普（法）

The scattered British possessions in the Lesser Antilles were organized into the Leeward Islands government in 1671. These included Antigua, Montserrat, British Virgin Islands, Saint Kitts, Nevis, Barbuda and Anguilla. The Leeward Islands were divided into two separate administration units (Antigua-Montserrat-Barbuda and Saint Kitts-Nevis-Anguilla-British Virgin Islands) between 1816 and 1833, and then were united again, with Dominica, which acquired in 1761, added. From 1871 the Leeward Islands was a federal colony. The Leeward Islands government, together with its counterpart the Windward Islands government, was abolished and its constituent parts became separate colonies.

155

Madras (1640-1947)

马德拉斯管辖区

含今印度泰米尔纳德邦等

The headquarters of English commercial interests along the India’s Coromandel coast was Masulipatam from 1611 to 1841 when it was moved to Madras. Until 1652 Madras was under Bantam in Java. In 1652 Madras was raised to the rank of a presidency but it lapsed to agency status in 1655. Madras again became a presidency in 1684. It was occupied by France from 1746 to 1749, and the presidency was moved to Fort St. David new Cuddalore. In 1947 Madras became part of India.

156

Malaya (1948-1963)

马来亚

今属马来西亚 

Before 1942 the British possessions in Malaya were governed by the governor of the Straits Settlements who served as high commissioner of the Unfederated Malay States as well as having jurisdiction over the chief secretaries of the Federated Malay States. In 1946 these governments were abolished and replaced by the Union of Malaya, with the exception that Singapore as a separate colony. Meanwhile the office of governor-general of Malaya existed with jurisdiction over Malaya, Singapore, British North Borneo, Sarawak and Brunei. In 1948 the Union of Malaya was replaced by the Federation of Malaya and the governor became high commissioner, whose jurisdiction was all of Southeast Asia. Malaya became a self-governing dominion, and it united with other former British colonies to form Malaysia in 1963 and became independent.

157

Malta (1800-1964)

马耳他

马耳他

The colony of Malta consisted of the islands of Malta, Gozo and Comino. Malta was under the Knights of Jerusalem until 1798 when it was conquered by Napoleon. The British occupied Malta in 1799-1800. While the 1802 Treaty of Amiens provided for the return, but it was never implemented, and they were permanently annexed by Great Britain in 1814 by Treaty of Paris. It was governed by a civil commissioner until 1813, a military governor until 1847, then a civil governor. Malta was a crown colony until 1921 when it was given a self-representative government. It reverted to crown colony status in 1933, gained its independence in 1964, and became a republic in 1974.

158

Martinique (1762-1763, 1794-1802, 1809-1814, 1815-16)

马提尼克

马提尼克（法）

Great Britain occupied the French colony of Martinique from 1762 to 1763, 1794 to 1802 and 1809 to 1814.

159

Maryland (1632-1776)

马里兰

今美国马里兰州

The area of Maryland was created in 1632 from part of the area granted Virginia earlier. It was colonized in 1634. Part of Maryland was lost when the colony of Pennsylvania was created in 1681. Maryland was a proprietary colony 1632-1691, and again 1716 to 1776. In 1776 Maryland expelled its governor and terminated its status as a British colony.

160

Massachusetts Bay (1629-1775)

马萨诸塞湾

今美国马萨诸塞州

Massachusetts Bay was colonized in 1629. After 1668 it governed Maine. New Hampshire was under Massachusetts Bay until 1680, and from 1682 to 1741. In 1684 Massachusetts Bay became a royal colony and it was part of the Dominion of New England from 1686 to 1689. In 1692 Massachusetts Bay absorbed its neighbor New Plymouth and became known as Massachusetts. In 1775 Massachusetts expelled its last royal governor.

161

Mauritius (1810-1968)

毛里求斯

毛里求斯

The island of Mauritius was previously occupied by the Dutch and the French. The British seized it during the Napoleonic Wars in 1810, and retained it after 1814. From 1810 to 1903 the Seychelles was a dependency of Mauritius. In 1968 Mauritius became independent.

162

Minorca (1708-1756, 1763-1782, 1798-1802)

梅诺卡岛

今属西班牙巴利阿里群岛

Minorca, the most easterly of the Balearic Islands in the western Mediterranean, was seized from Spain by Great Britain in 1708, and retained so by the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht. It was captured by the French in 1756 but returned to Great Britain in 1763. The island was surrendered to Spain in 1782, recovered in 1798, and finally ceded to Spain in 1802.

163

Montserrat (1632-1667, 1668-1782, 1784-

蒙特塞拉特

蒙特塞拉特（英）

The island of Montserrat in the Lesser Antilles was discovered by Columbus in 1493, was settled by the English from Saint Kitts in 1632, and became part of the Leeward Islands government in 1671. In 1667 and from 1782 to 1784 Montserrat was occupied by the French. From 1854 administrators, and later, commissioners, governed the island. It remained part of the Leeward Island until its dissolution in 1960. It remained a separate colony.

164

Moskito Coast (1658-1860)

莫斯基托斯海岸线

今属尼加拉瓜

The area known as the Moskito Coast, situated along the eastern coast of nowadays Nicaragua, was ceded to the British in 1740 by a native ruler. A superintendent was appointed to supervise the settlements and this office was abolished in 1782 as the British interest in Central America now moved to British Honduras (now Belize). A shadowy protectorate was maintained by Great Britain over this area until 1860 when it was transferred to Nicaragua.

165

Natal (1843-1910)

纳塔尔

今属南非纳塔尔省

The colony of Natal was established in 1843, but was granted responsible government only in 1893. Zululand and Tongaland were incorporated into the colony in 1897. Natal, together with the Orange River Colony, Transvaal, and the Cape Colony united in 1910 to form the Union of South Africa.

166

Nauru (1920-1968)

瑙鲁

瑙鲁

Nauru was administered by Germany as part of the Marshall Islands under German New Guinea from 1888 to 1914. It was seized by Australian forces in 1914, and was under the administration of the Western Pacific High Commission until 1921. In 1921 it was granted a League of Nations mandate jointly to Great Britain, New Zealand, and Australia, although solely administered by Australia. From 1942 to 1945 it was occupied by the Japanese. Nauru was administered by Australia as a United Nations trustship and became independent in 1968.

167

Nevis (1628-1782, 1783-1883)

尼维斯

今属圣基茨和尼维斯

Nevis, adjacent to the island of Saint Kitts, was discovered by Columbus in 1493 and settled by the English from Saint Kitts in 1628. In 1671 it became part of the Leeward Islands government and was administered by deputy or lieutenant governors. Nevis was briefly occupied by the French in 1706 and from 1782 to 1783. Nevis continued to remain nominally separated from Saint Kitts until 1882 when it was untied with the latter to form the government of Saint Kitts-Nevis-Anguilla.

168

New Brunswick (1784-1867)

新不伦瑞克

今加拿大新不伦瑞克省

New Brunswick was part of the French colony of Acadia until 1710 and thereafter of Nova Scotia. In 1784 New Brunswick was detached from Nova Scotia and erected into a separate colony, and in 1867 it became a charter member of the Confederation of Canada.

169

Newfoundland (1583-1949)

纽芬兰

今加拿大纽芬兰和拉布拉多省

An English attempt to colonize the island in 1583 failed but in 1610 the Company of Adventurers and Planters of London and Bristol for the Colony or Plantations of Newfoundland was formed. There’re other settlements established in the following years. It was decided in 1675 to remove all colonists but this was soon rescinded as France built a colony at Plaisance which threated the British influence. From 1675 the Newfoundland settlements were supervised by the commodores of the annual fishing convoys. The French colony of Plaisance was surrendered to Great Britain by the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht. After 1700 there were resident lieutenant governors, and after 1729 civil government was instituted and a royal governor appointed. In 1818 the first resident governor was appointed, and Newfoundland was raised to full colonial status. Labrador was ceded by France by the Treaty of Paris in 1763, and was included into Newfoundland. Responsible government was instituted in 1855, but Newfoundland did not confederate into Canada in 1867 and remained a separate colony. In 1918 Newfoundland acquired dominion status but it was in suspension since 1934. A commission replaced the cabinet until 1949 when Newfoundland became Canada’s tenth province and the cabinet government got restored.

170

New Hampshire (1680-1776)

新罕布什尔

今美国新罕布什尔州

Settlement in now New Hampshire from Massachusetts Bay began in 1630. Until 1680, and from 1692 to 1741, it was governed from Massachusetts. From 1699 to 1741 the governor of Massachusetts was also governor of New Hampshire. Between 1680 to 1692, and between 1741 and 1776, New Hampshire was a separate colony of Great Britain, governors appointed by the crown.

171

New Haven (1638-1664)

纽黑文

今属美国康涅狄格州等

The colony of New Haven was settled in 1638 from Massachusetts Bay. A separate colonial government was established in 1643. Controversies with New York and the small size of the colony led to its annexation into Connecticut in 1664.

172

New Hebrides Condominium (1887-1980)

新赫布里底群岛共管地

今瓦努阿图

A joint Anglo-French Naval Commission was formed in 1887 as there’s no solution to the ownership of the New Hebrides Islands. The commission governed the islands until 1902, and then a formal condominium was established in 1906. For the condominium, the British resident commissioner was appointed by the high commissioner for the Western Pacific High Commission, while the French resident commissioner was appointed by the French high commissioner at New Caledonia. It was the only true example of a condominium by the various European colonial powers, and it lasted till 1980 when it gained independence as Vanuatu.

173

New Jersey (1665-1674, 1702-1776)

新泽西

今美国新泽西州

The area of New Jersey was included in the grant given to James, Duke of York, in 1664. New Jersey was divided into the provinces of East New Jersey and West New Jersey from 1676 to 1702. From 1702 to 1741 the governor of New York served as governor of New Jersey. The last royal governor was expelled in 1776.

174

New Munster (1848-1853)

新芒斯特省

今属新西兰

New Zealand was divided administratively into New Munster, which included part of North Island, and New Ulster, which included the remainder of North Island and all of South Island. This experiment proved unsuccessful and the two provinces were abolished in 1853.

175

New Plymouth (1620-1692)

新普利茅斯

今属美国马萨诸塞州

New Plymouth in Massachusetts was settled in 1620 by the British, early than the colony of Massachusetts Bay. It was absorbed into Massachusetts in 1692.

176

New South Wales (1788-1900)

新南威尔士

今澳大利亚新南威尔士州 

The area of New South Wales was discovered and named by James Cook in 1770. In 1788 it became the site of the first British colony in Australia, which was in fact a penal colony. Effective settlement took place after 1810, and it originally included the whole continent except Western Australia and New Zealand. However new colonies were created in the following years: Tasmania detached in 1825, South Australia in 1836, New Zealand in 1841, Victoria in 1851, Queensland in 1859, and Northern Australia (placed under Soth Australia) in 1863. In 1901 New South Wales joined the Commonwealth of Australia, and in 1911 the Australian National Capital Territory was carved from New South Wales.

177

New Ulster (1848-1853)

新阿尔斯特省

今属新西兰

New Zealand was divided administratively into New Munster, which included part of North Island, and New Ulster, which included the remainder of North Island and all of South Island. This experiment proved unsuccessful and the two provinces were abolished in 1853.

178

New York (1664-1776)

纽约

今美国纽约州

The Dutch colony of New Netherlands alone the Hudson River was seized by the British in 1664, and it was granted to James, Duke of York, the brother of Charles II. The colony was retained by the 1667 Treaty of Breda, and it was briefly occupied by the Dutch again between 1673 and 1674. New York was part of the Dominion of New England 1688-1689, and then it fell under royal control. New York became part of the United States although New York City was not surrendered until 1783.

179

New Zealand (1769-1931)

新西兰

新西兰

New Zealand islands were annexed by James Cook in 1769 but his action was disregarded by the British authorities. Only in 1840 the British government dispatched a governor who signed the Treaty of Waitangi with several Maori chiefs who acknowledged the sovereignty of the British crown. In 1841 New Zealand was proclaimed a crown colony, and quickly following a series of wars the entire area of both islands were included. New Zealand was briefly divided into New Munster and New Ulster between 1848 to 1853. New Zealand received dominion status in 1907, and gained sovereignty through Statute of Westminster in 1931. New Zealand began administering the Cook Islands in 1888 and Niue in 1901.

180

Nigeria (1914-1960)

尼日利亚

尼日利亚

Until 1847 the British interest in the region was maintained by and under the responsibility of the anti-slavery patrols of Great Britain’s West African Squadron, operating from Fernando Po. In 1849 a consul was appointed for the Bight of Biafra, or the eastern part of Nigeria’s coast. Two years later a protectorate was established over the coastal state of Lagos, and in 1852 another consul was appointed for the Bight of Benin with headquarter at Lagos. In 1862 Lagos was annexed as a crown colony and the governor of Lagos acted as consul for the Bight of Benin until 1867 when the consul for the Bight of Biafra added it to his charge. (These consuls resided at Fernando Po until 1873, then at Old Calabar to 1875, then Fernando Po again to 1882, and Old Calabar again.) From 1866 to 1874 Lagos was part of the West Africa Settlements, and from 1874 to 1886 it was subordinate to the Gold Coast. In 1885 the Bights of Biafra and Benin became the Oil Rivers Protectorate and in 1891 the consul became commissioner. In 1893 this protectorate was extended inland and its name changed to the Niger Coast Protectorate. In 1900 the coastal territory of the Royal Niger Company was added to the Niger Coast Protectorate and combined into the Protectorate of Southern Nigeria. In 1906 Lagos was added to this to create the Colony and Protectorate of Southern Nigeria. Meanwhile also in 1910 the interior lands of the Royal Niger Company was formed into the Protectorate of Northern Nigeria. In 1914 the two areas merged into the Colony and Protectorate of Nigeria, and the two former areas were entrusted to lieutenant governors and later commissioners. In 1939 Sothern Nigeria was divided into as an eastern and a western region, and thus made Nigeria administratively divided into three areas. Nigeria became independent in 1960 and became a republic in 1963. A small part of the German colony of Kamerun that had been mandated to Great Britain after World War I was attached to Nigeria and remained so after Nigeria’s independence.

181

Niue (1900-1901)

纽埃

纽埃岛（新西兰）

Niue Island, 300 miles east of Tonga, was discovered by James Cook in 1884 and the inhabitants requested British protection in 1887. A protectorate was proclaimed in 1900 and it was annexed to New Zealand in 1901.

182

Norfolk Island (1788-1914)

诺福克群岛

诺福克群岛（英）

Norfolk Island , between New Zealand and New Caledonia, was discovered by James Cook in 1774. It was used as a convict settlement by New South Wales from 1788 to 1844, and by Tasmania from 1844 to 1856. In 1856 the administration was reverted to New South Wales, and the convict settlement was dissolved and the islands was resettled from Pitcairn Island. In 1914 it became a national territory of Australia.

183

North Carolina (1712-1776)

北卡罗来纳

今美国北卡罗来纳州

Roanoke Island off the coast of North Carolina became the site of the first English colony in North America in 1585 but soon abandoned. In 1663 King Charles II granted Carolina, which included both North and South Carolina, to eight lords proprietors. the northern part of this grant was under Carolina and was ruled by deputy governors. The proprietary control was revoked in 1729 and royal government substituted. In 1775 the last royal governor was expelled.

184

Northern Australia (1824-1829, 1838-1849, 1864-1910)

北方领地

今澳大利亚北领地

The first settlement in the area of Northern Australia took place in 1824 by abandoned in 1829, and also from 1838 to 1849. A territorial government was created in 1863 and Northern Australia, which has hitherto been under New South Wales, was placed under South Australia, where it remained until 1911 when it became a national territory.

185

Northern Rhodesia (1900-1964)

北罗得西亚

今赞比亚

Northern Rhodesia fell within the territory included in the charter of the British South African Company. The area was divided into North-Eastern Rhodesia and North-Western Rhodesia until 1911, when the two were combined to form Northern Rhodesia. It continued to be under the British South African Company until 1924 when it became a crown colony. From 1953 to 1963 Northern Rhodesia formed, with Southern Rhodesia and Nyasaland, the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland. After the dissolution of the federation, Northern Rhodesia became independent as Zambia in 1964.

186

North-West Frontier Province (1901-1947)

西北边境省

今属巴基斯坦开伯尔-普什图省

A separate province in the northwestern area of India was created in 1901 as the North-West Frontier Province. In 1932 it became a governor’s province. In 1947 it became a part of Pakistan.

187

Nova Scotia (1654-1670, 1690-1691, 1710-1867)

新斯科舍

今加拿大新斯科舍省

Nova Scotia, at the eastern tip of Canada, was discovered by John Cabot in 1497. From 1604 to 1710 the French colony of Acadia was located there, although the English occupied the colony from 1629 to 1632 and again from 1654 to 1670. The British conquered Acadia in 1710 but it was only informally administered until 1749. From 1763 to 1769 Prince Edward Island was part of Nova Scotia, and from 1763 to 1784 and from 1820 Cape Breton was attached to Nova Scotia. In 1848 Nova Scotia got a responsible government, and in 1867 it became an original member of the new Confederation of Canada.

188

Nyasaland (1889-1964)

尼亚萨兰

今马拉维

British interests in the area around Lake Nyasa in southeastern Africa began after 1874 with missionary activities. A consul was appointed in 1883 and a protectorate of Shire Highlands was proclaimed in 1889, and renamed Nyasaland Districts in 1891. The name was changed to the British Central African Protectorate in 1893 and the area was expanded to include the western shore of the lake. The name was changed back to Nyasaland in 1907 when the consul-general was replaced by a governor. From 1953 to 1963 it joined with Northern Rhodesia and Southern Rhodesia to form the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland. After the dissolution of the federation, Nyasaland became independent as Malawi in 1964, and a republic in 1966.

189

Orange River Colony (1845-1854, 1900-1910)

奥兰治自由邦

今属南非自由邦省

In 1848 the area north of the Orange River was annexed by the governor of Cape Colony and administered by a resident appointed from Cape Town. This annexation got abortive and the British sovereignty was transferred to the Boers in 1854 who established the Orange Free State. This state was occupied and annexed as a result of the Anglo-Boer War of 1899-1902 and was renamed the Orange River Colony. The high commissioner for South Africa, who was also governor of the Cape Colony, served as governor of the Orange River Colony, while a lieutenant governor administered the colony. In 1907 responsible government was granted and the lieutenant governor became governor. In 1910 it became part of the Union of South Africa.

190

Orissa (1936-1947)

奥里萨

今印度奥里萨邦 

The area of Orissa, southwest of Bengal, was occupied by the British after 1803. Until 1912 it was part of Bengal and then until 1936 of Bihar. In 1936 Orissa became a separate province and in 1947 it became a state of independent India.

191

Oudh (1856-1877)

奥德土邦

今属印度北方邦

The kingdom of Oudh in northern India was annexed to the British crown in 1856, and a chief commissioner was appointed to administer the area. Oudh remained a separate province until 1877 when it was amalgamated with Agra to form the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh.

192

Palestine (1918-1948)

巴勒斯坦

巴勒斯坦

At the end of World War I the non-Anatolian Asian part of the Ottoman Empire was parcelled out as mandates and Palestine fell to Britain’s lot. In 1948 independent Israel was proclaimed and the British high commissioner departed.

193

Papua (1883-1901)

巴布亚

今属巴布亚新几内亚

Papua, the southeastern part of New Guinea, was annexed to the Australian colony of Queensland in 1883. In 1888 it was annexed to Great Britain under the name British New Guinea. In 1906 it was made a territory of Australia and renamed Papua. After the Japanese occupation during World War II, it combined with British New Guinea in 1949 to form Papua and New Guinea. It was renamed Papua New Guinea in 1971 and became indepdenent in 1975.

194

Penang (1786-1957)

槟城

今属马来西亚

The sultan of Kedah ceded the small island of Penang off the northwestern coast of the Malay Peninsula to the British in 1786, and it was first called Prince of Wales Island. In 1800 the mainland territory opposite called Province Wellesley was purchased. In 1805 it was raised to the status of a presidency. The British secured Singapore in 1824 and two years later Penang, Singapore and Malacca were united to form the Straits Settlements.

195

Pennsylvania (1681-1776)

宾西法尼亚

今美国宾夕法尼亚州

The area of Pennsylvania was settled earlier 17th century by both the Swedes (New Sweden) and the Dutch (New Netherlands). Pennsylvania was originally included in the charter given to James, Duke of York, in 1664 (New York), and the area was detached from New York and granted as a proprietary to William Penn in 1681. It remained a proprietary province under the Penn family until 1776 when the lieutenant governor appointed by the proprietors was expelled.

196

Persian Gulf (1763-1971)

波斯湾

今波斯湾诸国

The East India Company began trading in the Persian Gulf after 1614. A residency was established at Bushir in 1763 and later another at Basra. In 1822 these were amalgamated to form the Persian Gulf residency. From 1822 to 1873 it was subordinate to the governor of Bombay, and from 1873 to 1947 to the viceroy of India. The resident resided at Bushir until 1946 when the headquarter was moved to Bahrain. The states of Bahrain and Kuwait were taken under British protection and political agents appointed, and the British representatives in Qatar, the Trucial Sheighdoms and Omen were also subordinate to the chief resident. All the British protection ended in 1971 and the post of chief resident was formally abolished in 1972.

197

Pitcairn Island (1790-

皮特凯恩岛

皮特凯恩岛（英）

Pitcairn Island in the east-central Pacific Ocean was discovered by the English explorer Philip Carteret in 1767. In 1790 it was settled by mutineers from H.M.S. Bounty. It was governed by annually elected chief magistrates since 1838, which was replaced by the president of the council from 1897 to 1904 and then the chief magistrates restored until 1999 when it was replaced by a mayor. In 1838 it was instituted as an unofficial protectorate, and in 1898 it was formally brought within the jurisdiction of the Western Pacific High Commission until 1952 when the responsibility was transferred to the governor of Fiji. In 1970 Pitcairn Island became a separate colony.

198

Prince Edward Island (1758-1873)

爱德华王子岛

今加拿大爱德华王子岛省

Prince Edward Island was first occupied by the French (Île Saint-Jean) until its seizure by the English in 1758. It was part of Nova Scotia until 1769 when it was created a separate colony. Prince Edward Island was granted responsible government in 1851, and it only joined the Confederation of Canada in 1873.

199

Providence (1630-1641)

普罗维登斯

今属哥伦比亚圣安德烈斯-普罗维登西亚和圣卡塔丽娜省

The island of Providence located in the southwestern Caribbean off the coast of Nicaragua was settled by the Providence Company in 1630. It was taken by a Spanish expedition from Cartagena in 1641. The English briefly recaptured it in 1665 but was retaken by the Spaniard within a year, and became part of the Spanish colony of Santa Catalina.

200

Punjab (1849-1947)

旁遮普

今属印度旁遮普邦和巴基斯坦旁遮普省

As a result of the Frist Sikh War the eastern part of Punjab (under the Sikh Kingdom) was annexed to British India in 1846, and the remainder annexed in 1849. Until 1856 Punjab was ruled by a Board of Administration then by chief commissioners to 1859 when a lieutenant governor was appointed. The old Mughal capital of Delhi was transferred to its jurisdiction from 1859 to 1912 when Delhi was created a separate province. In 1921 Punjab was raised to a governor’s province, and it was divided between India and Pakistan in 1947.

201

Queensland (1824-1900)

昆士兰

今澳大利亚昆士兰州

The first settlement in Queensland was a penal colony established from New South Wales in 1824. In 1859 it was detached from New South Wales, granted responsible government and constituted a separate colony under a governor. In 1901 it jined the newly established Commonwealth of Australia.

202

Réunion (1810-1815)

留尼汪

留尼汪（法）

Great Britain occupied the French colony of Réunion between 1810 and 1815.

203

Rhode Island (1636-1776)

罗德岛

今美国罗德岛州

Rhode Island was settled from Massachusetts in 1638. After 1647 the four towns which were separately governed (Newport, Portsmouth, Providence, and Warwick) began a process of amalgamation which was completed in 1654. In 1663 the colony was granted a charter as Rhode Island. It was part of the Dominion of New England from 1686 to 1689, and it broke itself with the British in 1775.

204

Rhodesia and Nyasaland (1953-1963)

罗得西亚和尼亚萨兰

含今赞比亚、津巴布韦、马拉维

In 1953 Nyasaland, Northern Rhodesia and Southern Rhodesia united to form the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, and a governor-general was appointed. It was dissolved in 1963 to create future independent country of Malawi, Zambia and Zimbabwe.

205

Rupert’s Land (1670-1870)

鲁柏特地

含今加拿大诸省

Rupert’s Land was the name given to the area granted to the Hudson’s Bay Company in 1670. In 1810 the Hudson’s Bay Company’s territories were divided into a Northern Department, (including York, Churchill and the Saskatchewan and Winnipeg posts), and a Southern Department (including Albany, Moose an Eastman). , each under a superintendent. In 1815 a governor-in-chief was appointed. With the merge of the Hudson’s Bay Company and the North West Company in 1821 this office of governor-in-chief was abolished and revived in 1826 (formally in 1839). The territorial rights of the Hudson’s Bay Company was sold to Canada in 1869, and were transferred in 1870.

206

Saint Eustatius (1665-1666, 1672-79, 1781, 1801-02, 1810-16)

圣尤斯特歇斯

今圣尤斯特歇斯（荷）

The Dutch colony of Sint Eustatius was occupied by the British several times in the history.

207

Saint Helena (1658-2009)

圣赫勒拿

圣赫勒拿岛（英） 

Saint Helena was discovered and named by the Portuguese in 1502. The island was occupied by the Dutch in 1645 but abandoned in 1651. It was then occupied by the East India Company and remained so until 1834 when the British government assumed direct and permanent control, with an exception between 1815 to 1821 when Napoleon’s exile there it was directly ruled by the crown. Ascension Island from 1922 and Tristan da Cunha from 1938, were Saint Helena’s dependencies, and in 2009 the official name was changed to Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha.

208

Saint Kitts-Nevis-Anguilla (1882-1980)

圣基茨-尼维斯-安圭拉

含今圣基茨和尼维斯、安圭拉 

Saint Kitts (or Saint Christopher) in the Lesser Antilles was settled by the English in 1623. It was shared with the French, who occupied the both ends of the island while the British held the centre, for most of the time in the 17th century, until the French was finally expelled from the island in 1702. In 1882 the neighbouring island of Nevis, along with Anguilla, united with Saint Kitts into a single colony. Saint Kitts was a member of the Leeward Islands government from 1671 to 1960, a member of the West Indies Federation from 1958 to 1962 and then a separate colony. It became an associated states in 1967. Anguilla was separated in 1980 and the name was changed to Saint Christopher and Nevis. It gained independence in 1983.

209

Saint Lucia (1666-67, 1722-23, 1762-63, 1778-84, 1794-95, 1796-1802,1803-1979)

圣卢西亚

圣卢西亚

Before 1781, the island of Saint Lucia lead a peculiarly checkered administrative existence. It was held by the French six times, the British three times, and declared neutral twice. Even after 1781 when it remained under the British, it was occupied by the French from 1783 to 1794, 1795 to 1796 and 1802 to 1803. Saint Lucia was a separate colony until 1838 when it joined the Windward Islands government under Barbados. After 1885 when Barbados was detached, Saint Lucia became a member of the Windward Islands government until its dissolution in 1960. It 1967 it became an associated state and in 1979 it became an independent country.

210

Saint Vincent (1627-1636, 1672-1673, 1762-1779, 1783-1979)

圣文森特

今属圣文森特和格林纳丁斯

Saint Vincent was granted to the Earl of Carlisle in 1627, but there’s no settlement at the time. It was occupied by the British in 1762, and there’s a brief occupation by the French between 1779 and 1782. From 1833 to 1885 it was under Barbados, and then part of the Windward Islands government until 1960. It became an associated state in 1969, and gained independence in 1979.

211

Sarawak (1841-1963)

沙劳越

今马来西亚沙捞越州

Sarawak in northern Borneo was ceded to an Englishman James Brooke by the Sultan of Brunei in 1841. Sarawak remained a possession of the Brooke family from 1841 to 1946 except for a period of occupation during World War II. In 1888 it officially came under British protection, and in 1946 it was ceded to the crown and became a crown colony. In 1963 Sarawak became part of the new Federation of Malaysia.

212

Senegal (1758-1763, 1809-1817)

塞内加尔

塞内加尔

The French colony of Senegal was occupied by the British from 1758 to 1763, and 1809 to 1816.

213

Senegambia (1765-1779)

塞内冈比亚

含今塞内加尔、冈比亚

The British occupied the French colony of Senegal in 1758 and returned only the islet of Gorée in 1763. The remainder, with the British posts on the Gambia River, was incorporated into the colony of Senegambia that was formed in 1765, the first crown colony in Africa. After the reoccupation ofSenegal by the French in 1778, the colony of Senegambia in practical terms ended in 1779, and in the 1783 Treaty of Paris Great Britain retained only her former posts on the Gambia.

214

Seychelles Islands (1903-1976)

塞舌尔群岛

塞舌尔

The Seychelles Islands in the western Indian Ocean were discovered by the Portugues in 1505. In 1743 it was claimed by the French and it was occupied by the British in 1794. This was only formally settled until 1810 when it was annexed and put under Mauritius. The Seychelles remained under Mauritius until 1903 when they were erected into a separate crown colony. Seychelles became independent in 1976.

215

Sierra Leone (1787-1961)

塞拉利昂

塞拉利昂

The province of Freedom was settled mainly by freed slaved from the former American colonies, and was established in 1787 on the Sierra Leone coast of West Africa. At first it was self-governing and not under direct British control, but from 1792 with more settlers coming under the aegis of the Sierra Leone Company which began to dominate the province. It was governed by the Company until 1808 when it became a crown colony. From 1821 to 1850 the governor of Sierra Leone exercised jurisdiction over the Gold Coast and from 1821 to 1843 over the Gambia as well. From 1866 to 188 the governor of Sierra Leone was also governor-in-chief of the West Africa Settlements, which included Lagos and the Gold Coast until 1874, and the Gambia until 1888. With all these separations the West Africa Settlements government was abolished in 1888. In 1896 the interior of Sierra Leone which was called the Protectorate was annexed to the colony. In 1961 Sierra Leone became independent and in 1971 a republic.

216

Sind (1843-1947)

信德

今巴基斯坦信德省

Sindh in southwestern India was annexed to British India in 1843 and was placed under a commissioner subject to the governor of Bombay. In 1936 it became a separate province under a governor. In 1947 Sind became a part of Pakistan.

217

Singapore (1819-1959)

新加坡

新加坡

Singapore was purchased in 1819 from the sultan of Johore to replace Penang as the main British port in Southeast Asia. It was governed by a resident between 1819 to 1826 and then it joined Penang and Malacca to form the Straits Settlements. The government of Straits Settlements was not reconstituted after the Japanese occupation in World War II. Singapore became a crown colony while other components joined together in the Union of Malaya. In 1959 Singapore became independent. It joined Malaysia in 1963, but withdrew in 1965 to became an independent republic.

218

South Africa High Commission (1847-1964)

南部非洲高级专员公署

含今莱索托（时巴苏陀兰）、博兹瓦纳（时贝专纳兰）、斯威士兰以及津巴布韦（时南罗得西亚）

Before 1931 the governor of Cape Colony and then the governors-general of the Union of South Africa served as ex officio as high commissioners for South Africa and in that role they were responsible for the protectorates of Basutoland, Bechuanaland and Swaziland which were administered by resident commissioners. In 1931 the role of the high commissioner was separated from the governor-general and it was purely in charge of the protectorates. The office was abolished in 1964 when the territories evolved toward independence.

219

South Arabian Federation (1839-1967)

南阿拉伯联邦

今属也门

The government of Aden was responsible for the so-called Eastern and Western Protectorates until 1959, when five of them formed the Federation of Arab Emirates of the South. By 1962 further nine states joined and the name was changed to Federation of South Arabia. And itself joined in 1963 and ceased to be a crown colony. In 1967 the Federation of South Arabia became independent Republic of South Yemen.

220

South Australia (1836-1900)

南澳大利亚

今澳大利亚南澳大利亚州 

The area of South Australia was under New South Wales until 1836. From 1836 to 1845, and from 1855 to 1901 South Australia was under governors; from 1845 to 1855 under lieutenant governors. In 1910 South Australia joined the new Commonwealth of Australia. From 1863 to 1910 Northern Australia (Northern Territory) was under the jurisdiction of South Australia.

221

South Carolina (1663-1776)

南卡罗来纳

今美国南卡罗来纳州

Carolina, including both South and North, was granted to a group of proprietors in 1663 but settlement was planted only in 1670. The governor of South Carolina was appointed by proprietors until 1719 when the crown began to appoint the governors, although the rights of the colony was only transferred to the royal by 1729. From 1691 to 1712 North Carolina was ruled by governors appointed from South Carolina. South Carolina remained a royal province until 1775 when the governor was expelled.

222

Southern Rhodesia (1900-1965, 1979-1980)

南罗得西亚

今津巴布韦

The territory north of South Africa was ceded to the British South African Company in 1889, and the kingdom of the Ndebele was subjugated in 1893. The area was known as Mashonaland until 1894 and then renamed as Southern Rhodesia. It was governed by the British South African Company until 1923 when it became a crown colony with a self-government. It was the dominant member of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland from 1953 to 1963. Southern Rhodesia unilaterally announced its independence in 1965, but it returned to colony status in 1979, and finally won independence in 1980 as Zimbabwe.

223

Straits Settlements (1826-1946)

海峡殖民地

含今马来西亚、新加坡 

Britain’s control over the Malayan Peninsula began with the establishment of Penang in 1786, Singapore in 1819 and Malacca in 1825. These three enclaves were united to form the Straits Settlements in 1826. It was part of British India until 1867 then it became a crown colony. The control of the peninsula was expanded, in 1895 four Malay states formed the Federated Malay States under the control of the Straits Settlements government, and in 1904 the governor of the Straits Settlements became high commissioner to the Unfederated Malay States. Furthermore, the Cocos and Keeling Islands were under the Straits Settlement in 1886, and Christmas Islands in 1900. The Straits Settlements were occupied by the Japanese from 1942 to 1945, and was not reconstituted after that, but rather was replaced by the Union of Malaya and by Singapore.

224

Surat (1612-1687)

苏拉特

今属印度古吉拉特邦

Surat on India’s west coast was the site of the first English factory in India built in 1612, and became the chief English factory in western India in 1616. Surat was replaced by Bombay as the English headquarter in 1668, while the presidency remained to 1687, with the governors of Bombay serving as Presidents and governing Bombay itself through deputies. In 1687 it came under the government of Bombay and remained part of the province of Bombay until 1947.

225

Suriname (1804-1815)

苏里南

苏里南

Great Britain occupied the Dutch colony of Surinam from 1804 to 1815.

226

Swaziland (1902-1968)

斯威士兰

斯威士兰

The area ruled by the Swazi became dependent on the Transvaal in 1895. After the Anglo-Boer War of 1899-1902 it was placed under the now British colony of Transvaal. It was made directly dependent on the high commissioner for South Africa in 1906, as were Basutoland and Bechuanaland. A Resident commissioner was appointed in 1907. Swaziland remained a protectorate until 1968 when it became independent.

227

Tanganyika (1916-1961)

坦噶尼喀

今属坦桑尼亚

Tanganyika, which was former colony under German East Africa, was conquered by the British and Belgians during World War I. The area except for Ruanda-Urundi was awarded to Great Britain in 1920 by the League of Nations as a mandate, and then it became a United Nations trusteeship in 1947. In 1961 Tanganyika was made an independent dominion within the British Commonwealth, and it gained independent in 1962. In 1964 Tanganyika combined with Zanzibar to became Tanzania.

228

Tangier (1662-1684)

丹吉尔

今属摩洛哥

The town and fortress of Tangier was occupied by the Portuguese in 1471. In 1661, it was included in the dowry of Catarina, wife of Charles II. The English abandoned it in 1684 after a long siege by the ruler of Morocco.

229

Tasmania (1803-1900)

塔斯马尼亚

今澳大利亚塔斯马尼亚州

Tasmania was discovered in 1642 by the Dutch and named Van Diemen’s Land. Great Britain annexed int to New South Wales in 1803 and made a separate colony in 1825. It was renamed Tasmania in 1855. In 1901 Tasmania became a state of the new Commonwealth of Australia.

230

Tobago (1639-1643, 1666, 1672, 1762-1781, 1793-1802, 1803-1962)

多巴哥

今属特立尼达和多巴哥

Tobago was settled by the English briefly in 1614, by the Dutch fro m1658 to 1672, and by the English and French variously from 1677 to 1762, and finally ceded to the British in 1763 Treaty of Paris. It was part of the Southern Caribbee Islands from 1763 to 1781. It was held by the French from 1781 to 1793 and from 1802 go 1803 Tobago was part of the Windward Islands government under Barbados from 1833 to 1885 and of separate Windward Islands government from 1885 to 1889. In 1889 it was transferred to Trinidad and finally merged as Trinidad and Tobago. Trinidad and Tobago became independent in 1962, and a republic in 1976. Tobago got autonomous status in 1980.

231

Tonga (1900-1970)

汤加

汤加

The Kingdom of Tonga remained free of overt European influence until 1900 when they signed a treaty with Great Britain to become a protectorate and a consul appointed. Tonga was under the Western Pacific High Commission until 1952, and then under Fiji to 1965. Tonga was then under the British Commonwealth Relations Office until 1970 when it gained full independence.

232

Transjordan (1921-1946)

外约旦

今约旦

The area of Transjordan was given to Great Britain as a mandate after World War I and in 1923 it was established as a kingdom. Transjordan was administered by the high commissioner for Palestine and was represented by a resident based in Transjordan. This office was abolished in 1946 when Transjordan became formally independent as Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan.

233

Transvaal (1877-1880, 1900-1910)

德兰士瓦

今属南非

The Boer Republic of Transvaal was invaded and annexed by the British in 1877, but withdrew in 1881 due to the persistent resistance of the Boers. The territory was reoccupied by the British during the 1899-1902 Anglo-Boer War and was erected into the colony of Transvaal, with the high commissioner for South Africa as governor. Transvaal was locally administered by a lieutenant until 1906. It was granted responsible government then and joined the Union of South Africa in 1910.

234

Trinidad and Tobago (1798-1962)

特立尼达和多巴哥

特立尼达和多巴哥

The large island of Trinidad was under the Spaniard until 1797, and then was seized by the British. In 1889 the nearby island of Tobago was detached from the Windward Islands government and added to Trinidad, and thus the crown colony was called Trinidad and Tobago. From 1958 to 1962 it was part of the West Indies Federation, and with the dissolution of the federation Trinidad and Tobago became an independent country.

235

Turks and Caicos Islands (1678-1706, 1710-

特克斯和凯科斯群岛

特克斯和凯科斯群岛（英）

The Turks and Caicos Islands at the southern end of the Bahamas began to attract settlers from Bermuda in 1678, but the first permanent settlement was only in the late 18th century. The islands were part of the Bahamas from 1799 to 1848, a separate colony from 1848 to 1874, and then dependencies of Jamaica from 1874 to 1962. In 1962 they were again a separate crown colony.

236

Uganda (1890-1962)

乌干达

乌干达

In 1890 the Imperial British East Africa Company began to extend its control over the area which was then dominated by the state of Buganda and some other states. In 1894 Buganda became a protectorate and other states followed in the next few years. Buganda retained a privileged status and in 1962 Uganda became independent and in 1963 a republic.

237

Union of South Africa (1910-1931)

南非联邦

南非

The Cape Colony, Natal, the Orange River Colony and the Transvaal united in 1910 to form the Union of South Africa. The governors-general of the Union were ex officio high commissioners for South Africa and were responsible for the administration of the so-called High Commission Territories of Basutoland, Bechuanaland and Swaziland, which were locally administered by resident commissioners. It gained sovereignty by the 1931 Statute of Westminster. The Union withdrew from the British Commonwealth in 1961 and became a republic.

238

United Province of Agra and Oudh (1902-1947)

阿格拉和奥德联合省

今属印度

In 1833 the presidency of Agra was created from Bengal, but this was not implemented. In 1836 the North-West Provinces was created under a lieutenant governor. Ajmer-Merwara was detached from the North-West Provinces in 1871 to create a chief commissionership, but Oudh was added to the North-West Provinces in 1877 and the lieutenant governor of the North-West Provinces became chief commissioner of Oudh as well. In 1902 the name of the province was changed to United Province of Agra and Oudh, and it was raised to a governor’s province in 1921. In 1947 the United Province of Agra and Oudh became the state of Uttar Pradesh in India.

239

Victoria (1839-1900)

维多利亚

今澳大利亚维多利亚州

The first attempt to settle at the now area of Victoria in 1803 in the extreme southeast corner of the Australian continent was unsuccessful. The first permanent settlement was established in 1834, and a superintendent was appointed in 1839. Victoria was separated from New South Wales in 1851 and a lieutenant governor was appointed. In 1885 it was granted a responsible government and a governor. In 1901 Victoria becase a state in the newly established Commonwealth of Australia.

240

Virginia (1607-1776)

弗吉尼亚

今美国弗吉尼亚州

Virginia was the first permanent English settlement on the North American continent and was established in 1607 under the auspices of the Virginia Company of London. It was governed under the company until 1624 when it was brought under royal control. Maryland was created from the territory in 1632. From 1697 to 1768 Virginia was ruled nominally ruled by a series of governors-in-chief who never resident in the colony, and rule through a lieutenant governor. In 1775 the last royal governor was expelled.

241

Weihaiwei (1898-1930)

威海卫

今属中国山东省

The port of Weihaiwei in the province of Shandong was leased by the British from China in 1898. A commissioner to represent the British interest in the area was appointed in 1901. Great Britain relinquished control of the port to Republic of China in 1930.

242

Western Australia (1825-1900)

西澳大利亚

今澳大利亚西澳大利亚州

The coast of Western Australia was discovered by the Dutch in 1616 but remained unsettled until 1826. A lieutenant governor was appointed in 1828 and was replaced by a governor in 1832. A penal colony was established in 1850 and a responsible government granted in 1890. Western Australia joined the new Commonwealth of Australia in 1901.

243

Western Pacific High Commission (1877-1976)

西太平洋高级专员公署

含今斐济、所罗门群岛等

Great Britain’s growing but scattered interests in the Pacific Ocean led to the creation of the Western Pacific High Commission in 1877. From 1877 to 1952 the governor of Fiji acted as high commissioner and came to exercise jurisdiction over the Gilbert and Ellice Islands, the British Solomon Islands Protectorate, the New Hebrides Condominium, Tonga and Pitcairn Island as well as Fiji. The office was moved to Honiara in the British Solomon Islands in 1953, and the governor of Fiji ceased to be the high commissioner. With the entities became independent and detached in the following years, the office was dissolved finally in 1976.

244

Western Samoa (1914-1962)

西萨摩亚

今萨摩亚

The former Germany colony of Samoa was occupied by New Zealand troops in 1914 during World War I. in 1920 a League of Nations mandate was granted to New Zealand for Western Samoa, and in 1946 it became a United Nations trusteeship of New Zealand. The resident administrator (from 1948 hign commissioner) was appointed by the governor-general of New Zealand. In 1962 Western Samoa became independent, and renamed as Samoa in 1997.

245

West Indies Federation (1958-1962)

西印度群岛联邦

In 1958 all of the British Indian colonies with the exception of the Bahamas and the British Virgin Islands united to form the West Indies Federation, with the capital on Trinidad. It was dissolved in 1962 due to the disparity of interests between the large colonies of Jamaica and Trinidad and the many very small colonies.

246

Willoughby (1650-1667)

威洛比

今属苏里南

An English colony was planted at the mouth of the Surinam River in 1651, but it only lasted until 1667 when it was captured by the Dutch. By 1679 Treaty of Breda the Dutch retained Surinam in exchange for New Netherland which had been occupied by the British in 1664.

247

Windward Islands (1833-1960)

向风群岛

含今圣卢西亚、圣文森特和格林纳丁斯、格林纳达、多米尼克、巴巴多斯、特立尼达和多巴哥等

The Windward Islands government, composing Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent, Tobago, Grenada and the Grenadines, was organized into a separate colony in 1885. Previously these isaldns had been governed by the governor of Barbados. In 1889 Tobago was detached and joined Trinidad to form the colony of Trinidad and Tobago. With the exception of the Grenadines, each of the islands was governed by an administrator subject to the governor of the Windward Islands. In 1960 the Windward Islands government was dissolved like that of the Leeward Islands.

248

Zanzibar (1890-1963)

桑给巴尔

今属坦桑尼亚

British interests in the island of Zanzibar were maintained by consuls since 1840. In 1890 when the British interests were recognized by France (in exchange for Madagascar for France), and by Germany (in exchange for Heligoland for Germany). A protectorate was established in 1891 under a consul-general subject to the British Foreign Office. In 1913 the Colonial Office assumed control, and a resident was appointed. In 1963 Zanzibar became independent, and in 1964 it joined Tanganyika to from Tanzania.

249

Zululand (1879-1897)

祖鲁兰

今属南非

As a result of the Zulu War because of the conflict between the most powerful state of Zulu and the colony of Natal, a resident was appointed at the court of the Zulu king. In 1887 Zulu was annexed and the resident commissioner was made responsible to the governor of Natal. Zululand was separately administered only until 1897 when it was incorporated into Natal.

New England (1686-1689)

新英格兰

今美国初始诸州

New England was established in 1686, and included Connecticut, Massachusetts Bay, New Plymouth, Rhode Islands, together with New Hampshire and Maine. It was expanded to include New Jersey and New York in 1688, but was dissolved after the deposition of James II in 1689.

意大利 Italy

250

Dodecanese Islands (1912-1945)

佐泽卡尼索斯群岛

 今属希腊

The Dodecanese Islands in the southern Aegean Sea off the southwestern coast of Turkey was occupied by Italy in 1912 during the Italo-Turkish War. They were formally recognized as Italian possessions by the Allies in 1915, acknowledged by the Ottoman government in the 1920 Treaty of Sevres and subsequently by the Turkish Republic in the 1923 Treaty of Lausanne During World War II the islands were progressively occupied by Great Britain. This Dodecanese Islands were under British military control until 1947 when they were ceded to Greece.

251

Eritrea (1882-1941)

厄立特里亚 

 厄立特里亚

The area of Eritrea along the western coast of the Red Sea was historically a part of Ethiopia until occupied by the Ottoman in the 16th century, and then the Egyptians in the 19th century. The Italians established themselves at Assab in 1870, and at the withdrawal of the Egyptians in 1882 Italy proclaimed its sovereignty over Assab. With Massawa added in 1885, a protectorate was soon proclaimed over the Danakil area and in 1890 this expanded area was proclaimed the colony of Eritrea. The Italian interpretation of the 1899 Treaty of Uccialli claimed that Ethiopia had accepted the Italian rule in the Eritrean area but this was not validated by the Ethiopians, which led to the invasion of Italy in 1896 and failed at Aduwa. Nearly forty years later in 1935, Italy successfully occupied Ethiopia and reorganized its possessions in the area as Italian East Africa of which Eritrea was a part. The British troops occupied Eritrea in 1941 and it remained so until 1952 when it was federally united with Ethiopia. The autonomy of Eritrea was revoked in 1962 after the rebellion in 1961. Eritrea finally won its independence in 1993.

252

Italian East Africa (1936-1942)

意属东非

含今埃塞俄比亚、厄立特里亚和索马里

Italian invasion to the kingdom of Ethiopia failed in 1896, but another in 1935 ended in the conquest and annexation of Ethiopia. Ethiopia itself was divided into the provinces of Amhara, Galla e Sidama, Harar and Scioa. Together with older colonies of Eritrea and Italian Somaliland, they formed the new colony of Italian East Africa. It was governed by a high commissioner to 1936 and then by a governor-general, or viceroy. Italian East Africa was occupied by Allied troops in 1941 and Ethiopia was reconstituted as an independent country, and other former Italian colonies came under British military administration.

253

Italian Somaliland (1889-1941, 1950-1960)

意属索马里

今属索马里 

With European penetration in the northeastern Africa, Italy proclaimed a protectorate over the Mijerstein sultanates of Alula and Obbia. The area south of this was leased from Zanzibar from 1889 to 1905, first by the Filonardi Company (1893-1896) and then by the Benadir Company (1896-1905). After 1905 it was directly ruled as an Italian colony. Jubaland in the extreme south was ceded by Great Britain in 1925, and the following year the two northern sultanats were incorporated directly into Italian Somaliland. In 1935 it became a province of Italian East Africa, and remained so until its occupation by the British military in 1941. British rule lasted until 1950 when Italy was granted United Nations trusteeship over its former colony. In 1960 the former Italian Somaliland and the former British Somaliland united to form the independent Republic of Somalia.

254

Libya (1911-1942)

 利比亚

利比亚

Libya was partially occupied by Italy during the Italo-Turkish War of 1911-12. In 1919 the two administrative areas, Cyrenaica and Tripolitania, were made separate colonies, only to be reunited in 1928 under one governor-general. The Italians were driven from Libya in 1943. Cyrenaica and Tripolitania were administered by Great Britain while Fezzan in the south by France. In 1949 Cyrenaica was granted autonomy in 1949 and all the three areas were federally united for form the kingdom of Libya in 1951.

日本 Japan

255

Chosen (Korea) (1910-1945)

朝鲜殖民地

今朝鲜、韩国

Japanese interest in Korea was revived in 1876 with a trade agreement with the Korean kingdom. As a result of the Sino-Japanese War of 1894-95, Japan secured effective control of the Korean government. This control intensified progressively and a resident-general was appointed in 1906. The Korean monarchy was abolished in 1910 and Korea (already renamed Chosen) was annexed to Japan. This lasted until the Japanese surrender by the end of World War II in 1945.

256

Formosa (Taiwan) (1895-1945)

台湾

台湾 

Formosa was ceded to Japan from China in 1895 as a result of the Sino-Japanese War and the Shimonoseki Treaty. Formosa became Japan’s first colonial possession, and it remained so until the end of World War II in 1945.

257

Karafuto (1855-1875, 1905-1945)

桦太厅

今俄罗斯库页岛 

The southern part of Sakhalin, as island directly north of Japan which belonging to Russia, was ceded to Japan by Russia under the terms of the Treaty of Portsmouth in 1905 after Russian defeat in the Russo-Japanese War. Japan established a military administration overs its part of Sakhalin in 1907 and named it Karafuto. Karafuto was occupied and returned to Soviet Union 1945 after World War II.

258

Kwantung Leased Territory (1905-1945)

关东州

今属中国辽宁省 

Kwantung at the southern end of the Liaoning peninsula was leased by China to Russia. It was occupied by the Japanese in the Russo-Japanese War of 1904-05 and Japan assumed Russia’s lease. Kwantung Leased Territory was under military administration until 1919, and from 1934 the Japanese ambassador to Manchukuo was also in charge of Kwantung Leased Territory. In 1945 the area was occupied by the Soviet troops who renewed the lease until 1955 when the new China government won it back.

259

Pacific Islands Mandate (1914-1944)

日本委任统治南洋诸岛（南洋厅）

含今北马里亚纳群岛、帕劳、马绍尔群岛、密克罗尼西亚联邦等 

With the outbreak of World War I, Japan occupied the Marshall, Mariana, and Caroline islands , hitherto part of German New Guinea. Japan was awarded a League of Nations mandate for the three islands in 1919. These islands were under military administration from 1914 to 1921 and then civil rule was introduced. The islands were occupied by U.S. troops in 1944-45.

荷兰 Netherlands

Aruba (1986-

阿鲁巴

阿鲁巴（荷）

Aruba was discovered and claimed for Spain in 1499. It was seized by the Dutch in 1636 during the Eighty Years’ War, and reaffirmed in 1648 Peace of Münster. Aruba was subordinated to Curaçao, and was occupied by the British in 1804, 1805, and 1807-1816. From 1828 to 1845, Aruba, Bonaire, Curaçao, Saba, Sint Eustatius, Sint Maarten and Dutch Guiana united as the Dutch West Indies with the governor of Dutch Guiana as the governor-general. Surinname was separated in 1845 and the rest islands were united as Curaçao and Dependencies in 1848, and the name was changed to Netherlands Antilles in 1948. In 1977 Aruba deicide to withdraw from Netherlands Antilles after a referendum. Its autonomy was granted in 1983, and the separation from the Netherlands Antilles was accomplished in 1986.

Bonaire (1636-

博奈尔

博奈尔（荷）

Bonaire was discovered and claimed for Spain in 1499, and it was part of New Andalucía from 1502 and from 1524 New Granada. Bonaire was occupied by the Dutch in 1635 as a retaliation to the Spanish occupation of Sint Maarten in 1633, and it was put subordinated to Curaçao. This was reaffirmed in 1648 following the Peace of Münster which ended the Eighty Years’ War between Spain and the Dutch Republic. It was kept as Curaçao’s dependency and became part of Curaçao and Dependencies in 1848, which in 1948 changed to Netherlands Antilles. The Netherlands Antilles dissolved in 2010 and Bonaire became a special municipality of the Netherlands.

265

Curaçao (1634-

库拉索

库拉索（荷）

The island of Curaçao was occupied by the Spaniards from 1499 to 1634 when it was conquered by the Dutch. The smaller neighbouring islands of Aruba and Bonaire were occupied soon and made administratively dependent on Curaçao. The islands were administered by the first West India Company to 1674 and by the second West India Company to 1792 when they came under direct state control. They were occupied by the British from 1800 to 1803, and again from 1807 to 1816. From 1828 to 1845, Curaçao, Aruba and Bonaire were subordinated to the short-lived government-general of the Dutch West Indies with the governor of Dutch Guiana as the governor-general. In 1845 this government was dissolved and Curaçao became administratively independent. In 1848 Saint Eustatius, Saint Maarten and Saba were added to untied under the name of Curaçao and Dependencies which later in 1948 renamed Netherlands Antilles. The Netherlands Antilles dissolved in 2010 and Curaçao became an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.

Saba (1640-65, 1667-72, 1679-1781, 1784-95, 1803-1810, 1816-

萨巴

萨巴（荷）

Saba became a Dutch colony in 1640, and it kept subordinate to Sint Eustatius to 1803, a Sint Maarten dependency from 1803 to 1821, and then a dependency of Sint Eustatius until 1848 when all were put under Curaçao and Dependencies (from 1948 Netherlands Antilles). Before 1816 there was intermediate occupation by the British 1665, 1672-1681, 1781, 1801-1803 and 1810-1816, and by the French 1781-1784, 1795-1801. The Netherlands Antilles dissolved in 2010 and Saba became a special municipality of the Netherlands.

280

Sint Eustatius (1636-1665, 1668-72, 1679-89, 1696-1781, 1784-1795, 1802-1810, 1816-

圣尤斯特歇斯

圣尤斯特歇斯（荷）

Sint Eustatius at the northern end of the Lesser Antilles was settled under the Dutch West India Company in 1636. The nearby island of Sint Maarten and Saba were settled about the same time and were attached to Sint Eustatius administratively. Sint Eustatius was occupied by the English from 1665 to 1668, 1672 to 1679, 1690 to 1698, 1781, 1801 to 1802 and 1810 to 1816, and by the French from 1689 to 1690 and 1781 to 1784. From 1828 to 1845, Sint Eustatius, Sint Maarten and Saba were subordinated to the short-lived government-general of the Dutch West Indies with the governor of Dutch Guiana as the governor-general. In 1845 this government was dissolved and in 1848 Sint Eustatius was attached to Curaçao as Netherlands Antilles and ceased to exist as a separate colony. The Netherlands Antilles dissolved in 2010 and Sint Eustatius became a special municipality of the Netherlands.

Sint Maarten (1631-1633, 1648-72, 1676, 1690-99, 1703-1779, 1784-95, 1802-1810, 1816-

圣马丁

圣马丁（荷）

For history of the island of Sint Maarten before 1816 see under the French Saint Martin. From 1816 to 1821 Sint Maarten was subordinated to Sint Eustatius, and from 1821 to 1828 Sint Eustatius was a dependency of Sint Maarten. From 1828 to 1845, Sint Eustatius, Sint Maarten and Saba were subordinated to the short-lived government-general of the Dutch West Indies with the governor of Dutch Guiana as the governor-general. In 1845 this government was dissolved and in 1848 Sint Maarten was attached to Curaçao as Netherlands Antilles. The Netherlands Antilles dissolved in 2010 and Sint Maarten became an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.

260

Berbice (1666-1781,1784-1796,1802-1803)

伯比斯

今属圭亚那 

A concession around Berbice, easternmost of the four Dutch settlements on the coast of western Guiana, was granted to the house of van Pere in 1627 and was privately administered by the group from 1666 to 1714. From 1720 it was governed by the Berbice Association. Along with the other Dutch colonies in this area, Berbice was occupied by the British n 1803 and retained by them as British Guiana.

261

Cape Colony (1652-1797, 1803-1806)

开普殖民地

今属南非

Cape Town at the southern tip of Africa was established by the Dutch East India Company in 1652. It rapidly became a colony settlement, spreading eastward alone the cape. Company rule ended in 1794 and in the following year the British first occupied Cape Colony. It was returned to the Dutch under the terms of 1803 Treaty of Amiens, but was finally occupied by the British in 1806.

262

Ceará (1637-1654)

塞阿拉

今属巴西塞阿拉州 

Netherlands occupied the Portuguese colony of Ceará from 1637 to 1654.

263

Ceylon (1658-1796)

锡兰

斯里兰卡

The Dutch came to Ceylon in 1640 at the invitation of the ruler of Kandy who expected to use the Dutch to drive the Portuguese out of the island. This was achieved in 1658 but the Dutch remained and increased its territory previously held by the Portuguese. By 1765 the Dutch controlled the entire coast line, reducing the kingdom of Kandy to an isolated kingdom in the interior highlands. The British occupied the Dutch possessions in Ceylon in 1796 and retained it permanently thereafter.

264

Coromandel Coast (1608-1825)

科罗曼德海岸

今属印度泰米尔纳德邦、安得拉邦和本地治里中央直辖区等

In 1608 the Dutch East India Company was given permission to build a fort and do trading along the Coromandel coast by ruler of Vijayanagara Empire. The Dutch fort of Pulicat was the headquarter until 1690 when the center of Dutch power was shifted to Negapatam. From 1693 to 1699 the Dutch were able to occupy the French posts in the area, but from 1795 to 1818 the Dutch posts were occupied by the British. In 1825 they were definitely ceded to Great Britain in return for concession elsewhere.

266

Demerara (1750-1781,1784-1796,1802-1803)

德梅拉拉

今属圭亚那 

The settlement of Demerara was developed from Essequibo in 1750 and remained subject to the latter until 1781 when it was occupied by the British. It was then occupied by the French from 1782 to 1784 when it was returned to the Dutch. From 1784 it replaced Essequibo as the headquarter of the Dutch control in western Guiana. Occupied by the British again from 1796 to 1802, followed by a short return, Demerara was finally occupied by the British in 1803.the

267

Essequibo (1616-1781,1784-1796,1802-1803)

埃塞奎博

今属圭亚那 

The area at the mouth of the Essequibo River in western Guiana was settled by the Dutch West India Company in 1624. It was briefly captured by the English in 1666 but retaken. Essequibo became subordinate to Demerara from 1784 after the occupation from the British and French. In 1803 the British finally occupied the Dutch colony together with other Dutch possessions in western Guiana.

268

Gold Coast (1598-1871)

黄金海岸

今属加纳
