Dutch Gold Coast Settlements began in 1598. In 1637 they captured the main Portuguese fort at Elmina and by 1642 they had driven the Portuguese from the coast entirely. In 1867 the eastern posts were sold to the British and five years later the remaining were likewise sold to the British for cash and for concessions in Sumatra.

269

Luanda (1641-1648)

卢安达

今属安哥拉

The Dutch captured Luanda, Benguela and other coastal towns of Angola from Portugal, driving the Portuguese into the interior lands. However this occupation was quite brief and in 1648 they were expelled by the Portuguese.

270

Malabar Coast (1663-1795)

马拉巴尔海岸

今属印度喀拉拉邦、卡纳塔克邦 

The Dutch appeared on the Malabar coast in 1656 and captured Cochin in 1663. Cochin remained their headquarter. The remaining Dutch posts were taken by the British in 1795, and were retained by the British in 1818 when the Dutch posts at Malacca and on the Coromandel coast were returned to the Netherlands.

271

Malacca (1641-1795, 1818-1826)

马六甲

今属马来西亚马六甲州

The strategic post of Malacca was captured from the Portuguese in 1641. In 1795 it was occupied by the British who retained it until 1818. In 1825 it was ceded to the British permanently in return for Bencoolen as a result of the 1824 agreement which demarcated the whole Malaya under British and the whole East Indies to the Dutch. Malacca was soon integrated into the British Straits Settlements.

272

Mauritius (1638-1710)

毛里求斯

毛里求斯 

Mauritius was named after Maurits van Nassau, stadholder of Holland. It was occupited by the Dutch in 1638 but abandoned in 1658. Mauritius was again partially re-settled in 1664m but was finally abandoned in 1710. Only twenty years later it was occupied by the French, and named it Île de France.

273

Netherlands Antilles (1848-2010)

荷属安的列斯群岛

 今库拉索、荷属圣马丁、博奈尔、圣尤斯特歇斯和萨巴

In 1848 the colony of Curaçao with its dependencies Aruba and Bonaire, and the colony of Saint Eustatius with its dependencies of Saint Maarten and Saba were united as Curaçao and Dependencies, with the seat of the government on Curaçao. It was official known as the Territory of Curaçao from 1936 and 1948 and after 1948 Netherlands Antilles. In 1954 it became an autonomous and equal province within the kingdom of the Netherlands, same as Suriname. Aruba was seceded from the Netherlands Antilles in 1986, and the remaining part finally dissolved in 2010. Curaçao and Sint Maarten became autonomous countries within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, and Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba (BES) became special municipalities of the Netherlands.

274

Netherlands Brazil (1630-1654)

荷属巴西（新荷兰）

今属巴西 

The Dutch possessions in Brazil began with the brief occupation of the Portuguese capital Bahia in 1624. In 1630 the Dutch began to encroach on Portuguese colonies in the northeastern corner of Brazil. The Dutch effort stagnated after the departure of Johan Maurits van Nassau in 1644, and by 1654 all Dutch possessions were captured by the Portuguese.

275

Netherlands East Indies (1602-1811, 1816-1949)

荷属东印度

今印度尼西亚 

The United East India Company (Veerinigde Oost-Indische Compagnie) was established in 1602 and a governor-general over the company’s forts, places, factories, persons and business was appointed, headquartered at Bantam in Java until 1619 when moved to Batavia. Gradually the British, Portuguese, and Spaniards were eliminated as commercial rivals, the Moluccas and Macassar were subdued and Java was finally conquered in 1755. During the height the company controlled, besides the East Indies, also areas in Ceylon, the Coromandel coast, the Malabar coast, Malacca, Taiwan and various trading posts from Japan to Mocha in the Yemen.

Then the company declined and was abolished in 1799, the East Indies coming under the control of the Dutch government. Java and most of the rest of East Indies were occupied by the British from 1811 to 1816, until 1824 when an agreement with the British gave the Dutch free hand over the whole East Indies. They proceeded to round out their control of the archipelago (except Portuguese Timor) by the conquest of Sumatra and various outlying islands. The Japanese occupied the East Indies during World War II. Unable to suppress the national movement after the end of the war militarily, and unwilling to agree to a mutually acceptable compromise, the Dutch government was forced in 1949 to agree a transfer of sovereignty over the islands to the Republic of Indonesia which was established in 1945.

276

Netherlands New Guinea (1828-1962)

荷属新几内亚

今属印度尼西亚

The western portion of New Guinea was a part of the Netherlands East Indies and was retained after the Dutch loss of the East Indies in 1949. The Dutch government turned it over to the control of the United Nations in 1962 and in turn the United Nations handed it to the Republic of Indonesia which created the province of West Irian.

277

New Netherlands (1623-1664)

新尼德兰

今属美国纽约州

The Dutch West India Company established a settlement upriver at Albany in 1624 and another at the mouth of the river in 1626. Directors-general were appointed from 1626 as well. New Netherlands was taken by the English in 1664, but was briefly recaptured by the Dutch from 1673 to 1674, when it was officially surrendered to England in return for English acceptance of Dutch rule in Suriname.

278

Paraíba (1635-1645)

帕拉伊巴

今属巴西帕拉伊巴州 

Netherlands occupied the Portuguese colony of Paraíba between 1635 and 1645.

279

Pomeroon (1657-1689)

波默伦

今属圭亚那

Pomeroon in western Guiana was settled from Netherlands Brazil by fugitives and in 1657 it was created a separate post subordinated to the main settlement at Essequibo. The English briefly occupied it in 1666 and it was not resettled until 1679. In 1689 a French-Carib attack devastated the colony and it subsequently existed only as a frontier post under Essequibo.

281

Suriname (1665-1802, 1816-1975)

苏里南

苏里南 

The Dutch occupied the English colony of Willoughby in 1667 and retained it at the Peace of Breda in return for the cession of New Netherlands. Suriname was occupied by the British from 1804 to 1815 and was the only possession in Guiana which was returned to the Dutch after the Napoleonic Wars. From 1828 to 1845 the governor of Suriname was also governor-general of the Dutch West Indies. In 1954 Suriname became autonomous and equal province in the kingdom of Netherlands, and it finally gained independence in 1975.

282

Tayowan (Formosa) (1624-1662)

福尔摩萨

今台湾 

The Dutch occupied the southern part of Taiwan in 1624 after being driven from the Pescadores Islands by the Chinese. The Dutch controlled the entire island in 1642 after the Spanish abandoned their settlement in the northern part of the island, who named it Formosa. In 1662 Zheng Chenggong drove the Dutch from the island completely.

新西兰 New Zealand

120

Cook Islands (1900-

库克群岛

库克群岛（新）

New Zealand Antarctic Territory (1923-

新西兰南极领地

新西兰南极领地

181

Niue (1901-

纽埃

纽埃（新）

Tokelau (1926-

托克劳

托克劳（新）

挪威 Norway

Norwegian Antarctic Territory (1928-

挪威北极领地

挪威北极领地

Svalbard (1916-

斯瓦尔巴群岛

斯瓦尔巴群岛

葡萄牙 Portugal

285

Azores (1432-

亚速尔

亚速尔群岛（葡）

The Azores were discovered by the Portuguese in 1427, and settlement began in 1432. Each of the islands became a donatária and in 1766 the islands were united under a single captain-general. In 1831 the islands were administratively regrouped into three metropolitan districts of Portugal.

297

Madeira (1420-

马德拉

马德拉群岛（葡）

The Madeira was settled by the Portuguese in 1418-20. The two islands (Madeira and Porto Santo) were granted as donatárias. After the Spanish occupation of Portugal in 1580 the islands were united under a governor-general (later governor), and remained so until 1834, when Madeira became a metropolitan district of Portugal.

287

Brazil (1500-1822)

巴西

巴西

Brazil only came into existance in 1775 with the incorporation of the Estado do Maranhão into the viceroyalty at Rio de Janeiro. There’s a big area called Estado do Brasil that became part of the new Brazil, including Bahia, Ceará, Goiás, Mato Grasso, Minas Gerais, Paraíba, Rio de Janeiro, Rio Grande do Norte, Rio Grande do Sul, São Paulo, Nova Colônia do Sacramento, Sergipe d’El Rei. (for the areas included in the Estado do Maranhão, see under Maranhão). The viceroyalty of Brazil eneded in 1808 when the Portuguese Prince Regent João VI fled to Brazil and became his own viceroy.

283

Alagôas (1817-1821)

阿拉戈斯

今巴西阿拉戈斯州

Alagôas was a district of Pernambuco until 1817 when it was created a separate captaincy. It lasted for only four years before it became a province of the Empire of Brazil.

286

Bahia (1549-1821)

巴伊亚

今巴西巴伊亚州

In 1514 Bahia was granted as a donatária but soon thereafter it was sold to the crown. In 1549 a governor (after 1578 governor-general) was appointed, but not replace or supersede the donatários. From 1574 ro 1578 and 1608 to 1612 the southern captaincies were detached from Bahia and administered separately (Rio de Janeiro). In 1763 the seat of the viceroy of Estado do Brasil was moved from Bahia to Rio de Janeiro. Bahia remained the seat of the captain-general until 1822 when it became a province of Brazil.

289

Ceará (1619-1821)

塞阿拉

今巴西塞阿拉州

Ceará in northereastern Brazil was created a donatária in 1534, but the area was not settled until 1603 from neighboring Pernambuco. In 1619 Ceará was erected into a royal captaincy in 1619. From 1621 to 1656 the capitães-móres were subject to Maranhão (between 1637 and 1654 Ceará was occupied by the Dutch). In 1656 Ceará was removed from the jurisdiction of Maranhão and placed under Pernambuco where it remained until 1799, when it was detached and became a separate captaincy. In 1822 it became a province of Brazil.

292

Espírito Santo (1534-1821)

圣埃斯皮里图

今巴西圣埃斯皮里图州

Espírito Santo on the southeast coast of Brazil was created a donatária in 1535. It remained under donatários, who later appointed capitães-móres, until 1718 when it lapsed to the Portuguese crown and was placed under Bahia as a royal captaincy. In 1822 Espírito Santo became a province of Brazil.

293

Goiás (1748-1821)

戈亚斯

今巴西戈亚斯州

Goiás was detached from the province of São Paulo in 1748. In 1822 it became a province of Brazil.

294

Grão-Pará (1616-1821)

格朗帕拉

今巴西帕拉州

Grão-Pará, extending inland from the mouth of the Amazon, was settled at the same time as neighbouring Maranhão. From 1615 to 1737 Grão-Pará was ruled by capitães-móres under Maranhão. From 1737 to 1775 both were still administratively united but in 1753 the governor-general was transferred to Grão-Pará while Maranhão was governed by capitães-móres. In 1757 the vast interior part of Grão-Pará was erected int othe province of São José do Rio Negro, which remained under Grão-Pará. In 1775 Grão-Pará was divided from Maranhão. In 1822 Grão-Pará became the province of Pará of Brazil.

299

Maranhão (1536-1821)

马拉尼昂

今巴西马拉尼昂州

Maranhão on the north coast of Brazil east of the Amazon estuary was granted in two donatárias in 1534, but no settlement was made until early 17th century in response to French colonization approach. A separate Estado do Maranhão was created in 1621 (effective 1626) which included Grão-Pará as well. The Estoda was abolished in 1652 but quickly revived in 1654. From 1737 to 1775 both Maranhão and Grão-Pará were administratively united but in 1753 the governor-general was transferred to Grão-Pará while Maranhão was governed by capitães-móres. In 1775 the Estado do Maranhão was abolished and the entire region came under the jurisdiction of the viceroy of Rio de Janeiro. The former Estado was divided into Grão-Pará, São José do Rio Negro , Piauí and a truncated province of Maranhão. In 1822 Maranhão beame a province of Brazil.

300

Mato Grasso (1748-1821)

马托格拉索

今巴西马托格拉索州

The province of Mato Grasso was detached from São Paulo in 1748, similar to Goiás and Minas Gerais. It became a province of Brazil in 1822.

301

Minas Gerais (1720-1821)

米纳斯吉拉斯

今巴西米纳斯吉拉斯州

The area of Minas Gerais was part of São Vicente before 1710 and then until 1720 of São Paulo when the new captaincy of São Paulo e Minas do Ouro was created. In 1720 Minas Gerais was created a separate province or captaincy. It remained so until 1822 when it became a part of Brazil.

305

Paraíba (1580-1821)

帕拉伊巴

今巴西帕拉伊巴州

The area of Paraíba was settled from Pernambuco and was a captaincy subject to Pernambuco. From 1635 to 1645 it was occupied by the Dutch. Paraíba remained under Pernambuco until 1799 when it was created an autonomous captaincy. Paraíba became a province of Brazil in 1822.

306

Pernambuco (1535-1821)

伯南布哥

今巴西伯南布哥州

Pernambuco in northeast Brazil was granted as a donatária in 1534. Until 1575 Pernambuco was governed by its donatários and thereafter it was ruled by capitães-móres. From 1637 to 1654 Pernambuco was under the Dutch control, and after the restoration of Portuguee rule it came under the control of the crown, although it nominally remained a donatária until 1716. Ceará was subornidated to Pernambuco from 1656 to 1799, Paraíba from 1582 to 1799, Rio Grande do Norte from 1701 to 1808 and Alagôas until 1817. Pernambuco became a province of Brazil in 1822.

307

São José do Piauí (1759-1821)

圣何塞-皮奥伊

今巴西皮奥伊州

Piauí was settled from Bahia in 1682. In 1715 the area was transferred to the control of Maranhão but only in 1759 was Piauí erected into a captaincy, still remaining under the jurisdiction of Maranhão. In 1811 it was detached from Maranhão and became a separate province. It became part of Brazil in 1822.

310

Rio de Janeiro (1563-1821)

里约热内卢

今巴西里约热内卢州

In 1563-65 the Portuguese settled the area and the captaincy of Rio de Janeiro was created, under the governor-general at Bahia until 1763 (except for the period 1574-78, 1608-12 when it was briefly removed from the control of Bahia). In 1763 the seat of the viceroy was shifted from Bahia to Rio de Janeiro however Rio de Janeiro ceased to be a separate province. With the suppression of the Estado do Maranhão in 1775, Brazil was for the first time united under a single administration.

311

Rio Grande do Norte (1597-1821)

北里奥格兰德 

今巴西北里奥格兰德州

Rio Grande was one of the fourteen created between 1534 and 1536, but failed to settle before sold back to the crown. After 1597 the area was settled from Pernambuco and governed by (exceot the period 1633-1654 under Dutch rule) until 1701 by governors, while still under the authority of Pernambuco. In 1822 Rio Grande do Norte became a province of Brazil.

312

São Pedro do Rio Grande do Sul (1737-1821)

圣佩德罗-南里奥格兰德

今巴西南里奥格兰德州

The area of Rio Grande do Sul was settled south of São Paulo, to be connected up with Nova Colônia do Sacramento. From 1737 to 1761 it was governed by military commandants since the area was under continuous intrusions from Spanish forces to the west. The territory was under Rio de Janeiro between 1761 and 1807, when it was erected into a separate captaincy-general. First it was known as São Pedro do Rio Grande, and gradually it came to be distinguished from Rio Grande do Norte, and began to be called Rio Grande do Sul.

313

Santa Catarina (1739-1821)

圣卡塔琳娜

今巴西圣卡塔琳娜州

The creation of Nova Colônia do Sacramento necessitated the settlement and administrative organization of the territory south of São Paulo in order to provide logistical support to the isolated Sacramento. Santa Catarina had been granted as a donatária in 1664 but this was never implemented. In 1739 it was organized, subornidated to Rio de Janeiro. In 1822 Santa Catarina became a province of Brazil.

315

São José do Rio Negro (1755-1821)

内格罗河畔圣何塞

今巴西亚马孙州

The boundaries between Portugal and Spain for the area of the upper Amazon was tentatively demarcated in 1750 Treaty of Madrid, and the area claimed by Portugal was administered by Grão-Pará. It was created as the province of São José do Rio Negro in 1757, remained under Grão-Pará until 1822. It was not retained as a province in 1822 when the Empire of Brazil established, only to be restored later in 1850 as the province of Amazonas.

316

São Paulo e Minas de Ouro (1709-1821)

圣保罗

今巴西圣保罗州

In 1681 the capital of São Vicente was moved from Santos to São Paulo. In 1710. The donatárias of SãoVicente, Santo Amaro and Itanhaém were sold to the Portuguese crown and all together with the vast interior lands were formed into the new province of São Paulo e Minas de Ouro. Minas Gerais, Goiás, and Mato Grasso had been separated from São Paulo I nthe following years till 1750. São Paulo became a province of Brazil in 1822.

318

São Vicente (1535-1709) and Itanhaém (1616-1753)

圣文森特和伊塔尼亚恩

今属巴西圣保罗州

São Vicente was established in 1532 and was the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. It was granted a donatária in 1534. The neighbouring donatárias of Santo Amaro, Santana and Itanhaém were usually held by the donatário of São Vicente. São Vicente (together with Santo Amaro and Santana) were sold to the crown and all became part of the new province of São Paulo e Minas de Ouro. Itanhaém remained a donatário until 1755 when it was annexed to São Paulo as well.

319

Sergipe d’El Rei (1590-1821)

赛尔希培

今巴西赛尔希培州

The area of Sergipe in northeast Brazil was settled from Bahia in 1590. From 1637 to 1648 it was disputed by the Portuguese and the Dutch and thus no organized government existed. Sergipe was governed by capitães-móres who were subornidated to the governor-general (later governor) of Bahia. In 1821 Sergipe was made a separate province, and it became a part of the new Empire of Brazil in the next year.

284

Angola (1575-1975)

安哥拉

安哥拉

Angola coast was discovered in 1482 by Diogo Cão. In 1575 Paulo Dias de Novais was granted an area along the coast as a donatária. At his death in 1589 this territory retroceded to the Portuguese crown, thus began the colony of Angola. [From 1641 to 1648 the Dutch occupied all the Portuguese settlements alone the coast.] in 1837 the governor was raised to the rank of governor-general, and in 1920 high commissioner as well. Sin 1951 Angola was an oversea province of Portugal, and it finally gained its independence in 1975.

288

Cape Verde Islands (1642-1975)

佛得角

佛得角

The Cape Verde Islands was discovered by the Portuguese probably in 1460. In 1495 the islands were parcelled out from the crown as donatárias, and were reverted back to the crown in 1564 and 1586. Already in 1550 the corregedors (magistrates) began in Riberira Grande, the most important donatária. In 1587 a single governor over all islands was appointed. The coast of Africa in what was later to become Portuguese Guinea was settled from Cape Verde Islands and remained under its control until 1879 when Portuguese Guinea became a separate province. In 1951 Cape Verde was constituted an overseas territory of Portugal and finally won its independence in 1975.

290

Ceuta (1415-1580)

休达

今属西班牙

Ceuta was captured by the Portuguese in 1415, and it may be seen as the first small step In what was to become a world-wide occupation of non-European areas by the various European colonial powers. Ceuta remained a Portuguese possession even after Spain rule in Portugal began in 1580. When in 1640 Portugal regained its independence, Ceuta remained in Spanish possession.

291

Ceylon (1518-1658)

锡兰

今斯里兰卡

The ruler of the Kingdom of Kotte solicited the assistance of the Portuguese to fight against its rivals. Portuguese stayed and in 1518 a captain was appointed to Colombo. Finally in 1594 the ruler of Kotte ceded his kingdom to the Portuguese and a governor /captain-general was appointed. In 1619 the Kingdom of Jaffna was annexed by the Portuguese as well. Meanwhile the Kingdom of Kandy in the interior highlands called the Dutch to help in 1638, and finally expelled the Portuguese in 1658 with the capture of Colombo.

295

Hormuz (1515-1622)

霍尔木兹

今属伊朗

The island of Hormuz was occupied by the Portuguese in 1515. It was governed by capitães-móres subject to the authority of the Portuguese viceroy at Goa (Portuguese India). In 1622 Persian forces supported by the English East India Company expelled the Portuguese from Hormuz.

296

Macao (1553-1999)

澳门

今中国澳门特别行政区

Macao was leased from China in 1516. From 1557 to 1623 (except for the periods 1563-65, 1616-17) Macao was governed by the captain of the annual Japan voyage. After 1623 Macao was governed by a resident governor who, until 1844, subordinated to the viceroy of Portuguese India. In 1849 Portugal proclaimed its sovereignty over Macao and ceased paying the annual rent fee to China. China took Macao back in 1999.

298

Malacca (1511-1641)

马六甲

今马来西亚马六甲州

Malacca was seized by the Portuguese in 1511, and it was governed by a capitão-mór subject to the viceroy of Goa (Portuguese India). Malacca was captured by the Dutch in 1641.

302

Mombasa (1593-1631, 1632-1698,1728-1729)

蒙巴萨

今属肯尼亚

Mombasa on the east coast of Africa was occupied by the Portuguese in 1593. It was captured by the Omanis in 1698. The Portuguese regained Mombasa in 1728 but abandoned it in 1729 in the face of a Omani siege.

303

Mozambique (1501-1975)

莫桑比克（葡属东非）

莫桑比克 

The coast of Mozambique in southeast Africa was first sighted by da Gama in 1498 and administration began in 1501. In 1505 a fort was built at Sofala. Mozambique was subect to the viceroy at Goa (Portuguese India) until 1752 when it was created a separate province under a governor/captain-general. In 1951 Mozambique became an overseas territory of Portugal and it gained its independence in 1975.

304

Nova Colônia do Sacramento (1680-1777, 1818-1828)

新萨克拉门托殖民地

今属乌拉圭

In 1680 the Portuguese placed a colony on the north bank of the Plate estuary direct opposite the Spanish colony of Buenos Aires, but it was immediately occupied by the Spaniards and only returned in 1683. From 1705 to 1715 Sacramento was again occupied by the Spaniards, but it was returned by the terms in the Treaty of Utrecht. The Portuguese agreed by the Treaty of Madrid in 1750 to abandon the colony, but it was only implemented in 1777 by the Treaty of San Ildefonso in return for the Spanish acceptance of Portuguese sovereignty in the Amazon hinterland.

308

Portuguese Guinea (1879-1974)

葡属几内亚

今几内亚比绍

The area which became Portuguese Guinea on the west coast of Africa was probably discovered by the Portuguese in 1446, and the settlement was from Cape Verde Islands in the 16th century. In 1614 a capitão-mór was appointed at Cacheu, subject to the governor of the Cape Verde Islands. In 1687 Bissau was established and a capitão-mór was appointed there five years later. From 1707 to 1753 the captaincy of Bissau was suppressed. After 1852 the administration at Cacheu was suppressed when Bissau surpassed it in importance. In 1879 the area was detached from the government of the Cape Verde Islands and erected into the colony of Portuguese Guinea. In 1951 it became an overseas territory of Portugal, and in 1974 it gained its independence as Guinea-Bissau.

309

Portuguese India (1510-1961)

葡属印度

今属印度果阿

Goa on the western coast of India was seized by the Portuguese from the ruler of Bijapur in 1510. Diu and Damão, several hundred miles to the north, were occupied in 1535 and 1538 respectively. These three enclaves formed Portuguese India. The viceror (or governor-general) of Portuguese India at Goa was the supreme authority in the East, governing also Mozambique, Mombasa, Hormuz, Ceylon, Malacca, Timor and Macao at various times. Only until 1961 when the Indian government militarily occupied these enclaves and ended the Portuguese sovereignty.

314

São Jorge da Mina (1482-1638)

圣若热达米纳

今属加纳

In 1482 the Portuguese established a post on the Gold Coast of west Africa, naming it São Jorge da Mina. In 1638 the Dutch seized São Jorge da Mina, and five years later the neighbouring Portuguese post at Axim, thus disappeared Portuguese existence in this region.

317

São Tomé and Príncipe (1470-1975)

圣多美和普林西比

圣多美和普林西比

The islands of São Tomé and Príncipe located in the Gulf of Guinea were discovered by the Portuguese in 1470. São Tomé was granted as a donatária from 1485 to 1522, and Príncipe from 1500 to 1753. São Tomé was ruled by capitães-móres until 1586 when a governor was appointed. After a short occupation of São Tomé between 1641 and 1644 by the Dutch, the whole São Tomé and Príncipe was under Portuguese control since 1648. It was constituted an overseas territory of Portugal in 1951, and gained its independence in 1975.

320

Timor (1642-1975)

帝汶岛

今东帝汶和印度尼西亚东努沙登加拉省

Timor is the largest of the Lesser Sunda Islands, and the western part of it was seized by the Dutch and in 1661 Portugal and the Netherlands decided on the division of the islands in which the Portuguese got the eastern part. Only in 1702 an organized administration was set up by the Portuguese. Timor was subordinated to Portuguese India until 1844 and then under that of Macao from 1844 to 1896. After 1896 it became a separate colony. In 1951 its status changed to an overseas territory of Portugal, and it was occupied and annexed by Indonesia as Timor Timur in 1975.

俄罗斯 Russia

321

Russian America (1799-1867)

俄属北美

今美国阿拉斯加州 

The coast of Russian America was explored in 1741. The Shelekhov-Golikov Company established a post on Kodiak Island to exploit the fur trade in 1784, and was succeeded in 1799 by the Russian-American Company, who began to explore the interior of Alaska after 1833. In 1861 the ownership was assumed by the state after the Russian-American Company failed ti renew its charter to administer the area. After the failure in the Crimean War which emphasized the vulnerability of the remote possession of the Empire, Russia sold the area to the United States in 1867.

西班牙 Spain

327

Canary Islands (1479-

加那利群岛

加那利群岛（西） 

Spanish Sovereignty was recognized by the Treaty of Alcáçovas in 1479, and settlement immediately followed. the islands were governed individually until 1589, when a captain-general was appointed who possessed jurisdiction over the entire archipelago and appointed by the crown. In 1821 the administration was reconstructed and it became a metropolitan province of Spain.

393

Tenerife (1495-

特内里费岛 

今属加那利群岛

Tenerife of the Canary Islands was conquered by the Spaniards in 1495. In 1589 a captain-general was appointed over all islands, but thus lasted only five years. In 1625 this was revived as a permanent role, and the governor of Tenerife was subordinate to the captain-general of the Canary Islands.

340

Gran Canaria

 大加那利岛

今属加那利群岛

Settlement of the Canary Islands in the early 15th century had not reached the island of Gran Canaria, which began to be occupied only in 1480. For a time after 1496 Gran Canaria was subordinated to the adelantado of Tenerife in his capacity as governor of all the islands. In 1589 the office of captain-general of the Canary Islands was created and it was abolished five years later. In 1625 the post was revived permanently and the captain-general ordinarily resided on Gran Canaria.

329

Ceuta (1580-

休达

休达

Ceuta was conquered by the Portuguese in 1415 and remained under its control during Portugal’s union with Spain from 1580 to 1640. When Portugal rebelled in 1640, Ceuta remained loyal to the Spanish crown. The treaty of 1688 which recognized Portuguese independence also confirmed the Spanish possession of Ceuta. In 1847 the captaincy-general of North Africa was created which included all the Spanish enclaves in the area and the governor of Ceuta became captain-general. With the formation of the Spanish zone of Morocco in 1913, Ceuta and Melilla became part of the zone and lost their administrative identity. Since the end of the protectorate in 1956 Ceuta and Melilla have been governed by mayors and are attached to the Spanish provinces of Cádiz and Malaga respectively.

329

Melilla (1497-

梅利利亚

梅利利亚

Melilla was occupied by the Duke of Medina Sidonia in 1497 and was transferred to the Spanish crown in 1556. (following history refer to Ceuta).

360

Nueva España, Viceroyalty (1521-1821)

新西班牙总督辖区

After the conquest of the Aztec, Hernán Cortés was named governor and captain-general of Nueva España. With the expansion, to regulate the government of Nueva España an audiencia was created in 1529 and 6 years later a viceroy was appointed. The viceroy of Nueva España came to have authority over all the Spanish possessions in Mexico, Central America, the Caribbean, the coast of Venezuela, and the Philippine Islands. The jurisdiction included the viceregal audiencia at Mexico City together with that at Guadalajara (Nueva Galicia), Manila (the Philippine Islands), Santo Domingo and Guatemala. In 1810 the revolt against Spanish authority began but these has been suppressed by 1815. The viceroy was finally deposed in 1821 and was replaced by an independent Mexico.

362

Nueva Granada, Viceroyalty (1717-1819)

新格拉纳达总督辖区

In 1525 and 1533 Santa Marta and Cartagena de Indias were founded on the northwest coast of South America. The province of Nueva Reino de Granada was created in 1538. In 1549 an audiencia was established at Santa Fé de Bogotá in Nueva Granada, although a president was not appointed un 1564. The audiencia of Santa Fé was part of the viceroyalty of Peru and it held jurisdiction over the provinces of Santa Marta, Cartagena de Indias and Popayán (in 1563 transferred to the audiencia of Quito). In 1717 Nueva Granada was raised to a viceroyalty, and it had jurisdiction over Nueva Andalucía, Guayana, Venezuela, Mérida-La Grita, Popayán and Quito (which was suppressed), as well as Santa Marta and Cartagena. The viceroyalty was suppressed in 1722 and the various provinces returned to their former allegiances. In 1739 the viceroyalty was re-erected with the same jurisdiction as previously plus Panama. In 1777 the captaincy-general of Venezuela was created and Guayana, Mérida-La Grita, Nueva Andalucía and Venezuela were detached from Nueva Granada and placed under Venezuela. In 1821 the Spanish forces evacuated and Gran Colombia was created, later became Gran ranada in 1830 nd later Colombia.

371

Peru, Viceroyalty (1535-1821)

秘鲁总督辖区

秘鲁

After the conquest of Inca Empire in 1533, an audiencia was established for Lima and a viceroy appointed in 1542. In time the viceroyalty of Peru included all of Spanish South America except for the northern coast of Venezuela and Panama. Included within it were the audiencias of Lima (the viceregal audiencia), Charcas, Chile, Santa Fé (Neuva Granada), Panama, and Quito. In the 18th century the viceroyalties of Nueva Granada and Río de la Plata were created from Peru. The Spanish rule lasted until 1820 when it was defeated and Peru became independent.

381

Río de la Plata, Viceroyalty (1776-1814)

拉普拉塔总督辖区

含今阿根廷、玻利维亚、巴拉圭、乌拉圭等

The viceroyalty of Río de la Plata was established in 1777, and it included the provinces of Buenos Aires, Paraguay, Tucumán, Montevideo, and the Malvinas Islands, together with the presidency of Charcas (detached from Peru), Cuyo (detached from Chile). In 1783 a viceregal audiencia was created in Buenos Aires. In the same year the intendencia system was implemented within the viceroyalty, which was divided into intendencias of Córdoba, Cochabamba, La Paz, Paraguay, Potosí, Salta, Charcas, Buenos Aires, and Puno (transferred to Peru in 1796), and the provinces of Mojos, Chiquitos, Misiones, Montevideo and the Malvinas Islands. The viceroy was ousted from Buenos Aires in 1810 and direct Spanish rule ended. Final independence was formally declared until 1816, and eventually Argentina, Bolivia, Paraguay and Uruguay were established.

332

Chile, Captaincy General (1541-1810, 1814-1818)

智利都督府

智利

Chile was settled by Spanish in 1540 and was initially called Nueva Extremadura, and subordinated to Peru. An audiencia was created at Concepción 1565 but suppressed ten year later. In 1609 an audiencia was revived in Santiago, and in 1778 Chile governor became captain-general. Chile remained under the jurisdiction of the viceroyalty of Peru until the end of Spanish control in 1818.

337

Cuba, Captaincy General (1511-1899)

古巴都督府

古巴

Spain began occupying Cuba in 1511. Until 1533 Cuba was administered by lieutenant governors, from 1535 to 1577 by governors, and from 1579 by governors/captains-general, all subject to the audiencia of Santo Domingo. In 1764 Cuba became a separate captaincy-general with control over province of Louisiana and later of Florida.

When the Santo Domingo audiencia was suppressed in 1797 it was transferred to Puerto Principe on Cuba. In 1898 Cuba was occupied by the United States.

343

Guatemala, Captaincy General (1523-1821)

危地马拉都督府

危地马拉

From 1527 to 1544 Guatemala was under the audiencia of Nueva España, then under the audiencia of the Confines to 1564, and again under Nueva España to 1570. From 1570 on it was the seat of its own audiencia, the successor to that of the Confines. From 1560 on the president of the audiencia possessed the additional rank of captain-general. The captaincy-general of Guatemala had under its jurisdiction the governments of Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Soconusco. After 1786 the intendencia of San Salvador was added to the jurisdiction. In 1821 Guatemala became free of Spanish rule and for two years it was united with Mexico. Thereafter they formed the United States of Central America, and then in 1840 each pf the former provinces became an independent republic.

372

Philippine, Captaincy General (1565-1898)

菲律宾都督府

菲律宾

The Philippine Islands were discovered by Magellan in 1521, and in 1565 an expedition from Nueva España began the occupation for Spain. From 1583 to 1589 and after 1595 there was an audiencia at Manila, the capital, although the Philippine Islands were subject to the viceroy of Nueva España. By 1600 all the major islands except Mindanao and the Sulu archipelago in the south were under Spanish control. There was short occupation of Manila by British troops in 1762. The governor became captain-general in 1783. The intendencia system was introduced in 1786 and the intendencias of Manila, Ilocos, Camarines, Iloilo and Cebu were created but supressed in the next year. In 1898 Spain ceded the Philippine Islands to the United States after the Spanish-American War.

375

Provincias Internas, Captaincy General (1776-1821)

内部省都督府 

今美国西南部及墨西哥北部

The Provincias Intrnas was created in 1777 as a result of Spanish settlement northward away from Mexico City and the military needs, and it included all the northern provinces of Nueva España except California. This new captaincy was headed by a commandant-general and was initially completely independent of the viceroy, while later partically subordinated to it. From 1788 to 1793 and again from 1813 to 1921 the Provincias Internas was divided into eastern and western part for efficiency. After 1793 Nuevo León and Nuevo Santander were removed from it. With all the complexity of management and boundary change with the introduction of the intendencia system in 1787 , the Provincias Internas preserved until the end of the Spanish dominion in Mexico in 1821.

377

Puerto Rico, Captaincy General (1508-1898)

波多黎各都督府

波多黎各（美）

Puerto Rico was discovered by Columbus in 1493. Settlement began in 1509 from Cuba. Together with Cuba, Puerto Rico was ceded to the United States in 1898 when Spain lost the Spanish-American War.

387

Santo Domingo, Captaincy General (1492-1795,1808-1821,1861-1863)

圣多明各都督府

今多米尼加共和国

The island of Hispaniola was discovered by Columbus in 1492 and the city of Santo Domingo was founded in 1496. Initially the island was given to Columbus but it was put under royal control in 1500. An audiencia was established in 1511, suppressed in 1517, and re-established in 1520. The audiencia of Santo Domingo had authority over Cuba, Puerto Rico, and Florida, as well as Mérida-La Grita, Margarita, Nueva Andalucía, Santa Marta, Guayana and Venezuela. (All but the first three were later placed under the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada in 1739.) In 1587 the governor/president of Santo Domingo was also a captain-general. In 1697 the western third of the island was ceded to France by the Treaty of Ryswick. The captaincy-general lost Florida to British in 1763, and Cuba became an independent captaincy-general in the following year. Finally in 1797 the audiencia was removed to Puerto Principe on Cuba. In 1801 Haiti (in French part of the island) occupied Santo Domingo, while Spain recovered it in 1809, but lost it in 1821 to revolutionary elements in Santo Domingo itself. It was re-occupied by Haiti in 1822 and finally gained its independence as Dominican Republic in 1844.

399

Venezuela, Captaincy General (1528-1811, 1812-1816)

委内瑞拉都督府

委内瑞拉

The coast of Venezuela was explored by the Spaniards in 1499. In 1528 the area was granted to a German banking family, the Welsers, and remained nominally under their control until 1556. Until 1717, and from 1723 to 1730, it was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Santo Domingo. From 1717 to 1723 and fom 1739 to 1742 it was under the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada. After 1742 Venezuela was under the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada but the audiencia of Santo Domingo. In 1777 Venezuela was raised to a captaincy-general, and in 1786 its own audiencia at Caracas. The captain-general of Venezuela has jurisdiction over the provinces of Maracaibo, Barinas, Guayana, Trinidad (to 1797), Margarita, and Nueva Andalucía. In 1820 the Spanish were finally expelled andVenezuela became part of Gran Colombia. On the dissolution of Gran Colombia the former provinces under the captaincy-general united to form the independent Venezuela.

401

Yucatán, Captaincy General (1565-1821)

尤卡坦都督府

今墨西哥尤卡坦州

The Yucatán peninsula in extreme southeastern Mexico was discovered by the Spaniards in 1517, and settlement began in 1527. From 1527 to 1543 Yucatán was under the audiencia of Mexico (Nueva España), then under that of Los Confines (Guatemala) to 1549, Mexico to 1550, Guatemala from 1550 to 1560, and after 1560 that of Mexico. The province was ruled by governors except for the period from 1549 to 1565 when alcaldes mayores governed it. In 1617 the governor gained the rank of captaion-general. With the intendencia system introduced in 1787, Yucatán became the intendencia of Mérida, until in 1821 it became a part of Mexico.

326

California (1768-1804)

加利福尼亚（新西班牙）

今美国加利福尼亚州和墨西哥下加利福尼亚州

Alta California (1804-1821)

上加利福尼亚（新西班牙）

今美国加利福尼亚州

Baja California (1804-1821)

下加利福尼亚（新西班牙）

今墨西哥下加利福尼亚州

By 1543 the entire cost of both Baja and Alta California had been explored by the Spaniards, but the serious occupation began in 1767. The two provinces were excluded from the control of the commandant-general of the Provincias Internas. Until 1804 they were ruled jointly, and then separated. Alta California fell into the United States in 1846, while Baja California continues to be a state of Mexico.

331

Chiapas (1528-1821)

恰帕斯（新西班牙）

今墨西哥恰帕斯州

Chiapas became part of the captaincy-general of Guatemala in 1529 and remained so till 1821. It became an intendencia in 1786 when the intendencia system was introduced. Together with Guatemala, Chiapas joined Mexico when Spanish rule finished. When Guatemala broke with Mexico, Chiapas remained as part of Mexico.

333

Coahuila (1575-1821)

科阿韦拉（新西班牙）

今墨西哥科阿韦拉州

Coahuila in northern Mexico was first settled by the Spaniards in 1575. In 1674 the area was detached from Nueva Vizcaya and erected into a separate province. In 1777 Coahuila fell under the jurisdiction of the Provincias Internas and remained so until 1822. After that it became a state in Mexico.

342

Guanajuato (1787-1821)

瓜纳华托（新西班牙）

今墨西哥瓜纳华托州

Guanajuato in central Mexico was created as intendencia within the viceroyalty of Nueva España in 1787. It remained an intendencia until 1821 when it became part of Mexico.

361

Nueva Galicia (1531-1821)

新加利西亚（新西班牙）

今属墨西哥阿瓜斯卡连特斯州、瓜纳华托州、科利马州、哈利斯科州等

The area of Nueva Galicia, west of Mexico City, was conquered by the Spaniards after 1530. From 1545 to 1549 it was reduced to an alcaldia mayor, and then an audiencia was created for Nueva Galicia but only until 1574 a governor/president was appointed. In 1708 the governor/president became captain-general as well. In 1787 the intendencia of Guadalajara was created with the governor/president of Nueva Galicia as intendent. In 1821 Guadalajara became a part of Mexico.

364

Nuevo León (1582-1821)

新莱昂（新西班牙）

新莱昂州

The province of Nuevo Reino de León was created in 1582 in northern Mexico from the earlier province of Nueva Vizcaya, and placed under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Nueva Galicia. In 1777 Nuevo León became part of the newly-created Provincias Internas, but was detached in 1793. Nuevo León remained a province of the viceroyalty of Nueva España until 1821 when it became part of Mexico.

365

Nuevo México (1598-1821)

新墨西哥（新西班牙）

今美国新墨西哥州

The settlement of the upper Rio Grande in the extreme northern portion of the viceroyalty of Nueva España began in 1598, and it was named Nuevo México and was part of Nueva Vizcaya. It remained something of a frontier outpost and virtually abandoned during 1680 and 1696. The province of Nuevo México was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Nueva Galicia within the viceroyalty of Nueva España. In 1777 Nuevo México became part of newly-created Provincias Internas. Spanish authority ended in 1822 when Nuevo México became part of Mexico.

366

Nuevo Santander (1748-1821)

新桑坦德（新西班牙）

今属墨西哥塔毛利帕斯州和美国得克萨斯州

The settlement in the area northeastern coast south of the Rio Grande within Nueva España was occupied in 1746 amd the province of Nuevo Santander was created. It was part of the Provincias Internas until 1793 when it was placed again under the direct rule of the viceroyalty of Nueva España. After 1812 Neuvo Santander was directly administered by the commandant-general of the Provincias Internas, and finally in 1821 became part of Mexico.

363

Nueva Vizcaya (1562-1821)

新比斯开（新西班牙）

今属墨西哥奇瓦瓦州和杜兰戈州

The area of Nueva Vizcaya in northcentral Mexico was settled from 1562. Initially the province covered northern part of the viceroyalty of Nueva España but as settlement moved north, Nuevo, Nuevo México, Coahuila and Sinaloa and Sonora were established as separate provinces. In 1777 Nueva Vizcaya became part of the Provincias Internas, and upon the creation of the intendencia system in Nueva España in 1786, Nueva Vizcaya became the intendencia of Durango. In 1821 this area became part of Mexico.

367

Oaxaca (1787-1821)

瓦哈卡（新西班牙）

今墨西哥瓦哈他州

The alcaldia mayor of Oaxaca was made an intendencia of the viceroyalty of Nueva España in 1787. Oaxaca remained its status until 1821 when Mexico became independent and it was a state of Mexico.

376

Puebla (1787-1821)

普埃布拉州（新西班牙）

今墨西哥普埃布拉州

The alcaldia mayor of Puebla in eastern Mexico was created an intendencia of the viceroyalty of Nueva España in 1787. In 1821 it became part of Mexico.

383

San Luis Potosí (1787-1821)

圣路易斯波托西（新西班牙）

今墨西哥圣路易斯波托西州

The intendencia of San Luis Potosí was created in 1787 within the viceroyalty of Nueva España. In 1821 it became part of Mexico.

388

Sinaloa and Sonora (1732-1821)

锡那罗亚和索诺拉（新西班牙）

今墨西哥锡那罗亚州和索诺拉州

Sinaloa and Sonora in northwestern Mexico was explored as early as 1530 but not settled until later in the century. Sinaloa and Sonora was part of the viceroyalty of Nueva España, and in 1732 the territory was separated from Nueva Vizcaya and created a separate province under the audiencia of Nueva Galicia. After 1777 Sinoloa and Sonora formed part of the Provincias Internas. In 1787 this area became an intendencia of Sonora. In 1821 it became part of Mexico.

Tabasco (1525-1821)

塔巴斯科（新西班牙）

今墨西哥塔巴斯科州

394

Texas (1682-1821)

得克萨斯（新西班牙）

今美国得克萨斯州 

The first permanent Spanish settlement in Texas occurred in 1682. In 1716 Texas was separated from Coahuila and created a separate province. Texas was subordinated to the commandant-general of Provincias Internas, under Nueva España. In 1821 Texas came under the control of Mexico.

Tlaxcala (1585-1821)

特拉斯卡拉（新西班牙）

今墨西哥特拉斯卡拉州

398

Valladolid (1787-1821)

巴利亚多利德（新西班牙）

今墨西哥米却肯州

The Michoacán region of central Mexico was formed into the intendencia of Valladolid in 1787, and it became a state of Mexico in 1821.

400

Vera Cruz (1787-1821)

维拉克鲁斯（新西班牙）

今墨西哥维拉克鲁斯州

Vera Cruz was created an intendencia within the viceroyalty of Nueva España in 1787. It remained this until Mexico independence in 1821.

402

Zacatecas (1787-1821)

萨卡特卡斯（新西班牙）

今墨西哥萨卡特卡斯州 

The alcaldia mayor of Zacatecas was raised to an intendencia in the viceroyalty of Nueva España in 1787. It remained this until Mexico independence in 1821.

322

Antioquia (1537-1811)

安蒂奥基亚

今哥伦比亚安蒂奥基亚省

Antioquia was first penetrated by Spaniards in 1537. Until 1579 Antioquia was part of the Province of Popayán, and then it was a separate province subject to the audiencia of Santa Fé (later the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada). As a result of the independence war it became part og Gran Colombia.

323

Arequipa (1784-1825)

阿雷基帕

 今属秘鲁

Intendency of Arequipa within Viceroyalty of Peru in 1784, and it was one of the last areas in South American to be evacuated by Spanish troops and only became part of Peru in 1825.

324

Barinas (1786-1810)

巴里纳斯

今委内瑞拉巴里纳斯州

Province of Barinas, created in the Captaincy-General of Venezuela in 1782, as last separate province created in Venezuela. In 1819 it became part of Gran Colombia, and later of Republic of Venezuela.

325

Buenos Aires (1618-1776)

布宜诺斯艾利斯

今阿根廷布宜诺斯艾利斯州

In 1618 the province of Río de la Plata was divided into the provinces of Paraguay and Buenos Aires (also called Río de la Plata). An audiencia was established at Buenos Aires in 1661 and it was abolished in 1671. For other than this decade, Buenos Aires was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Charcas. When the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata was created in 1777, it included Buenos Aires, as well as Paraguay, Tucumán and areas detached from the viceroyalty of Peru.

328

Cartagena de Indias

卡塔赫纳

今属哥伦比亚

The city of Cartagena was founded on the northern coast of Colombia in 1533. It was under the audiencia of Santa Fé after its creation in 1549. Later it became part of the viceroyalty of Neuva Granada. In 1811 Cartagena became independent, only to fall again to Spanish control from 1816 to 1821 when it became part of Gran Colombia.

330

Charcas

查尔卡斯

今属玻利维亚

The audiencia de los Charcas was created in 1559 to administer the vast territories of Upper Peru. Except for the period from 1661 to 1671, when an audiencia was created for Río de la Plata, Charcas embraced most of the territory which later became Bolivia, Paraguay and Argentina. Charcas was subject to the viceroyalty of Peru until 1777 when Río de la Plata was made a viceroyalty Charcas was transferred to its jurisdiction. The area was occupied by forces of the United Provinces of Río de la Plata in 1819 but was reoccupied by royalist in 1816. In 1824 last Spanish authority was terminated and the much reduced audiencia became part of Bolivia.

334

Cochabamba

科恰班巴 

今属玻利维亚

The intendencia of Cochabamba was created in 1783 within Río de la Plata. Spanish authority ended after 1810, and in 1825 Cochabamba became part of Bolivia.

335

Córdoba

 科尔多瓦

今阿根廷科尔多瓦省

In 1783 with the introduction of the intendencia system in the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata, the province of Tucumán was divided into two parts, Córdoba in the south and Salta in the north. The intendent of Córdoba was deposed in 1810 and eventually became part of Argentina.

336

Costa Rica (1568-1821)

哥斯达黎加

哥斯达黎加

Costa Rica was discovered by Columbus in 1502, initially called Nueno Cartego, and in 1568 it was made a province under the audiencia of Guatemala. Costa Rica remained a simple province till 1821 when it became part of the independent United State of Central America and later became a separate republic.

338

Cuzco

库斯科

今属秘鲁

Cuzco, the former Inca capital, became the seat of an intendencia with an audiencia in 1784. In 1824 Cuzco became part of Peru.

339

Florida (1565-1763, 1783-1821)

佛罗里达

今美国佛罗里达州

In 1565 the Spanish settled in the east coast after destroying the French settlement, and named it Florida. Florida was ceded to the United Kingdom after the Seven Year’s War in 1763. During the Wars of American Revolution Spain occupied British West Florida, and in 1783 East Florida was ceded to Spain by the Treaty of Paris. Both were sold to the United States in 1819. During the period from 1784 to 1821 the Florida were subject to the captain-general of Cuba.

341

Guam (1668-1898)

关岛

今关岛（美）

The Guam was probably discovered by Magellan in 1521, but it was only in 1668 the Spaniards seriously attempted to occupy the island. Guam and the Mariana Islands were subordinate to the government of the Philippines. As a result of the Spanish-American War, Guam was ceded to the United States in 1898 while the rest of the Marianas were sold to Germany (German New Guinea).

344

Guayana

圭亚那（委内瑞拉）

今委内瑞拉圭亚那州

The province of Guayana in eastern Venezuela was formed in 1591. Until 1735 the province included the nearby island of Trinidad, when Trinidad became a separate province. From 1735 to 1762 the province of Guayana was suppressed and placed under the contiguous province of Nueva Andalucía. From its creation in 1591 until 1766 Guayana was subordinate to Nueva Granada and then it was transferred to the captaincy-general of Venezuela. Guayana remained under Spanish control until 1817 when it became part of Gran Colombia and later part of Venezuela.

345

Guayaquil

 瓜亚基尔

今属厄瓜多尔

The port of Guayaquil was founded in 1535 and was a corregimiento under the audiencia of Quito unil 1763 when it was raised to the status of a province. The Spanish rule was ended in 1820 and Guayaquil became part of Gran Colombia until 1830 when Ecuador gained its independence.

346

Honduras (1528-1821)

洪都拉斯

洪都拉斯

Honduras was discovered by Columbus in 1502. It was subject to the audiencia of Nueva España from 1528 to 1539 and thereafter of the audiencia of the Confines (later Guatemala). In 1786 Honduras became the intendencia of Comayagua. The intendencia was suppressed in 1812, and until 1821 the province was an alcaldia mayor. In 1821 together with other province sunder the captaincy-general of Guatemala, Honduras became part of Mexico, and then divided United States of Central America. In 1840 Honduras became a separate republic.

347

Huamanga

瓦曼加

今秘鲁瓦曼加省

Huamanga in southern Peru was one of the eight intendencias created within the viceroyalty of Peru in 1784. After 1824 it became part of Peru.

348

Huancavelica

万卡韦利卡

今秘鲁万卡韦利卡省

Huancavelica in central Peru became one of the intendencies of the viceroyalty of Peru. In 1824 the region was occupied by nationalist forces and became part of Peru.

349

Ifni (1860-1969)

伊夫尼

今属摩洛哥

From 1478 to 1524 Spain occupied the post of Santa Cruz de la Mar Pequeña on the Moroccan coasdt opposite the Canary Islands. In 1860 the Spaniards persuaded the Sultan of Morocco to recognize the right of Spain to reoccupy the area, but the real occupation of this area, known as Ifni, was only implemented in 1934. In 1952 Ifni became a part of Spanish West Africa, which in 1958 was divided into Spanish Sahara and Ifni. Ifni was retroceded to Morocco in 1969.

350

Jamaica (1509-1655)

牙买加

牙买加

The island of Jamaica in the western Caribbean was discovered by Columbus in 1494 and subsequently granted to him and his descendants, the Dukes of Veragua. The governor of Jamaica was appointed by the Duke with the approval of the Spanish monarch. In 1655 it was attacked by the English. By 1650 the Spaniards were driven out of the island, and Jamaica became part of British Empire.

351

La Paz

拉巴斯

今属玻利维亚

The intendencia of La Paz within the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata was organized in 1793. After the transfer of Puno from Río de la Plata to Peru in 1796, La Paz became the most northwesterly intendencia in Río de la Plata. The Spanish rule was only ended by 1825 and La Paz became part of Bolivia.

352

Louisiana(1762-1800)

路易斯安那

今美国中部诸州

France ceded its colony to Spain in 1762, and Spain took over administration only in 1765. Louisiana was under the government of Cuba. Spain retroceded Louisiana to France in 1800 by the Treaty of San Ildefonso, and France took back possession in 1803, but soon sold it to the United States.

353

Malvinas Islands (1767-1811)

马尔维纳斯群岛

今福克兰群岛（英）

The islands were discovered by the English in 1592 and it was named Falkland Islands by them in 1708. The French, who call them Îles Malouines, established a post on East Falkland 1764, but abandoned it and transferred the settlement to Spain in 1767. The Spanish called them follow the French name, so Islas Malvinas. British abandoned its post in 1774 and Spain took possession of the islands, which were put under the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata. The islands remained in Spanish possession until 1810 when the Spanish governor fled, and finally the islands were fully occupied by the British in 1833.

354

Margarita

玛格丽塔岛

今属委内瑞拉

Margarita, a small island off the coast of Venezuela, was granted to the Villalobos family in 1525 and continued to be governed privately until 1600 when it reverted to the Spanish crown. Until 1739 the province of Margarita was subject to the audiencia of Santo Domingo, and from 1739 to 1777 it was under the audiencia of Santa Fé (Nueva Granada). Margarita fell under the jurisdiction of the captaincy-general of Venezuela when it was created in 1777. The Spanish control ceased in 1820, and in 1821 eventually it became part of the Venezuelan state of Nueva Esparta.

355

Mérida-La Grita

梅里达-拉格里塔

今属委内瑞拉苏利亚省

In 1575 the province of Espíritu Santo de La Grita was created under the audiencia of Santa Fé (Nueva Granada). This province was suppressed in 1608 and La Grita was united with Mérida to form a corregimiento. In 1625 Mérida-La Grita was raised to a provice. In 1676 Maracaibo was detached from Venezuela and added to Mérida-La Grita. The governor and captain-general (from 1625) moved to Maracaibo in 1678 and the province name was changed to Maracaibo in 1751. Untill 1777 the province was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Santa Fé and then it ws placed under the new captaincy-general of Venezuela. Spanish rule was ended in 1811 with no organized government. In 1819 it became part of Gran Colombia and later of Venezuela.

356

Montevideo

蒙得维的亚

今属乌拉圭

Montevideo on the north side of Río de la Plata was founded in 1726 and it was raised to the rank of a province in 1751. After the expulsion from Buenos Aires in 1810 the viceroy of Río de la Plata moved to Montevideo, but in 1814 the Spanish authority ended there as well. Eventually in 1830 the area became independent as Uruguay.

357

Morocco (1912-1956)

摩洛哥

摩洛哥

After France proclaimed a protectorate over most of Morocco in 1912, a Franco-Spanish agreement delimited a zone of Spanish control in the northern part of Morocco named Spanish Southern Zone alone the Mediterranean coast. After 1934 the high commissioner for the Spanish zone has jurisdiction over Spanish West Africa as well. In 1956 follow the French withdrawal, Spain also quitted its rights to the Spanish zone, while keeping Ceuta and Melilla..

358

Nicaragua (1522-1821)

尼加拉瓜

尼加拉瓜

The coast of Nicaragua was discovered by Columbus in 1502, and the settlement began in 1522. Until 1538 it was subject to the audiencia of Santo Domingo, to that of Panama from 1538 to 1544, and after 1544 to that of the Confines (later Guatemala). In 1786 the captaincy-general of Guatemala introduced the intendencia system and the governor of Nicaragua became the governor/intendent of León. In 1821 when Spanish authority was expelled, Nicaragua became part of Mexico as a member of the United States of Central America. Finally in 1839 Nicaragua gained its independence as a republic.

359

Nueva Andalucía

新安达卢西亚

今属委内瑞拉

The area of Nueva Andalucía in eastern Venezuela was settled by the Spaniards after 1521, and the province itself was only created in 1569. Nueva Andalucía was under the audiencia of Santo Domingo until 1739 when it fell under the that of Santa Fé in the newly created viceroyalty of Nueva Granada. In 1777 it became part of the captaincy-general of Venezuela. Finally in 1821 Nueva Andalucía became part of Gran Colombia and later of Venezuela.

368

Orán (1509-1708, 1732-1792)

奥兰

今属阿尔及利亚 

Orán, a city on the northern coast of Africa was occupied by Spain in 1509. Except for the period from 1708 to 1732 when Orán was captured by the Turks, it remained a Spanish possession until 1792 when it was abandoned.

369

Panama (1501-1821)

巴拿马

巴拿马

The isthmus of Panama was discovered by the Spaniards in 1501, and was created a province (often called Tierra Firme and Castilla de Oro) in 1513. An audiencia was created in Panama in 1538 and suppressed four years later. In 1567 the audiencia was revived and placed under the viceroyalty of Peru. The audiencia was briefly abolished in 1718, restored in 1722 and finally suppressed in 1751, while remained as a separate province. With the recreation of the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada in 1739, Panama fell under its jurisdiction and remained so till 1821, when it became part of Gran Colombia (later Colombia). Finally Panama gained its independence in 1903.

370

Paraguay (1535-1813)

巴拉圭

巴拉圭

Paraguay was under the province of Río de la Plata until 1618 when Buenos Aires and Paraguay were made separate provinces. Both were under the audiencia of Charcas except for the years from 1661 to 1771 when there’s a separate audiencia of Buenos Aires. The province was divided between the Spaniards and the Portuguese (Rio Grande do Sul) in the 1760s. In 1783 Paraguay became an intendencia within the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata and subject to the new audiencia in Buenos Aires. In 1811 the governor/intendant was driven out and Parguay became an independent country.

373

Popayán

波帕扬

今属哥伦比亚

Popayán, the area of southwestern Colombia was settled from Peru after 1536 and erected into the province of Popayán in 1541. In 1549 Popayán fell under the jurisdiction of the newly created audiencia of Santa Fé (Nueva Granada), but remained so only until 1563 when the audiencia of Quito was created. In 1717 with the suppression of the Quito audiencia, Popayán became part of the new viceroyalty of Nueva Granada. In 1820 Spanish authority was eliminated and Popayán became part of Gran Colombia (later Colombia).

374

Potosí

波托西

今属玻利维亚

The area of Potosí was transferred from the viceroyalty of Peru to the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata in 1777. In 1783 it was created an intendencia. It was deposed in 1810 and was disputed between Spanish and nationalist forces. Finally most of the area became part of Bolivia and some lost to Chile.

378

Puno

普诺

今秘鲁普诺省

Puno was first created an intendencia within the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata in 1783. In 1786 it was transferred to the viceroyalty of Peru due to its extreme distance to Buenos Aires. Spanish control was retained until 1824 after which it became part of Peru.

379

Quito (1532-1820)

基多

今厄瓜多尔 

Quito was occupied by the Spaniards in 1533. It was administered by a series of lieutenant governors until 1556 when it became a province. In 1563 it was erected into an audiencia under the viceroyalty of Peru. In 1767 the governor/president became captain-general as well. In 1718 the audiencia was suppressed and Quito came under the jurisdiction of the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada. The audiencia of Quito was reconstituted in 1722 when the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada was suppressed. When the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada was reestablished in 1739, Quito fell back into its control but remained as an audiencia. Spanish control was finally ended in 1822, and Quito became part of Gran Colombia until 1830 when Ecuador won independence.

380

Río de la Plata, Province (1536-1618)

拉普拉塔省

今阿根廷 

Buenos Aires was founded in 1536, abandoned the following year, and re-founded in 1580 and came to be the seat of the governor of Río de la Plata. The province of Río de la Plata was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Charcas. In 1618 it was divided into provinces of Buenos Aires and Paraguay.

382

Salta

萨尔塔

今阿根廷萨尔塔省

Salta was divided from the old province of Tucumán when the intendencia system was introduced in the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata in 1783. After 1810 Salta was no longer under Spanish control and later became part of Argentina.

384

San Salvador

圣萨尔瓦多

今萨尔瓦多

The area of San Salvador, part of the captaincy-general of Guatemala, was erected into an intendencia in 1786. It remained so until the independence of the United States of Central America and then it became El Salvador.

385

Santa Catalina

圣卡塔琳娜岛

今属哥伦比亚圣安德列斯-普罗维登西亚和圣卡塔利娜群岛省

The island of Santa Catalina was held by the English, who called it Providence, from 1630 to 1641. The Spanish authority of Nueva Granada seized the island in 1641. During the period 1641 to 1670 the island was under the jurisdiction of the audiencia of Panama, and then it was briefly occupied by the English again. In 1688 Spain reoccupied the island but not constituted a separate province any more.

386

Santa Marta- Río Hacha

圣玛尔塔-里奥阿查

今属哥伦比亚

The town of Santa Marta in northern Colombia was founded in 1525 and the province was known as Santa Marta- Río Hacha since 1600. Santa Marta remained under the audiencia of Santo Domingo until 1740 (except from 1719 to 1723), and then it was part of the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada and its audiencia of Santa Fé. It became the seat of the viceroyalty of Nueva Granada when the viceroy was expelled, and in 1821 the Spanish forces are fully expulsed and Santa Marta became a province of Gran Colombia (later Colombia).

389

Spanish Guinea (1885-1968)

西属几内亚

今赤道几内亚

Spanish Guinea consisted of the islands of Fernando Pó and Annobón, and the small coastal enclave known as Río Muni. The islands were discovered by the Portuguese in 1472 and later disputed by the two countries until 1777 Treaty of San Ildefonso it was definitely ceded to Spain. Spanish administration only began in 1855. In 1959 it became an oversea province of Spain, and in 1963 internal autonomy was granted, with name changed to Equatorial Guinea and the governor became high commissioner. In 1968 Equatorial Guinea gained its independence.

390

Spanish Sahara (1958-1976)

西属撒哈拉

今西撒哈拉

In 1958 Spanish West Africa was dissolved and divided into the provinces of Ifni and Spanish Sahara. Spain withdrew from this area in 1976 and left the conflict between Morocco and Mauritania.

391

Spanish West Africa (1860-1958)

西属西非

今西撒哈拉

The area of Río de Oro was discovered by the Portuguese in the early 15th century. In 1860 Spain secured vague rights in the area from Morocco and in 1884 they proclaimed a protectorate over the coast. In 1934 the Ifni enclave was settled to under Spanish West Africa until 1958 when then latter was divided into Spanish Sahara and Ifni.

392

Tarma

塔尔玛

今秘鲁塔尔玛省

Tarma was one of the eight intendencias created within the viceroyalty of Peru in 1894. It remained so until 1823 wnen Peru gained independence.

395

Trinidad (1498-1797)

特立尼达 

今属特立尼达和多巴哥

The island of Trinidad off the coast of Venezuela was discovered by Columbus in 1498. A governor was appointed in 1532 but no settlement effected until much later. Trinidad was part of the province of Guayana until 1735 when it was created a separate province. Until 1739 it was under Santo Domingo, then under Nueva Granada until 1777 when it became part of the new captaincy-general of Venezuela. In 1797 Trinidad was conquered by British forces and later this was confirmed by the Treaty of Amiens in 1802.

396

Trujillo

特鲁希略

今属秘鲁

Trujillo was the most northerly of all the intendencias created in the viceroyalty of Peru in 1784. In 1821 it became part of Peru.

397

Tucumán

图库曼

今阿根廷图库曼省

The area of Tucumán in northern Argentina was settled from Peru and was erected a province in 1550. Until 1776 Tucumán was subject to the audiencia of Charcas. It fell into the jurisdiction the viceroyalty of Río de la Plata when the viceroyalty was created in 1777. When the intendencia system was introduced in 1783, Tucumán was divided into Córdoba and Salta, and it ceased to exist as an administrative unit.

瑞典 Sweden

403

New Sweden (1638-1655)

新瑞典

含今美国特拉华州、宾夕法尼亚州以及新泽西州一部

New Sweden on the Delaware River was fostered and initially governed by disaffected Dutchmen who had left the service of the Dutch West India Company’s colony of New Netherlands, supported by the Swedish South Company. In 1655 it was captured by the nearby Dutch colony of New Netherlands

404

Saint Barthélemy (1785-1801, 1802-1878)

圣巴泰勒米

今圣巴泰勒米（法） 

The French sold Saint Barthélemy, which is one of the Leeward Islands in the northern Lesser Antilles and located about 200 miles east of Puerto Rico, to Swden in 1784 in return for trading concessions in the Sweidish port of Goteborg. Sweden tried to sell it to the United States several time in 1845, 1868, and 1870 due to the cost issue, but all failed. Finally in 1878 France repurchased and incorporated it as a dependent of Guadeloupe.

美国 United States

405

American Samoa (1900-

美属萨摩亚

美属萨摩亚 

American Samoa was acquired as a result of the 1900 Tripartite Treaty between the United States, Great Britain and Germany, which specified that all islands of the Samoan group situated east of longitude 171 degree were to be in the American sphere. American Samoa was under a naval governor under the Department of Navy until 1951 due to its strategic importance, and then followed by a civilian governor under the authority of the Department of the Interior, as an unincorporated island territory.

406

Guam (1898-

关岛

关岛（美）

Guam was under Spain from 1668 to 1898. As a result of the Spanish-American War of 1898 the island fell under the control of the United States. Similar to American Samoa, Guam was under a naval governor until 1950 when a civilian governor under the authority of the Department of the Interior was appointed to govern the island.

Guantanamo Bay (1898-

关塔那摩湾

关塔那摩湾（美）

With the occupation of Cuba by the United States in 1898, the Guantanamo Bay was leased to the United States in 1903. In 1934 a new treaty affirmed that the U.S. held a perpetual sovereignty over this naval bay unless a mutual agreement or U.S abandonment can terminate the lease, and this was reaffirmed again in 1963.

Midway Island (1867-

中途岛

中途岛（美）

Northern Mariana Islands (1944-

北马里亚纳群岛

北马里亚纳群岛（美）

410

Puerto Rico (1898-

波多黎各

波多黎各（美）

The United States acquired Puerto Rico at the end of the Spanish-American War in 1898. The island was under military government from 1898 to 1901, and then under civilian rule. In 1947 Puerto Rico was granted the right to elect their governors and in 1952 it became a commonwealth of the United States,

412

Virgin Islands (1917-

美属维尔京群岛

美属维尔京群岛

The U.S. Virgin Islands were bought from Denmark in 1917. Until 1931 the islands were administered by a naval governor, thereafter by a civilian appointed by the Department of the Interior until 1971 when they had a elected governor.

Wake Island (1898-

威克岛

威克岛（美）

Swains Island (1856-

斯温斯岛

今属美属萨摩亚

407

Micronesian Trust Territory (1947-1994)

太平洋群岛托管地

含今马绍尔群岛、密克罗尼西亚联邦、帕劳、北马里亚纳群岛（美）

The Micronesian Trust Territory was the former Japanese Pacific Islands Mandate, which was granted to the United States as a trusteeship by the United Nations in 1947 as, in fact, Japan had similarly received the mandate from the League of Nations in 1921. It was composed of the Marshall Islands, Caroline Islands, Wake Island, Marcus Island and the Mariana Islands, except Guam which is governed separately. Until 1951 the commander-in-chief of the Pacific Fleet stationed in Hawaii was ex officio high commissioner, although until 1949 a deputy high commissioner was stationed at Guam. In 1951 the trust territory fell under the jurisdiction of the Department of the Interior and a civilian high commissioner was appointed who resided at Saipan in the Mariana Islands. Federated States of Micronesia and Marshall Islands gained their autonomy in 1979 and Palau was proclaimed a republic in 1981. The high commissioner retired in 1987, and the trusteeship for Micronesia and Marshall Islands ended in 1990 and that of Palau ended in 1994. The Mariana Islands became a commonwealth in political union with the United States in 1978, and it cam under U.S. sovereignty in 1986.

408

Panama Canal Zone (1903-1979)

巴拿马运河区

今属巴拿马 

By the 1903 Hay–Bunau Varilla Treaty, the United States was granted in perpetuity a strip of land across the isthmus on which to build an interoceanic canal. The civil administration of the Canal Zone was in the hands first of governors and then of civil heads of the administration. Since the completion of the canal in 1914 it was administered by a general officer of the U.S. Army who served ex officio as the president of the Panama Canal Company. In 1979 the canal was returned to Panama under the 1977 Panama Canal Treaty, but the U.S kept the operational control for another twenty years till 1999.

409

Philippine Islands (1898-1946)

菲律宾群岛

菲律宾

The United States won the Philippine Islands in 1898 war with the Spanish. From 1898 to 1901 it was under a military government, and from 1901 to 1935 by a governor-general approved by the President of the United States.in 1935 the Philippine Islands were declared a commonwealth and the governor-general replaced by a high commissioner and a president elected by the Filipinos. From 1942 to 1945 it was occupied by the Japanese. In 1946 Philippines were made independent.

411

Ryukyu Islands (1945-1972)

琉球群岛

今属日本冲绳县 

The Ryukyu Islands was annexed by the Japanese and became a prefect of Japan in 1879. After World War II it was occupied by the American forces. It was under military rule and the commander-in-chief of the Far Eastern Command served ex officio as governor, while the commanding general of the islands’ garrison served as deputy governor. In 1952 civil administration was introduced but until 1962 the civil administrator was a general officer of the U.S. Army. In 1957 a high commissioner was appointed who was also always a high ranking general officer of the army. The sovereignty was fully returned to Japan in 1972 and it became the prefecture of Okinawa.

Others

Courlander Gambia (1651-1660, 1660-1661)

库尔兰属冈比亚

今属冈比亚

In 1651 Duke Jakob of Courland purchased an island at the mouth of the Gambia River and established trading forts. In 1659 the possessions were, due to the captivity of the duke and the consequent inability of the government to administer them, leased to the Dutch West India Company. The Courland commandant made a very short return, but in 1661 it was finally expelled by the English, and this was retained in 1664.

Courlander Tobago (1654-1659, 1680-1690)

库尔兰属多巴哥

今属特立尼达和多巴哥

Courland tried to settle on the island of Tobago for several times (1637, 1639, 1642) but all failed. In 1654 a settlement was established and named New Courland and in 1659 the Courlanders were expelled by the Dutch. It was agreed in 1660 Treaty of Oliwa that Tobago to be returned to the Courlander, but it was abandoned by 1666 after a pirate raid. Courland occupied Tobago again in 1680, but they permanently left in 1689.

Brandenburg/Prussian Gold Coast (1682-1717)

普鲁士属黄金海岸

今属加纳

Brandenburg established several posts along the Guinea coast of West Africa, with headquarter at Gross Friedrichsburg, established in 1682. It was named Brandenburger Gold Coast Settlements until 1701 when it was renamed Prussian Gold Coast Settlements with the establishment of the Prussian Kingdom which replaced the Brandenburg. The Prussian abandoned and sold it to the Dutch in 1717.

非洲与马尔加什共同组织 African and Malagasy Common Organization (OCAM)

15 Dec 1960

African and Malagasy Organization for Economic Cooperation (Organisation Africaine et Malgache de Coopération Économique)(OAMCE) established.

12 Sep 1961

African and Malagasy Union (Union Africaine et Malgache)(UAM).

10 Mar 1964

African and Malagasy Union for Economic Cooperation (Union Africaine et Malgache de Coopération Économique)(UAMCE); established in succession to OAMCE; charter signed 29 Apr 1964.

12 Feb 1965

African and Malagasy Common Organization (Organisation Commune Africaine et Malgache)(OCAM), established as merger of UAMCE and UAM (charter signed 27 Jun 1966, enters into force 28 Dec 1967).

1970

Renamed African, Malagasy and Mauritian Common Organization (Organisation Commune Africaine, Malgache et Mauricienne)(OCAMM).

1973

Renamed African and Mauritian Common Organization (Organisation Commune Africaine et Mauricienne)(OCAM).

23 Mar 1985

Formally dissolved.

4 Aug 1963

African Development Bank agreement signed.

欧洲联盟 European Union (EU)

18 Apr 1951                European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC) founded.
10 Sep 1952                Common Assembly of the European Coal and Steel Community (with
                             Common Assembly of the European Coal and Steel Community) opens.
 1 Jan 1958                European Economic Community (EEC) founded (with European
                             Parliamentary Assembly 19 Mar 1958 - 30 Mar 1962, from
                             30 Mar 1962, European Parliament) .
 1 Jul 1967                EEC joined with European Coal and Steel Community and European
                             Atomic Community to form the European Communities (from
                             the 1980's usually known as European Community [EC]).
24-25 Sep 1972             Norwegian referendum opposes European Economic Communities
                             membership, 53.5% vs. 46.5% for it.
 1 Feb 1985                Greenland, which joined as part of Denmark and was never recognized
                             as a separate member, withdraws.
 1 Nov 1993                European Union (EU)
28 Nov 1994                Norwegian referendum rejects European Union membership 52.2%
                             to 47.8% in favor.
 1 Jan 1999                European monetary union, conversion to the Euro begins
                             (introduced into circulation 1 Jan 2002).
 4 Mar 2001                Swiss voters in referendum reject European Union membership,
                             76.8% to 23.2%.
16 Jul 2009                Iceland applies to join the European Union, but suspended talks
                             13 Sep 2013, and withdrew its application on 12 Mar 2015.
20 Oct 2013                San Marino referendum supports European Union membership, 50.28%
                             to 49.7% (but low turnout does meet a required minimum 32% of
                             registered voters).
31 Jan 2020                United Kingdom withdraws from the EU.

国际奥林匹克委员会 International Olympic Committee (IOC)

776 BC - 394 AD            Era of the ancient Greek Olympic Games.
23 Jun 1894                International Olympic Committee founded.
1916                       Games are suspended due to World War I.
14 Aug - 30 Aug 1920       Games in Antwerp do not invite Germany, Austria, Hungary, Bulgaria,
                             and the Ottoman Empire from the competition as aggressor nations
                             in World War I, nor is Soviet Russia invited.
1940                       Games are suspended due to World War II.
1944                       Games are suspended due to World War II.
26 Jul - 14 Aug 1948       Games in London do not invite Germany and Japan as aggressor nations
                             in World War II.
22 Nov –  8 Dec 1956       Games in Melbourne are boycotted by some nations due to the Soviet
                             invasion of Hungary or UK-France-Israel invasion of Suez, Egypt.
11 Oct - 24 Oct 1960       Games in Tokyo are boycotted by Indonesia and North Korea.
 5 Sep 1972                Games in Munich are attacked by Arab militant group Black September,
                             killing 11 Israeli athletes. 
18 Jul -  1 Aug 1976       Games in Montreal are boycotted by 26 nations in protest of a tour
                             of South Africa by the New Zealand national rugby team.
19 Jul -  1 Aug 1980       Games in Moscow are boycotted by the U.S. and 62 countries for
                             the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
28 Jul - 12 Aug 1984       Games in Los Angeles are boycotted by the Soviet Union and 13
                             other countries.
17 Sep -  2 Oct 1988       Games in Seoul are boycotted by Cuba, Ethiopia, and North Korea. 
27 Jul 1996                Games in Atlanta are bombed by serial bomber Eric Rudolph, killing 2.
24 Jul -  9 Aug 2020       Games in Tokyo are postponed to 23 Jul-8 Aug 2021 due to the
                             global Covid-19 flu pandemic. 

国际卫星空间通信组织 International Organization of Space Communications (Intersputnik)

联合国第一期紧急部队1956–1967 First United Nations Emergency Force (UNEF I)

7 Nov 1956

the first emergency special session of the General Assembly passed resolution 1001 (ES-1) approving the guiding principles for the Emergency Forces to handle the Suez Crisis

14 Nov 1956

the Government of Egypt gave its consent to the arrival of UNEF in Egypt and the first transport of troops took place on the next day.

16 May 1967

Egypt requested UNEF withdrawal, and this ultimately triggered Six Day War.

17 Jun 1967

Last UN soldier left Egypt.

联合国刚果行动1960-1964 United Nations Operation in the Congo (ONUC)

The Republic of Congo became independent.

10 Jul 1960

Belgium sent troops to the Congo to protest its nationals, without permit from Congo government.

12 Jul 1960

the Congolese Government asked for United Nations military assistance

14 Jul 1960

UN Security Council Resolution 143

15 Jul 1960

Frist UN troop arrived Congo.

21 Feb 1961

UN Security Council Resolution 161 to further strengthen the forces

30 Jun 1964

UN Forces completed withdrawal.

1 Oct 1962

the administration of West New Guinea transferred to UNTEA.

1 May 1963

the administration of West New Guinea transferred to Indonesia representative Tjondronegoro.
